<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Sino-SovietBarter     11-30 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Sino-Soviet Barter,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese to Barter Consumer Goods for Soviet Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A southern China company will barter $94 million
worth of clothes, electrical goods and daily necessities for six
medium-range Soviet passenger jets, an official newspaper said
today.
   The China Daily said the Land Economic Group, a collectively
owned company based in the special economic zone of Hainan Island,
would soon sign the agreement with the Soviet Aviation Import and
Export Corp.
   It quoted the Chinese company's president as saying the three
Tupolev-154 and three Yak-42 planes would be sold to local airlines
in Jiangsu, Fujian and Sichuan provinces.
   The report said there was real potential for such deals since
both countries are short of hard currency. China would be able to
supply consumer goods _ piling up due to a domestic economic
slowdown _ to a Soviet Union plagued by chronic shortages of such
products.
</TEXT>
