<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USDA-Watchdog     11-30 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USDA-Watchdog,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Farmers Getting Around Subsidy Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's watchdog agency
says some large farming operations are successfully using highly
complex methods to get around federal limits on crop subsidies.
   Despite recent reforms ordered by Congress, these farming
operations have been able to dodge a $50,000 limit on federal crop
subsidies and probably will continue collecting the fat subsidies
again this year.
   The department's Office of Inspector General said 1987
legislation failed to effectively limit the use of ``multiple legal
entities'' to avoid the payment curbs. Other loopholes were also
cited.
   A new audit report released to The Associated Press on Wednesday
included an example of how the curbs are circumvented:
   One operation reviewed by auditors in Tunica, Miss., created 51
irrevocable trusts in 1989 so as not to have payments reduced by
further restrictions taking effect this year.
   The remodeled operation involved three joint ventures controlled
by two intermingled families, which had included 43 ``persons'' in
1988.
   Auditors said the 43 ``persons'' consisted of six individuals
and 37 corporations. Owners of the 37 corporations consisted of 11
individuals and one corporation.
   ``Seven of the individual owners were the immediate members of
the two families (a father and two daughters, and a father, two
sons and a daughter) that controlled the operation,'' the report
said.
   If the complex arrangement had remained as it was in 1988, it
would have collected no more than $700,000 in payments in 1989. But
with reorganization, the operation is expected to collect as much
as $1,431,576 in subsidies this year.
   ``One of the family members of this organization told us that
the main purpose of the reorganization was to maintain the maximum
program benefits,'' the report said. ``He said it became a
challenge to see if he could get a trust established for all of the
operation's full-time employees. He called it a profit-sharing
plan.''
   Although the reorganization was allowed by current regulations,
auditors said the trusts are believed to be ``flow-through
entities'' to avoid new regulations last year limiting a person's
membership in more than three entities.
   ``We conclude this because about $1.3 billion per year will be
routed back to the seven immediate family members through
management fees, equipment and land leases, and loans,'' the report
said.
   The heart of the crop subsidies are federal ``deficiency''
payments used to make up part of the difference between a higher
target level and a lower market price are supposed to be limited to
$50,000 per person. As an example, last month's average corn price
at the farm was $2.20 per bushel. The target price for 1989 corn is
$2.84.
   ``However, our review determined that producers have found new,
innovative ways to reorganize farming operations so that 1989
payments will not be limited significantly by the legislative
changes,'' the report said.
   The audit report followed one sent to Congress describing the
USDA inspector general's activities for the six-month period that
ended Sept. 30.
   In that review, the excessive crop subsidies were noted among a
number of abuses checked by USDA investigators and auditors. The
audit report released Wednesday dealt specifically with operations
of crop programs handled by the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service.
   The auditors checked five state offices of the agency and 14
county offices. In the counties, 822 of 7,424 farm operating plans
were selected for preliminary review. Finally, 52 farms were chosen
for in-depth analysis. No individual names were released.
   States and counties selected for in-depth review included:
   Arkansas: Jefferson, Crittenden and Phillips counties;
California: Butte and Kern; Louisiana: Morehouse, Natchitoches and
Tensas; Mississippi: De Soto, Noxubee and Tunica; and Texas:
Jackson, Jefferson and Lubbock.
   The review of 52 farming operations identified 12 that
reorganized so that all entities _ which can be individuals,
corporation, association, trust or other legal entities _ could
continue receiving payments as ``persons'' under the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
