<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Medicare     11-30 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Needs More Muscle in Substandard Medicare Care: Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House committee say the
government needs more disciplinary muscle against doctors and
hospitals that provide substandard care for Medicare patients.
   The recommendation was in a report Wednesday by the House
Government Operations Committee that also criticized the Department
of Health and Human Services for a four-year delay in writing
regulations to implement a law that gives the agency more power to
punish health-care providers.
   The law, enacted in 1985, allows HHS to deny payment to
hospitals and physicians in cases where substandard care is
provided.
   The department is working on the regulations, said Dennis
Siebert, a spokesman for the Health Care Financing Administration.
That agency handles Medicare, the government health care program
for 33 million elderly, blind and disabled Americans.
   ``They're fairly controversial and complex regulations,'' he
said. ``We've spent a lot of time consulting with medical care
industry.''
   Physicians may be terminated from participating in Medicare or
fined up to the amount of the care provided, but only in cases
where there has been a clear pattern of incompetence by physicians
who were ``unwilling or unable'' to improve their treatment.
   The report said the standard that must be met is too stringent
because it allows physicians to escape punishment by agreeing to
take an educational course to indicate their willingness to
improve. It also said the monetary penalty is too low.
   HHS Inspector General Richard Kusserow has recommended that
Congress strengthen the standard and raise the fine to $10,000 per
case.
   The report, based on a three-year investigation by the panel's
Human Resources and Intergovernmental Relations Subcommittee,
estimated that more than 800,000 errors are made each year by
doctors and hospitals caring for Medicare patients.
   The most common error was not having adequate discharge plans
for post-hospital care, the report said. That was the case for
about 3 percent of the Medicare admissions selected randomly and
reviewed by peer review organizations in 1989, the report said.
   Extrapolating that to the 11 million annual Medicare admissions
amounts to 330,000 failures.
   ``The large number of beneficiaries who may be at risk of
inadequate hospital-discharge planning is of special concern to the
committee due to fears that the PPS system (Medicare's system for
paying hospitals) ... is resulting in patients being discharged
faster and less stable,'' the report said.
   Eight Republicans on the 39-member committee cautioned in an
accompanying document that the error estimate was derived by
extrapolating from reviews, called generic screens, that are
designed to detect potential problems.
   An error can result from merely failing to sign a form in the
proper place, they said.
   ``If an exhaustive look were taken at all generic screen
failures, we are convinced the number of quality problems would be
far below the committee report's projections,'' they said.
   Under the PPS system, or prospective payment system created in
1983 as a Medicare cost-saving measure, hospitals are paid a flat
fee for each treatment they provide. The fee assumes a certain
length of hospital stay and medical services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0014 </DOCNO>
