<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Budget     11-30 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Budget,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Estimates $1.7 Billion Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon estimates it will be forced to
slash about $1.7 billion from its planned 1990 spending because of
the effect of the Gramm-Rudman budget reduction law.
   Pentagon spokesman Jim Turner said Wednesday it wasn't
immediately clear what the exact impact of the cuts would be, or
how they would affect manpower decisions.
   Turner called the figure a ``preliminary estimate'' pending
formal notification from the Office of Management and Budget.
   ``We're still trying to figure out how it's all going to fall,''
Turner said.
   Had the terms of the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law been
fully enforced over a year, defense programs would have been pared
by $8 billion, or half the $16 billion spending reductions the law
would have automatically imposed on most federal programs.
   President Bush said repeatedly in recent weeks that he preferred
retaining the across-the-board cuts for a full year to accepting
congressional efforts to reduce the deficit, which he said
contained phony savings.
   Pentagon officials had warned of severe cutbacks in military
personnel and weapons acquisition if the Gramm-Rudman cuts had been
left in place the entire year.
   The development comes as Bush signed, with reservations, a bill
authorizing $305 billion for defense programs for the current
fiscal year, including a cut in his request for the Strategic
Defense Initiative.
   The measure cuts $1.1 billion from Bush's $4.9 billion request
for spending on the SDI program, or Star Wars, in the fiscal year
that began Oct. 1.
   Bush said in a statement that the measure would provide
sufficient funds to ``provide a national defense sufficient to meet
foreseeable threats to the national security'' in the coming year.
   The legislation represents the first cut in the SDI program in
six years.
   The bill also trimmed his request for other major strategic
programs such as the MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles and the B-2
stealth bomber.
   The legislation reduces the ceiling on the number of U.S. troops
overseas by about 15,000. Those troops were associated with
intermediate-range nuclear weapons, banned by a U.S.-Soviet treaty
signed in December 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
