<FIRST>r w PM-Riegle-LincolnS&amp;L     11-30 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riegle-Lincoln S&amp;L,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Testimony Shows Senators Didn't Influence Regulators, Riegle Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Donald Riegle, voicing frustration with
the controversy over the nation's biggest savings and loan failure,
says news reports downplay evidence that he and four other senators
did nothing improper.
   ``Very sensationalized stories have run, putting such a sinister
colorization on this thing,'' Riegle, D-Mich., said Wednesday. ``I
resent it. I think it's unfair.''
   He said little attention was given to sworn testimony by federal
regulators that the senators did not influence the regulators'
actions toward Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association. Such testimony
``basically blows away the story,'' he said.
   Riegle, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, has said
little publicly about his role in the battle between federal
regulators and Lincoln, which the government seized in April.
Regulators estimate the thrift's failure will cost the taxpayers $2
billion, making it the costliest S&amp;L collapse in the nation's
history.
   The Senate Ethics Committee has hired an independent counsel to
examine allegations that five senators improperly intervened with
regulators on Lincoln's behalf. The senators are Riegle; Alan
Cranston, D-Calif; John McCain, R-Ariz.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; and
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.
   All the senators except Riegle attended an April 2, 1987,
meeting with Edwin J. Gray, then chairman of the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board. Gray says the senators improperly pressured him to drop
a regulation that would have curtailed risky savings and loan
investments.
   Riegle joined the other senators at an April 9, 1987, meeting
with California regulators who were investigating Lincoln.
   All five received large campaign donations from former Lincoln
owner Charles H. Keating Jr. Riegle returned the $78,250 he
received from Keating and associates.
   In an interview, Riegle voiced frustration over allegations that
Keating bought the senators' influence. He said Gray and other
regulators who testified before the House Banking Committee
repeatedly said the senators did not influence them.
   ``They were absolutely clear-cut on that issue and they said it
over and over again,'' he said.
   Some of the senators have described their involvement as a
normal constituent service. Riegle, however, said he did not
consider his attendance at the April 9 meeting a constituent
service _ even though he had visited Keating properties in Arizona
the previous year and Keating had purchased and renovated the
Pontchartrain Hotel in Detroit.
   ``I went as a member of the banking committee,'' he said. ``The
responsibility for handling their situation was in the hands of
others who had them as a direct constituent.''
   He said he was confident the ethics committee would find that
``all my actions were entirely proper'' and that case would do him
no long-term political damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USX-Icahn     11-30 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USX-Icahn,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn Seeks Permission to Acquire 25 Percent of USX Corp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Carl C. Icahn is making another play
for USX Corp., the giant oil, gas and steel concern.
   Icahn, who announced plans to acquire sizable stakes in
Pittsburgh-based USX twice before, disclosed Wednesday that he is
requesting federal approval to acquire at least 25 percent of the
corporation.
   Icahn, known for his past corporate takeover attempts, owns
Trans World Airlines Inc.
   USX finished down 12{ cents at $33.62{ in New York Stock
Exchange trading Wednesday. Icahn's disclosure came after the
markets closed.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Icahn
revealed that he was seeking permission from the Federal Trade
Commission to increase his stake in USX. FTC antitrust clearance
for such an acquisition is required under the Hart-Scott-Rodino
Antitrust Improvements Act.
   USX spokesman William Kessler said the company was aware of
Icahn's filing but had no comment. Icahn, Kessler said, made
similar requests in late 1987 and late 1988 but never boosted his
stake to the amount requested with the allotted year.
   ``This is the third time he's filed,'' Kessler said. ``This is a
renewable thing.''
   According to the SEC filing, made public just after 5 p.m.
Wednesday, Icahn owned nearly 34 million, or 13.26 percent, of
USX's outstanding shares of common stock.
   The SEC document noted that in November 1988, Icahn made a
Hart-Scott-Rodino filing indicating his intention to acquire more
than 15 percent of USX's voting securities ``and, depending upon
market conditions, more than 25 percent'' of its voting securities.
   But because his group did not acquire in excess of 15 percent
within a year, a new filing is required to permit acquisition above
15 percent, said the filing.
   In the latest SEC filing, Icahn said he was doing so under
Hart-Scott-Rodino ``indicating that the registrants have a good
faith intention'' to acquire more than 15 percent and up to 25
percent of USX's voting securities.
   The filing said the acquisition was dependent on market
conditions and redemption or invalidation of a ``poison pill'
shareholder rights plan adopted by USX on Oct. 10 in an attempt to
ward off a hostile takeover.
   The USX plan would take effect once a person or group acquired
at least 15 percent of the company's common stock.
   Under the plan, shareholders would be issued one stock right for
each common share they already hold. The USX board could give
shareholders the option of exchanging the rights for common stock,
at the ratio of one share of common stock for each right, thus
increasing the number of shares a raider would have to acquire.
   USX has said the plan was designed to prevent someone from
gaining control of the company without offering a fair price to all
stockholders.
   In October, Icahn said his group was considering making
proposals for ``business combinations'' with USX.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
