<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Mulroney     11-30 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Mulroney,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mulroney Says Gorbachev Deserves Help from the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, fresh
from Moscow, says Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev isn't
looking for miracles from Malta, but deserves help from the West
such as observer status at world trade talks.
   President Bush and Mulroney had a private dinner at the White
House Wednesday night in the last of Bush's pre-summit
consultations with leaders of the Western alliance before he leaves
today for Malta and this weekend's shipboard talks with Gorbachev.
   Mulroney, who returned Sunday from his own talks with Gorbachev,
spent nearly three hours at the White House before flying back to
Ottawa. Bush thanked him profusely for coming.
   ``I can't tell you how much I appreciate your advice and your
observations,'' Bush said.
   Then, in what the president acknowledged was ``a little
unorthodox'' fashion, Bush left his guest on the driveway to hold
forth for Canadian and American reporters.
   Mulroney defended Bush against charges that he has been too
timid in responding to the fast-moving tide of democratic and
economic changes sweeping the East Bloc nations.
   ``The administration has a responsibility to act with
prudence,'' he said. ``President Bush is president of the United
States and leader of the Western alliance, and it is important that
he act not in haste, but that he act effectively.
   ``I believe that his intensive preparations and his very
constructive attitude, I believe that this is going to bring about
good results.''
   Mulroney said he recommended that the Soviet Union be granted
observer status at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks
_ the discussions where the world's major industrialized nations
lay the ground rules for international trade _ and that Gorbachev
get a personal briefing after each economic summit of the seven
major nations of the West.
   That briefing, he said, should be conducted by the chairman and
host of the G-7 summit, which happens to be Bush for the 1990
meeting to be held next spring or summer in Texas.
   ``What did President Bush think of it? I think he kind of liked
it,'' said Mulroney.
   ``My belief is that President Gorbachev looks upon the Malta
summit not with a view to any achieving any miracles, but with a
view to building a sustained and solid relationship with President
Bush that will give rise to major accomplishments down the road,''
Mulroney said.
   Gorbachev, Mulroney said, is ``in for the long haul himself. I
think he's got an ambitious, progressive agenda for the future.
   ``Some of his suggestions are worthy of thoughtful and generous
response, and on the basis of that, there are some gestures that
can be taken,'' he said.
   There also ``might be a series of steps to bring (the Soviets)
more closely into the INF and World Bank ambit,'' the Canadian
leader suggested.
   The meeting was the fourth one-on-one session this year between
the two North American leaders.
   Also attending the private dinner were: Secretary of State James
A. Baker III; White House Chief of Staff John H. Sununu; Brent
Scowcroft, the national security adviser; Robert M. Gates, deputy
national security adviser; and Edward N. Ney, the U.S. ambassador
to Canada.
   Mulroney was accompanied by Canadian Secretary of State for
External Affairs Joseph Clark; Stanley H. Hartt, the prime
minister's chief of staff; and Derek Burney, the Canadian
ambassador to Washington.
   Bush conferred with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at
Camp David, Md., last Friday, and has spoken with other NATO and
Western alliance leaders by telephone in advance of the
Mediterranean summit. He has promised not to spring any surprises
on the allies.
   Asked if Bush had assured him of no surprises such as former
President Reagan's discussing abandoning nuclear arms with
Gorbachev at Reykavik, Iceland, in 1987, Mulroney said, ``Oh, you
can be certain of that.''
</TEXT>
