<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Postage Stamps and Envelopes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service, already testing a
self-adhesive stamp, is about to try marketing a plastic stamp and
a hologram.
   The self-adhesive 25-cent stamps, showing an eagle and selling
for slightly more than face value, are being tested in 15 cities.
Early sales have been reported good.
   The plastic stamp, also self-adhesive, was unveiled this week at
World Stamp Expo here and will be test-marketed in Seattle. It was
designed to be sold in bank automatic cash machines, and is made of
plastic to make it easier for the machines to dispense.
   A 25-cent stamp, the plastic model features a stylized American
flag, with a dozen stamps sold together on a backing sheet the size
of a dollar bill. Testing will begin early next year.
   The hologram, a specialized design in which the image changes
color when viewed from different angles, goes on sale Sunday.
   It is on a stamped envelopes and features a picture of the
planned space station. The stamped envelope will cost 30 cents,
including the 25 cents postage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Machinists Leaders Vow Continued Strike</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Machinist union leaders are vowing to continue
their strike against Eastern Airlines.
   Machinists President George Kourpias said Wednesday that the
union would try to pressure Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent
company, and the bankruptcy court overseeing the cash-strapped
carrier into a settlement.
   The union also plans to push Eastern to make overdue payments to
its pension plan, which is owed as much as $1 billion, and take
legal action against Eastern and Texas Air if the payments are not
made.
   Eastern is strapped for cash and court actions involving the
underfunded pension plan could affect Eastern's attempt to emerge
soon from bankruptcy.
   Kourpias said the union would lobby Congress to win enough
support to override President Bush's veto of legislation creating a
congressional panel to recommend a solution.
   Eastern pilots and flight attendants cited the veto last week in
deciding to end sympathy strikes in support of the machinists, who
walked off the job March 4 after refusing to grant more than $150
million in work-rule and other concessions.
   The union represents more than 3,000 Eastern employees who
worked as mechanics and baggage handlers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bentsen Says Panel Will Ponder Savings, Investment Incentives</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen says his Senate Finance
Committee will consider a wide array of proposals next year to
encourage saving and investment, including a cut in capital gains
taxes.
   Expanded Individual Retirement Accounts also will be considered
as Congress looks for ways to increase productivity and the
nation's ability to compete with foreign producers, the Texas
Democrat said Wednesday in remarks prepared for a meeting of the
Tax Foundation in New York.
   With Bentsen and Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell,
D-Maine, leading the way, Congress this year defeated President
Bush's call for a reduction in taxes on capital gains, profits from
the sale of investments.
   Democratic leaders viewed the proposed reduction as a windfall
for the rich, the beginning of the undoing of the landmark 1986 tax
overhaul and a deficit-increaser that would do little for the
economy.
   They responded with a plan to liberalize tax-deductible IRAs,
but withdrew that proposal when the capital gains cut failed.
</TEXT>
