<FIRST>r w PM-Thornburgh-CivilRights 250   11-30 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Civil Rights, 250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Membership in All-Male Club Shouldn't Disqualify Dunne: Thornburgh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh says the man
whom President Bush is expected to name civil rights chief
shouldn't be disqualified simply because he's a member of an
all-male golf club.
   Thornburgh refused to discuss former New York state Sen. John R.
Dunne's expected nomination to be assistant attorney general for
civil rights, saying ``that is a matter for the White House.''
   But the attorney general dismissed suggestions Wednesday that
Dunne's membership in an all-male golf club would pose a problem.
   ``Mr. Dunne has indicated that if he is nominated by the
president he will resign. So I think he feels it's inappropriate
for the head of the civil rights division to belong to such a
club.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday that Dunne
was the top candidate for the job.
   Sources at the White House, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said they expected Bush to nominate Dunne, a personal friend of the
attorney general for 17 years.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee refused to approve Bush's first
nominee, William C. Lucas, after critics said he lacked
professional experience for the job.
   Thornburgh said membership in all-male clubs doesn't disqualify
candidates because ``we don't believe in litmus tests.''
   ``My objection is to a litmus test which says hat somebody
because of any characteristic or any part of their background ought
to be excluded,'' the attorney general told reporters.
   ``They ought to look at the whole record.''
</TEXT>
