<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Westerners     11-30 0920</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Westerners,0951</SECOND>
<HEAD>Starting Over Made Easier By Memories of What They Fled</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his spacious apartment, Werner Rhode
reflected on the price of fleeing West: more than two years'
separation from his wife and two sons, starting over in his 40s,
and an enduring sense of isolation.
   ``But I'd do exactly the same again. I don't regret not
waiting,'' said Rhode. ``We won three years.''
   The pediatrician left East Germany illegally in 1986, never
expecting the Communist government would permit freedom of travel
in his lifetime.
   ``Now I feel a tremendous pride that I did what I did. It was
like moving a mountain with a shovel,'' Rhode said.
   Rhode was among the East Germans who managed to escape before
last summer, when neighboring Hungrary opened its borders and
released a flood of East Germans to the West.
   On Nov. 9, East Germany's Communist leaders gave up, scrapped
travel restrictions and opened the Berlin Wall.
   Among the new Westerners, many are young and hopeful, but some
are disillusioned. Others, like Rhode, 44, simply are determined to
adapt, buoyed daily by the memory of their desperation to leave
East Germany.
   ``I don't think that anybody who has never lived there could
ever understand,'' Rhode said. ``I did not want my children to wind
up in their 40s in the situation we were in. It was like being a
marionette, constantly manipulated.''
   Despite the changes, including an amnesty for illegal emigrants
declared in October, Rhode has no intention of going back and has
not visited. He believes his children, now 14 and 16, have better
opportunities in the West.
   For two 23-year-old East Berlin secretaries who ducked out of a
vacationing group in Hungary and reached West Berlin via Austria in
October, life in the West consists of sharing a room in a refugee
center with three other women.
   They have never used computers and have little prospect of
finding work or housing. In January, they are due to start a
retraining course.
   ``It's disappointing,'' said one, Kirsten Senger, who left with
her best friend, Katrin Mueller. ``But if you want to succeed here,
it's possible to fight your way through. On the other side,
whatever you did, somebody always closed a door.''
   ``If we'd known what was going to happen, I suppose we'd have
waited,'' Miss Mueller. ``But we'd have been the first through the
wall on Nov. 9.''
   Miss Mueller went home to visit East Berlin soon after the wall
opened, and Miss Senger also plans a visit soon.
   ``It was good to see my mother, because leaving her without
telling her I was going was the saddest thing I've ever known,''
said Miss Mueller.
   Even with the hardships of adapting to their new lives, neither
wants to give up.
   ``There was no hope'' in the East, and authorities made promises
they did not keep, said Miss Mueller.
   After repeated applications, Rhode, who worked at a hospital in
Frankfurt an der Oder along the border with Poland, got a five-day
exit visa in 1986 to visit relatives in West Berlin, 50 miles away.
   His wife, Sabine, a neurologist, and their sons were not allowed
to accompany him.
   The couple agreed that Rhode would not return. Knowing their
telephone would be tapped and mail opened, Mrs. Rhode feigned
amazement when her husband pretended to break the news in a
telephone call.
   Secret police raided her apartment. She was fined 20,000 East
German marks _ more than 10 times Rhode's annual salary. Officials
decided on the sum as representing half the state-assessed value of
their property.
   Repeatedly, Mrs. Rhode was refused permission to leave.
   ``They were granting some applications, but highly skilled
people had no chance,'' said Rhode. ``There were times when I
thought it was hopeless. I promised her if things got too bad, I'd
go back even if it meant a year in jail.''
   Suddenly, on Dec. 28, 1988, Mrs. Rhode was told she could go
that day. ``I just picked up the children, two suitcases and
went,'' she said.
   In East Germany, the Rhodes had a relatively good living
standard _ an apartment at a nominal rent, a car and more money
than there were goods to buy.
   Their skills were in desperately short supply, while West
Germany has a surplus of doctors. Some 1,200 doctors are out of
work in West Berlin alone, with numbers being swelled by emigres
from the east.
   Rhode, a senior consultant in East Germany, got a job as an
assistant consultant at West Berlin's Neukoelln Hospital. It pays
5,500 West German marks, nearly $3,000 a month after taxes.
   He lived in a small apartment in the nurses' quarters, saving
for the arrival of his family. They now live in their own
apartment, which rents for $973 a month.
   Mrs. Rhode considers herself lucky to have found a job _ she
works assessing accident victims' disabilities for an insurance
group _ and both speak with distaste of what they see as a
mercenary attitude of many of their West German colleagues.
   Mrs. Rhode said some had suggested she should feel guilty about
leaving patients behind in East Germany.
   ``They have no place to talk to me about feeling guilty,'' she
said. ``Here we see them cheating patients by giving them
unnecessary treatment.''
   Her husband cited instances when, he said, doctors ``see a
patient four or five times when one or two appointments would do.'
</TEXT>
