<FIRST>r a PM-Hepatitis Bjt   11-30 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hepatitis, Bjt,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interferon First Treatment for Hepatitis C</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Injections of the natural disease-fighting protein
interferon give doctors their first effective weapon against
hepatitis C, a virus that infects at least 150,000 Americans
annually, according to a report today.
   ``In my opinion, this is a major clinical advance,'' said Dr.
Gary L. Davis of the University of Florida.
   The work appears to represent another milestone in a year of
advances against this elusive virus. Until recently, doctors were
sure of only two hepatitis viruses, type A and type B. Since many
people got hepatitis without exposure to these viruses, their
disease was simply labeled non-A, non-B.
   In April, researchers from Chiron Corp. in Emeryville, Calif.,
reported the discovery of a new hepatitis virus, which they called
hepatitis C. They said it is the principal culprit in non-A, non-B
hepatitis. They also described a new test that will reveal whether
blood is tainted with the virus.
   Hepatitis C is the most common serious infection that is passed
through blood. Perhaps 5 percent of all Americans who get routine
transfusions become infected, although estimates vary widely.
However, this hazard should largely disappear soon when the new
screening test for the virus becomes available, perhaps next year.
   Most cases of hepatitis C are mild. About half those infected
become long-term carriers, and 10 percent suffer cirrhosis of the
liver.
   The latest research, involving 207 people, shows that therapy
with alpha interferon, a human protein produced through genetic
engineering, can temporarily shut down the virus' attack. The
treatment stopped the destruction of liver cells in about half of
those with chronic disease. However, in more than half of those who
are helped, the disease returned when treatment ended.
   Researchers hope that giving interferon for longer period or in
higher doses will hold the virus in check or wipe it out.
   ``This is a very common disease,'' said Davis. ``There has been
nothing available for these people in the past. While this controls
the disease rather than cures it, it is the first therapeutic
intervention that has been offered these people.''
   ``It looks promising that anti-viral treatment will be useful in
this disease,'' added Dr. Jay H. Hoofnagle of the National
Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases.
   Davis and Hoofnagle were co-authors of separate studies that
reached similar conclusions about interferon's effectiveness. Both
were published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
   Hepatitis B is spread mainly through blood and sexual contact
and is a major underlying cause of cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Blood banks also test donations for hepatitis A, which usually
spreads through contaminated food and water. While it can cause
serious illness, people do not get lingering infections with
hepatitis A.
   ``Hepatitis C virus is a vastly more common problem than HIV
(the AIDS virus) and considerably more common than hepatitis B, for
which we have been testing for 20 years. It's the most common
serious virus infection'' passed through transfusions, said Dr.
Lewellys F. Barker, head of blood services at the American Red
Cross in Washington.
   In another report in the journal, Chiron scientists teamed with
researchers from the Department of Transfusion Medicine at the
National Institutes of Health to strengthen the case that hepatitis
C is the major, and possibly the only, cause of non-A, non-B
hepatitis.
   They tested 15 people who got non-A, non-B hepatitis through
transfusions and found that all were infected with hepatitis C.
Donors were also infected with this virus.
   Just how many Americans get hepatitis C each year is unclear.
Davis estimates that about 150,000 of the 3 million Americans who
get transfusions annually become infected. However, the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control uses a far lower estimate.
   In an editorial in the journal, the CDC's Dr. Miriam J. Alter
estimated that a total of 150,000 Americans get hepatitis C each
year from all causes. Among these are 7,500 to 15,000 who catch it
through transfusions.
   The CDC estimates that 40 percent get the infection through drug
abuse. Other sources include on-the-job exposure to blood, sexual
intercourse and household contact with infected people. However, in
about 40 percent of cases there is no clear explanation of how the
infection occurs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-RomaniaAlone Bjt   11-30 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania Alone, Bjt,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Increasingly Alone On Orthodox Communist Path</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicolae Ceausescu's ringing rejection
of reform is leaving him increasingly isolated as Warsaw Pact
allies move toward democracy.
   The supreme leader of Romania renounced the reforms gripping the
six other Warsaw Pact nations at his Communist Party's 14th
congress last week.
   Instead, he proclaimed a strengthened role for the party, which
already runs the most tightly controlled country in the Soviet bloc.
   ``The party cannot give up its responsibility,'' he declared.
``It cannot surender its historical mission to another force.''
   Exppressing contempt for the political liberalization reshaping
Eastern Europe, Ceausescu _ whose 24 years in power make him the
most senior Soviet bloc leader _ suggested that reform-minded
Communist leaders elsewhere had betrayed their people.
   The displays of orchestrated support from congress delegates did
not gloss over the rapidly widening political gap between
Ceausescu's Romania and the Soviet Union, Poland, Hungary, East
Germany, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
   He has often been at odds with the Kremlin, rejecting the Soviet
lead in the 1970s at a time whent the rest of the Warsaw Pact was
in lock-step with Moscow.
   Now, he is resolute in rejecting reform.
   And in a new challenge, Ceausescu suggested in his congress
speech that the Soviet Union give up control of territory gained
through a pre-World War II pact with Nazi Germany that resulted in
Romania ceding Bessarabia, now Soviet Moldavia, to its powerful
neighbor.
   Distate for Romania was evident in the fact that several
countries, including Italy and Warsaw Pact ally Hungary, boycotted
the congress _ a move which would have been an unheard of affront
just five years ago.
   The growing isolation of Ceausescu's Romania also was reflected
in the near-complete absence of the Western camp from the congress.
   Chiefs of Western diplomatic missions had attended past
Communist Party congresses as a show of courtesy. But the 14th
congress was boycotted by the 12-member European Economic
Community, all 16 NATO nations save Turkey, most Latin American
democracies, and almost all of Europe's neutral counries.
   The issue was Romania's poor human rights record, which was
``ignored back in the 1970s, when Ceausescu was tweaking the
Russian bear's tail,'' said a diplomat, who invoked the customary
rules of anonymity.
   The Romanian leader's independent foreign policy decisions, such
as refusing to join other Warsaw Pact nations in invading
Czechoslovakia in 1968, or defying a Soviet bloc boycott of the
1984 Los Angeles Summer Olympics, was met the with applause from
the United States and its allies.
   The cheers have turned to jeers, however.
   ``They're being very consistent, it's the rest of the world
that's changing,'' Canadian Ambassador Sol Gray said of Romania in
the brightening rights picture in the rest of the Soviet bloc.
   Romania is under growing attack for a rights record marred by
severe travel restrictions, no freedom of expression and strict
limitation on the practice of religion.
   Fear of opposing Ceausescu even appears to extend into the
highest party echelons, with senior officials seemingly restricted
to carrying out the leader's decrees.
   Explaining the American decision to stay away from the congress,
the U.S. Embassy said it would be ``inconsistent with the depth of
United States concern over the human rights situation in Romania,
for which the Romanian Communist Party bears responsibility.''
   Romanian officials deny that Ceausescu's refusal to embrace
change is leading to international isolation and point to what they
say are vibrant ties with the developing world.
   Ceausescu seems to turn to increasingly to developing countries,
particularly those with a Communist system similarly opposed to
reform.
   Reporting on a meeting between Ceausescu and Chinese chief
delegate Qiao Shi, the Romanian Communist Party daily Scinteia said
both sides expressed pleasure over the ``upward movement '' and
``constant gowth'' of ties.
   Similar language was used to describe Ceausescu's meetings with
the head of the North Korean and Cuban delegations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Jahn, now based in Vienna, has reported
on Eastern Europe for The AP since 1982.
</TEXT>
