<FIRST>r w PM-BRF--SewerAccident     11-30 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Sewer Accident,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worked Killed When Swept Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A river of raw sewage swept away a city worker
when a barrier used to plug a sewer pipe burst, and officials said
the man's body was found more than half a mile away.
   The body of the Public Works Department employee was found in a
giant filtering device in a pumping station. Police withheld the
name of the victim pending notification of his family.
   The incident occurred about 3 p.m. beneath the basement of the
Kennedy Center, where city employees were repairing a 10-foot city
sewer line, said Fire Department Battalion Chief Joseph L. O'Neill.
   The worker was standing on a scaffold inside the line when the
accident occurred, he said.
   To stop the flow of sewage while workers fix such pipes, large
balloons are inflated upstream from the work site, O'Neill said.
The balloon that workers were using burst, releasing a river of raw
sewage that had been backed up for as long as four hours, he said.
   The cause of the accident was not known.
</TEXT>
