<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bugged     11-30 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bugged,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Waiter, There's a Sawtoothed Grain Beetle in My Rice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rice was bugged, and we're not talking
wiretaps.
   The sesame seeds had a problem, too. So did the apricots, the
bean curd and the macaroni. In all, City Council President Andrew
Stein said Wednesday, 15 of 17 imported foods his staff bought in
the city and had tested at a private laboratory contained bugs or
bug parts.
   At a City Hall news conference, Stein accused the federal Food
and Drug Administration of failing to enforce its food
contamination standards. He also said the standards themselves are
too low.
   Most of the foods he had tested _ including 2 ounces of Haitian
milled corn with 26 insect fragments in it _ were within allowable
federal standards. But six were so badly tainted they violated the
limits, Stein said.
   Among them, he said, were a 5-pound bag of Indian rice
containing one live bug _ a red flour beetle _ and 11 whole dead
ones, including sawtoothed grain beetles and a rice weevil. There
was a dead moth in the Chinese sesame seeds, a rat or mouse hair in
the Chinese bean curd preserves and 481 insect fragments in the
Greek macaroni.
   ``Had they been properly inspected, they would have been barred
from sale in this country,'' Stein said. He blamed federal budget
cuts under the Reagan administration that reduced the number of FDA
inspectors while food imports tripled.
   The FDA replied that it spends most of its time looking for food
that contains microbiological contamination that could make people
sick. Bugs, while unappetizing, generally do not pose a direct
health threat, said Herman Janiger, an FDA consumer affairs officer
in Brooklyn.
   ``We do screen for filth in food, but it's possible that some
can get by us,'' Janiger said.
</TEXT>
