<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Playboy     11-30 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Playboy,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Risque Business? Playboy Hops Over Remnants of Iron Curtain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Playboy of the Western world
arrived in the the East bloc today, unveiling American women to a
nation more concerned with shedding Communism.
   A Hungarian version of the men's magazine hit the stands today.
Playboy debuted the edition Wednesday at a news conference that was
the best attended since President Bush visited Hungary in July.
   The star attraction was December's Playmate of the Month,
American Pia Reyes, who told reporters she hoped she is
``recognized with clothes on.''
   Hungary apparently was chosen for the first East Bloc edition
because of its liberal cultural and political climate. This year,
the Communist Party disbanded and reform-minded leaders have
promised free elections by June.
   In the maiden Hungarian edition, Playboy founder Hugh Hefner
wrote, ``The Hungarian people can now enjoy the same democratic
freedom which Playboy has always championed.''
   Playboy, however, isn't likely to shock Hungarians the way it
did Americans in the 1950s. The past year has seen a rash of
soft-core pornography appearing at Budapest kiosks.
   There are no pornography statutes on the books in Hungary, but
customs officials did routinely confiscate such magazines until
1983.
   The Hungarian edition of Playboy will have an initial printing
of 95,000 copies and will sell for 197 forints, or about $3, a
steep price in a country where the average monthly salary is about
6,000 forints, or $100.
   The Hungarian Playboy, a joint venture between Playboy
Enterprises Inc. of Chicago and Hungarian entrepreneurs, will carry
locally generated material as well as photo spreads and features
from the American editions.
   Hungarian editor Dezsoe Futasz said there were no plans yet to
feature a Hungarian Playmate of the Month because of the higher
standards of photography available from the U.S. edition.
   The Hungarian Playboy marks the 13th national edition and the
11th language in which the magazine is published, said Playboy
spokesman William Stocken.
   During the news conference, a reporter from the Soviet news
agency Tass asked about a possible Soviet edition, to which Stocken
replied that ``we are open to a business venture with the
U.S.S.R..''
   Miss December had a chance to clear up an error in the text
accompanying her Hungarian debut: She likes leather and lingerie,
not _ as the Hungarian text has it _ leather lingerie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
