<FIRST>r a PM-Lites SUB a0450 11-30 0118</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites, SUB, a0450,0121</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of final item to delete extraneous word `said'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ah, the fast-paced modern age.
   Traffic in central London in the 1980s moves only 3 mph faster
than in 1912 when most of it was horse-drawn, according to the
Department of Transport.
   The department reported Wednesday that average speeds in 1986
were 10 mph, almost identical to those in 1936. Average speeds were
7 mph in 1912.
   The highest average speeds were recorded just after World War
II, when traffic moved at around 11.5 mph in 1947.
   Traffic congestion has had one positive effect, the report said.
   London's traffic tripled since 1912, whereas nationally it
multiplied eight times.
</TEXT>
