<FIRST>r a PM-Poll-Method     11-30 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Method,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews Nov. 17-25 with 1,117 adults in the
continental United States.
   Phone numbers were selected randomly and interviews were
conducted with the adult who had the most recent birthday, a random
phenomenon.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that 19 of
20 times its findings should be within 3 points of the result if
every adult American were asked the same questions. The error
margin is larger for subgroups.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions in this
poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
George Bush? Favorable: 70 percent. Unfavorable: 17 percent. Don't
know or no answer: 14 percent.
   2. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev? Favorable: 68 percent.
Unfavorable: 16 percent. Don't know or no answer: 16 percent.
   3. Do you approve or disapprove of the way George Bush is
handling relations with the Soviet Union? Approve: 74. Disapprove:
14. DK-NA: 13.
   4. Are your feelings toward the Soviet Union generally
favorable, generally unfavorable or neutral? Favorable: 24.
Unfavorable: 18. Neutral: 54. DK-NA: 4.
   5. Who do you think is doing more to reduce East-West tensions
right now _ George Bush or Mikhail Gorbachev? Bush: 29. Gorbachev:
41. DK-NA: 30.
   6a. Do you believe Mikhail Gorbachev wants to bring about
meaningful reform in the Soviet Union, or not? Yes: 77. No: 12.
DK-NA: 12.
   b. (if yes) Do you think he will succeed, or not? Yes: 60. No:
15. DK-NA: 25.
   7. Do you think George Bush is doing enough to encourage reform
in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe, or is he being too
cautious? Enough: 46. Cautious: 40. DK-NA: 14.
   8. To encourage reform, do you think the United States should
have free trade with the Soviet Union, on the same terms the U.S.
gives its main trading partners? Yes: 57. No: 28. DK-NA: 15.
   9. To encourage reform, do you think the United States should
provide foreign aid to the Soviet Union? Yes: 21. No: 71. DK-NA: 8.
   10a. Because of the reforms that have taken place in Eastern
Europe, should the United States immediately begin reducing its
troops stationed in Western Europe? Yes: 25. No: 68. DK-NA: 7.
   b. (if no) If the reforms continue, should the United States
reduce its troops stationed in Western Europe? Yes: 56. No: 37.
DK-NA: 7.
   11. Do you think the United States should withdraw all its
troops from Western Europe if the Soviet Union withdraws all its
troops from Eastern Europe? Yes: 42. No: 47. DK-NA: 10.
   12. Should the United States significantly reduce its military
spending because of reduced tensions between the Soviet Union and
the United States, or not? Yes: 41. No: 52. DK-NA: 7.
   13. Do you think the Soviets can be trusted to live up to their
arms control agreements? Yes: 30. No: 53. DK-NA: 18.
   14. Do you think the Soviet Union is trying to dominate the
world, or don't you think so? Yes: 35. No: 57. DK-NA: 8.
</TEXT>
