<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-30 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down In Tokyo, Stocks At Another New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined moderately against the Japanese
yen Thursday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
to a new high.
   The dollar closed at 142.90 yen, down 0.63 yen from Wednesday's
close of 143.53 yen. After opening at 143.13 yen, the currency
moved in a range of 142.75-143.18 yen in mixed trading.
   On the stock market the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which rose 36.16 points to a record high closing Wednesday,
added another 247.33 points, or 0.67 percent, to close trading at
37,268.79.
   A currency dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said that after its low
opening, the dollar remained stable because of end-of-month demand
for the American currency.
   But another dealer said that end-of-month purchases have already
been completed, and predicted that the dollar would fall during the
day to around 142.75 yen.
   Participants said there was little prospect that any Japanese or
U.S. economic data on the horizon would knock the dollar out of the
general range of 141.50 to 144.50 yen.
   The Nikkei index continued to gain on small-lot buying in a
broad front due to the yen's appreciation against the dollar and
investor expectations for higher prices, securities dealers said.
</TEXT>
