<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of his release from prison
in 1983, Texas flim-flam artist Billie Sol Estes said his wheeling
and dealing days were over.
   The problem wasn't that he was crooked, Estes confided to a
reporter, but compulsive.
   ``I'm just one drink away from being a drunk and just one deal
away from being back in prison,'' sighed the former west Texas
millionaire whose friendship with President Johnson eroded after an
historic fertilizer tank scandal in the 1960s.
   Now, at age 64, the state's most colorfully persistent con man
is back in trouble, indicted with five others and a defunct
corporation on charges of stealing trade secrets.
   He posted $10,000 bail Tuesday in Brady and was released along
with three co-defendants.
   Estes dropped out of sight, and attempts Wednesday to contact
him through friends and family were unsuccessful. In 1987, he moved
to Brady from his longtime home in Abilene.
   McCulloch County District Attorney Ron Sutton said Estes and his
associates face a Dec. 7 arraignment on felony charges of engaging
in criminal activity _ a scheme to form a company with plans that
had been stolen from another firm.
   ``The indictment sets out that he kind of came th the idea,''
Sutton said.
   ``I've always been able to make money,'' Estes bragged in an
interview in the current issue of Texas Monthly magazine. ``If I
put my mind to it, I could make a million in the next 30 days.''
   Estes went on to say:
   ``Me, I've never cared about money. I love puttials together and
watching them run. For some people, money is death. You might as
well give th a loaded .45 pistol and point it right at thei''
   This is the Billie Sol who, after promis 1983 that his fast buck
deals were a thing of past, outlined a grand scheme to corner the
wirket by growing grapes in the west Texas desert`We could, truly,
move the wine business from Fr to West Texas, and I've got some
people who woike for me to go out there and do that,'' he sa Now,
he says, if he had money he would put itJapanese stock market.
   This is the Billie who once told a reporter:
   ``You can shear mb every year, but you can only skin it once.''
   A running Texas joke is that it takes a gooindler to make
millions peddling cow manure, bureat one like Estes to amass a
fortune selling antom cow manure.
   And that's what got Estesble in 1963.
   He was convicted of federal ma fraud and conspiracy in a
multimillion-dollar involving phony financial statements and
non-exnt fertilizer tanks.
   The paper empire was propped up with federal agricultural loans,
a cus arrangement that critics later maintained coulbe traced to
Billie Sol's ties with fellow Texaon Johnson.
   Estes was a Johnson confidant anancial contributor as far back
as Johnson's U.ays.
   The extent of the relationship is debathe late president's
associates insist it was nster bonding that Estes implied.
   Estes wasom prison the first time in 1971 after serving years of
a 15-year term. After being convicted o and conspiracy to conceal
