<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India     11-30 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singh May Be Persuaded to Be Prime Minister, Colleagues Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of a centrist coalition seeking
to form India's first minority government said today they believe
their reluctant leader will yet become prime minister.
   Vishwanath Pratap Singh, head of the five-party National Front
coalition, has maintained he is not interested in replacing Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi. But his colleagues say he has no choice in
the matter.
   ``He has to bow to the wishes of the people and the party,''
said Mohan Guruswamy, an associate of Singh. ``He has no
alternative.''
   Guruswamy said another contender for the post, Chandra Shekhar,
was persuaded Wednesday night to withdraw. Guruswamy claimed no one
in the coalition would contest Singh's nomination.
   Singh, who as late as Tuesday said he would not accept office in
the new government, could not be reached for comment.
   Gandhi resigned Wednesday after his Congress Party failed to win
a majority in last week's parliamentary polls, but he was asked by
President Ramaswamy Venkataraman to continue until a new government
is formed.
   Results of 521 of the 525 seat at stake in the elections had
been announced by today, and the Congress emerged as the single
largest party with 191. Its small-party allies got another 17 seats.
   The National Front has 143 but has been promised support by the
right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party, which has 88 seats, and by a
coalition of left-wing groups, which won 51 constituencies.
   That would give the National Front and its tacit allies a total
of 282 seats _ enough to carry a vote if there are no defections.
   The rest of the Parliament seats went to small parties and
independents who have not specified whether they would support a
National Front government.
   ``Singh is not sure he will be able to handle a hung house,''
said a senior leader of the National Front, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``That's why he was so hesitant to become the prime
minister.''
   ``Singh was told he has no business to be in politics if he does
not seek office,'' said another source in the National Front,
referring to meetings held by the coalition on Wednesday night.
   The National Front's Parliament members are to meet Friday to
elect their leader, who would likely be asked by the president to
become prime minister. If the National Front leader cannot win a
vote of confidence in Parliament _ which takes a simple majority of
263 _ he will have to resign as prime minister.
   Under the Indian Constitution, the president decides who will be
asked to form a government. In past elections, one party always
emerged with a comfortable majority. In the absence of such a
majority, the president is free to choose the party he considers
the most capable of forming a government.
   The Congress Party has said it will not stake a claim to form
the government. Gandhi said he will lead the new opposition.
   Singh, a former defense and finance minister, is the best-known
leader in the National Front. But the 58-year-old politician has
said he just wants to be president of the Janata Dal, or People's
Party, the largest component of the coalition.
</TEXT>
