<FIRST>r i PM-Greenpeace-Soviet     11-30 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenpeace-Soviet,0281</SECOND>
<UNK>Greenpeace Stops Soviet Trawler Fishing In Antarctica</UNK>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greenpeace activists in
inflatable boats battled raging seas and freezing temperatures in
Antarctica today to stop a Soviet factory trawler from fishing, the
environmental group said.
   It said three inflatables were launched from the Greenpeace ship
Gondwana stationed off South Georgia in the South Atlantic, where
the group claims the Soviets are overfishing.
   The group, in a statement, said the seven activists steered the
inflatables on board the Soviet factory trawler Mikjail Verbitzkiy
after a wild ride.
   It said the Soviet ship was attempting to put out nets when
Gondwana approached and lowered the inflatable boats. The
inflatables reportedly stayed with the ship for three hours despite
10-foot swells.
   The statement said Greenpeace radioed the Soviet captain, in
both English and Russian, explaining the reasons for the
non-violent protest.
   At one point, the inflatables actually landed on the stern ramp,
blocking the trawling operation.
   ``For the last 20 years the Antarctic ecosystem has been
plundered by indiscriminate fishing, especially by the Soviet Union
in the South Georgia area, and now these stocks are commercially
extinct,'' said Greenpeace Antarctic Program Coodinator Maj de
Poorter.
   She said the whole ecological balance was at risk, as the fish
are food for penguins, seabords, seals and whales.
   Greenpeace, as part of its campaign to have Antarctica declared
a world park, is demanding a moratorium on all fishing south of the
Antarctic convergence until stocks have recovered.
   ``The great whales that once populated this area are gone, now
the fish are going,'' De Poorter said. ``Greenpeace will not simply
stand by and watch.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
