<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People-SteelWheels     11-30 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Steel Wheels,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Wheels Churning Toward Multimillion-Dollar Finish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three weeks before the finale of the Rolling
Stones' ``Steel Wheels'' concert tour, Mick Jagger and Keith
Richards are proud of the band's new-found discipline, and its
trainload of money.
   ``I've never seen the boys so serious,'' Richards said
Wednesday. ``Everyone is really conserving their energy for the
shows instead of like 10 to 15 years ago when we would have, like,
been up three or four days in a row. Things change.''
   Since opening the 60-show North American tour Aug. 31 in
Philadelphia, the 25-year-old rock band consistently has drawn
sellout crowds despite admittedly bad acoustics in stadiums such as
the Metrodome in Minneapolis. The Stones play there tonight for the
second time.
   By the time the tour grinds to a halt Dec. 20 in Atlantic City,
N.J., more than 3 million concertgoers will have oiled the ``Steel
Wheels'' machine with about $80 million.
   And that doesn't count souvenir sales, corporate sponsorship
from Budweiser and MTV, a line of Stones clothing, album proceeds,
and the multimillion-dollar payoff at the end of the tour from a
live pay-per-view television concert with Eric Clapton, Guns 'N
Roses stars Axl Rose and Izzy Stradlin and others.
   ``I'm very proud of the way it's financially run because I have
a lot to do with it,'' the 46-year-old Jagger said in an interview
before Wednesday's show. ``But I'm also very proud of the fact that
we do spend a tremendous amount of money on production.''
   The overhead includes a 300-member entourage, stadium rentals
Jagger describes as sometimes ``unreasonable,'' and two huge stage
sets loaded with pyrotechnics _ the larger of which will not fit
into many stadiums.
   Asked about the accuracy of published estimates that each of the
five band members will net $18 million, Jagger said many of the
estimates have been inflated ``twice or three times.''
   ``America is besot with money. It's always been besot by
money,'' the singer said. ``People like juggling figures around. I
certainly don't know what the end numbers will be and if I did I
certainly wouldn't tell you.''
   Richards, 45, said he's not bothered by America's obsession with
the tour's bottom line.
   ``The Stones have incredible timing. They've always had
timing,'' Richards said. ``Of course everyone has done very well
out of it. But then, why shouldn't they? They are the best.''
   The guitar player said ``Steel Wheels'' is the most demanding
Stones tour he can remember. The 2{-hour show is the band's longest
ever and four shows a week leave little room to play, Richards said.
   In addition, a more complicated sound system is requiring the
band to do a sound check before every concert. In past tours,
Richards said the band would do a single sound check at the outset
and hope for the best the rest of the way.
   Jagger credited the band's ``professionalism'' for a smooth tour.
   ``When you're doing 60 shows the challenge is after the first 20
to keep your interest up _ to keep the general standard high,''
Jagger said. ``I think we've managed to do that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
