<DOCNO> AP891130-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     11-30 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Closer Higher; Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed at a
new high for the seventh consecutive trading day today, while the
U.S. dollar declined moderately against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 247.33
points, or 0.67 percent, closing at 37,268.79.
   The index had gained 36.16 points Wednesday, climbing above
37,000 points for the first time.
   It rose today on small-lot buying on a broad front due to the
yen's appreciation against the dollar and investor expectations of
still higher stock prices, securities dealers said.
   A dealer at Nikko Securities Co. said trading company and
electronics shares were bought actively.
   ``The bullish mood is expected to continue for some time,'' said
the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1 billion shares,
down from 1.61 billion shares Wednesday.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 142.90 yen,
down 0.63 yen from Wednesday's close of 143.53 yen. After opening
at 143.13 yen, it ranged between 142.75 yen and 143.18 yen.
   A currency dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said that after its low
opening, the dollar remained stable because of month-end demand for
the American currency.
   But another dealer said end-of-month purchases already had been
completed and the dollar was likely to move lower.
   Dealers said there was little prospect that any Japanese or U.S.
economic data to be reported in the near future would knock the
dollar out of the general range of 141.50 to 144.50 yen.
</TEXT>
