<FIRST>r a PM-Episcopal-Salvador     11-30 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Episcopal-Salvador,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Worker Says Salvadorans Threatened to Slit Her Throat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American church worker says Salvadoran
authorities threatened to slit her throat after she was arrested at
an Episcopal refugee sanctuary in San Salvador last week.
   ``I was blindfolded, handcuffed, hit in the head, threatened,''
Josephine Beecher, 37, of Lopez Island, Wash., said Wednesday.
   ``They said, `Let's set the electric shock up; let's turn on the
electricity.' They ran some object _ we were blindfolded, so I
don't know what it was _ across our throats and said, `This is
what's going to happen to you.'''
   Ms. Beecher was among 19 lay workers arrested Nov. 20 when the
Salvadoran national guard raided St. John the Evangelist Church,
which was sheltering 400 refugees.
   She and five other foreigners were released within a day. But 14
to 16 Salvadorans remain in custody, according to the Rev. Ricardo
Potter, the church's partnership officer for Latin America and the
Caribbean.
   Ms. Beecher said at a news conference that she had been helping
to feed and shelter refugees brought to the church by the Red Cross
when the national guard arrived at 5:45 a.m., searched the area and
removed the lay workers.
   She was taken first to the national guard headquarters, then to
the offices of the treasury police, where the abuse occurred, she
said.
   Ms. Beecher said she was accused of being a terrorist.
   ``There's no way that I or anybody else in the churches are
doing that kind of work,'' Ms. Beecher said.
   After first refusing to sign a release form which stated she had
not been physically or psychologically mistreated, Ms. Beecher said
she was advised by a U.S. consular official named David Ramos to
agree to the clause. She did so and was released.
   She said consular officials later told her ``what I had received
was normal treatment for a prisoner of war and that they didn't see
any problem with that.''
   Episcopal Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning said he has
requested a meeting with President Bush, and will send four bishops
to El Salvador on behalf of the remaining church workers, including
the Rev. Jose Serrano, rector of St. John the Evangelist.
   A statement signed Wednesday by nine religious leaders,
including Browning, said Washington has not done enough to change
the Salvadoran government.
   ``The focus at this moment must be on the immediate cessation of
hostilities directed at the churches, including the release of all
those now being held in detention,'' the statement said.
   St. John the Evangelist was one of at least seven churches or
church schools in El Salvador raided by security forces on Nov. 19
and 20. U.S. Ambassador William Walker blamed the raids on ``overly
aggressive security forces'' and suggested President Alfredo
Cristiani was having ``management control problems'' with extremist
elements of his government.
   Two weeks ago, six Jesuit priests, including the rector and vice
rector of the country's Central American University, were slain.
Fellow Jesuits blamed the killings on government soldiers, and the
government promised to investigate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
