<FIRST>r a PM-ParkJogger     11-30 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Park Jogger,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Park Rape Victim Returns to Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jogger who was raped, beaten and left for
dead in Central Park seven months ago has gone back to work as an
investment banker, and a relative said she's ``as sharp as she ever
was.''
   The 29-year-old woman, who has undergone physical and emotional
rehabilitation since the April 19 attack, returned full time Monday
to her job at Salomon Brothers Inc., a court source said, speaking
on condition of anonymity. She was assigned to advising large
corporations on investments.
   ``I'm sure they're not going to overload her,'' the source said
Wednesday. ``The doctors were very concerned about the effect of
stress on her.''
   A spokesman for Salomon, Bob Baker, told The New York Times that
the woman returned to work this week ``on a limited basis.''
   Her name has not been published because of the crime's nature.
   The woman's aunt told WABC-TV: ``She has no animosity. She has
the determination that `I'm going to make it,' and she's thankful.''
   The aunt, in silhouette on the Wednesday broadcast, said the
jogger has no memory of the attack, ``and hopefully it will never
come back.''
   ``She's as sharp as she ever was, I think ... and in
conversation, in her grasp of what's going on in the world, she is
very cognizant of world events,'' the aunt said.
   As the woman returned to work, six youths who allegedly
assaulted her appeared in court for a pretrial hearing on whether
statements they gave to police after their arrests should be
permitted as evidence at their trials. Defense lawyers say the
statements were illegally acquired.
   The woman was discovered early on April 20 in a wooded area off
Central Park's 102nd Street transverse. Authorities said she had
been attacked hours earlier, while jogging at night, by a gang of
``wilding'' youths.
   The gang beat and raped her and left her. When found, the woman
had lost most of her blood and was suffering from hypothermia.
   Doctors, initially guarded in their prognoses, have called her
recovery remarkable.
   Before the attack, according to friends and colleagues, the
woman often began working at 7:30 a.m. and spent up to 12 hours in
the office.
   A native of a Pittsburgh suburb, she was released earlier this
month from a Connecticut rehabilitation hospital. She has moved
from her Upper East Side apartment to lower Manhattan, the source
said.
   The source also said the woman has resumed jogging, accompanied
by relatives and friends. She has told prosecutors she is eager to
testify at the trial of the six youths accused of attacking her.
</TEXT>
