<HEAD>Frost In Georgia, Snow In Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter weather chilled high altitudes in the South and Southwest
today as parts of Georgia braced for lows in the teens. A snow
advisory was posted in the south-central mountains of New Mexico,
where up to 3 inches was predicted.
   Snow moved across the east-central mountains of Arizona on
Wednesday with flurries in the White Mountains and as far south as
Morenci.
   Warnings of gale force winds remained over much of the Great
Lakes and the western Gulf of Mexico.
   Winds of 25 to 35 mph gusted to 44 mph at Milwaukee, providing a
wind chill of about 5 below zero Wednesday.
   Santa Ana winds increased across Southern California, where
several trucks were overturned by winds gusting to 70 mph along
Interstates 10 and 60 east of Los Angeles on Tuesday.
   Snow showers were scattered across Michigan late Wednesday and
over northwest Pennsylvania and northwest New York state.
   A trough of low pressure is expected to approach the northern
Plains tonight, pushing into Minnesota and Wisconsin on Friday with
an increase in cloud cover and a possibility of light snow.
   Flurries extended over parts of northwest Texas. Rain was
scattered over central Texas and across southern Florida.
   Wednesday's high temperature was 83 degrees at San Juan
Capistrano, Calif.
