<FIRST>r a PM-LouisianaExecution     11-30 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Execution,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer Wins Ninth Reprieve from Louisiana's Electric Chair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who killed a state trooper as a
teen-ager won a ninth stay of execution when the U.S. Supreme Court
said it needed more time to decide whether to hear his formal
appeal.
   Dalton Prejean was to have died today in the electric chair for
the second murder he committed as a teen-ager _ the 1977 shooting
of Donald Cleveland. Cleveland was the only Louisiana state trooper
ever murdered while on duty.
   Prejean was 17 when he shot Cleveland in the face after being
stopped for driving with a broken tail light. Prejean had been
freed six months earlier from a juvenile detention center where he
served time for killing a taxi driver when he was 14.
   He would have been the first person executed after the U.S.
Supreme Court's ruling in June that authorized executions of people
who commit capital crimes while they were 16 or 17.
   Prejean, 9 days from his 30th birthday, has been on Louisiana's
Death Row longer than any other inmate.
   Just eight hours before his scheduled execution, the Supreme
Court said it needed more time to decide whether to hear Prejean's
formal appeal to set aside his death penalty. No date has been set
for the court's action on the appeal.
   On Tuesday, Gov. Buddy Roemer rejected the State Pardon Board's
3-2 recommendation that Prejean's sentence be commuted to life
imprisonment. Soon afterward, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
denied a ninth stay of execution.
   Death penalty opponents made Prejean's case a national cause
celebre, saying he should be spared because he was nearly retarded
with an IQ of 76 and because he was so young when he killed the
trooper.
   The 5th Circuit said he is not retarded under standards of the
American Association on Mental Retardation, which sets the
threshhold at an IQ of 70.
   Prejean would have been the 19th person executed in Louisiana
since the Supreme Court upheld the death penalty in 1976.
Nationwide, 119 people have been put to death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     11-30 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Navajo Chairman Arraigned on Criminal Counts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspended Navajo Chairman Peter
MacDonald has pleaded innocent to 107 criminal counts, but his son,
also facing tribal charges, failed to appear for his arraignment.
   Judge Robert Yazzie of the tribe's Window Rock District Court
rejected the prosecution's motion for a $400,000 bond and released
the elder MacDonald on his own recognizance Wednesday. A
prosecution request that MacDonald be required to surrender his
passport also was denied.
   Yazzie did not set a trial date, but tentatively scheduled a
pretrial hearing for Jan. 29.
   Meanwhile, special prosecutor Mark Donatelli said he would apply
today for an arrest warrant to have MacDonald's son, Peter
MacDonald Jr., brought to the reservation.
   The elder MacDonald, the leader of the nation's biggest Indian
tribe, was charged Oct. 11 by special prosecutors hired by the
tribe with 107 offenses, including conspiracy, bribery, fraud,
extortion and election-law violations.
   The 60-year-old MacDonald, who was suspended by the Tribal
Council in February, also is the target of a federal grand jury
investigation in Phoenix and a defendant in a multimillion-dollar
lawsuit filed by the 225,000-member tribe in a state court.
   The lawsuit and most of the criminal charges focus on the
tribe's 1987 purchase of an Arizona ranch for $7.2 million more
than the sellers had paid for it minutes earlier.
   Suspended vice chairman, Johnnie R. Thompson, and MacDonald's
son also were charged. Thompson pleaded innocent Nov. 17 to 15
election-law violations.
   Donald Benally, an attorney for the younger MacDonald, filed a
motion on Wednesday asking that the charges be dismissed. Benally
challenged the tribal court's jurisdiction, noting that his client
has lived recently in Phoenix and San Jose, Calif.
   In seeking a $400,000 bond for the elder MacDonald, special
prosecutors said he was a flight risk and posed a danger to the
community.
   ``MacDonald may take this opportunity to flee the country and
get at money in foreign countries,'' Donatelli said. ``The time for
him to leave the country is quickly disappearing.''
   MacDonald scoffed at the prosecution's contention.
   ``I'm a good citizen of the Navajo nation,'' he said. ``I have
no plans to take a flight anywhere.''
   Allegations emerged in testimony before the U.S. Senate Select
Committee on Indian Affairs in January that MacDonald personally
profited from the tribe's purchase of the Big Boquillas Ranch from
Byron T. Brown and K. Tom Tracey, two longtime friends of
MacDonald's.
   The tribe paid $33.4 million for the ranch within minutes after
Brown and Tracey had purchased it for $26.2 million.
   Brown told the Senate panel that MacDonald received $50,000 plus
vacation trips and lease of a BMW automobile.
   In August, the tribe filed a $24 million lawsuit in state court
against MacDonald and others over the ranch purchase.
   The 88-member Tribal Council placed MacDonald on administrative
leave in February, following the Senate hearings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
