<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Two, Injure One, in Attack on Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen burst into a bar
frequented by Roman Catholics and opened fire, killing two people
and wounding one, police said.
   The attack shortly before midnight occurred in Moortown, a city
30 miles west of Belfast and a stronghold of supporters for the
predominately Catholic Irish Republican Army.
   Killed were bar owner Liam Ryan, 39, and customer Michael
Devlin, 33. An unidentified man was shot five times in the legs and
was in a stable condition at a Belfast hospital.
   Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, and the mainly
Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party party said the raid
appeared to be a reprisal by Protestant paramilitaries for an IRA
shooting in the nearby village of Coagh.
   The police statement on Wednesday's raid said: ``A number of
people were in the bar at the time. A knock was heard at the front
door. Just before the door opened, or it was about to be opened,
there were a number of shots.''
   The IRA is fighting British rule in Northern Ireland. It wants
to unite the predominantly Protestant province with the 95 percent
Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule. Protestant
paramilitaries are opposed to union with the Republic of Ireland.
