<SECOND>PM-Randy Kraft,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serial Killer Told By Victim's Father to `Burn in Hell'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of one of Randy Kraft's 16
mutilation-murder victims yelled ``Burn in hell'' after a judge
sentenced the serial killer to die in the gas chamber.
   The judge also vented outrage Wednesday at Kraft, 44, who
prosecutors said picked up young male hitchhikers between 1972 and
1983, gave them drugs and alcohol, sexually tortured or mutilated
them and then strangled them.
   ``He demonstrated an unbelievable, aggressive, violent tendency
toward humanity. I just can't imagine this violence to satisfy his
sexual desires,'' said Orange County Superior Court Judge Donald A.
McCartin.
   ``If anyone ever deserved the death penalty, he's got it
coming,'' McCartin said.
   Kraft played with his pen cap, yawned, laughed and chatted with
his lawyer during the sentencing hearing. After being sentenced,
Kraft briefly addressed the court.
   ``I have not murdered anyone and I believe a reasonable review
of the record will show that,'' said Kraft, a computer consultant
from Long Beach.
   But Juror Connie Goldfarb said the evidence in the case ``was
more horrible than any horror movie, because it was real. Yet at
times, it was so unimaginable that it was hard to believe it was
real.''
   Darwin Hall could not contain his rage at the man convicted of
murdering his 22-year-old son, Mark Howard Hall.
   ``Burn in hell, Kraft!'' the elder Hall screamed as his son's
killer was led from the court.
   Victims' relatives who endured six years of trial procedures
after Kraft's arrest cried and hugged each other outside the
courtroom.
   They wondered how Kraft, who prosecutors said tortured one
victim with a cigarette lighter before castrating and strangling
him, could appear so indifferent in court and maintain his
innocence.
   ``I saw the evidence. I guess we all know the evidence,'' said
Judy Nelson, whose 18-year-old son Geoffrey was one of Kraft's
victims. ``I don't know how he could sit there and say it other
than (because) he wants to make appeals.
   ``It just show you how pathologically a liar, a Doctor Jekyll
and Mr. Hyde, he is.''
   The judge made a similar observation.
   ``I sat here for a year, and I didn't see any remorse, feelings
or regret,'' McCartin said. ``It seemed he was in another world
during this trial.''
   McCartin assessed the death penalty for 11 murders and
consecutive life prison terms for the other five murders, saying
that would ensure Kraft's imprisonment in case all the death
sentences were somehow overturned. A death sentence is
automatically appealed to the state Supreme Court.
   Kraft also was sentenced to 10 years in prison for three counts
of sodomy, four counts of mayhem and three counts of great bodily
injury.
   A jury convicted Kraft on May 12 after a 10{-month trial and
recommended the death penalty in August.
   California Highway Patrol officers arrested Kraft in 1983 when
they pulled him over for erratic driving and discovered a strangled
Marine from El Toro Marine Corps Air Station in his car.
</TEXT>
