<UNK>Dollar Higher In Quiet Trading, Gold Falls</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
early European trading today, with some analysts predicting it
would move higher and others saying it was only pausing momentarily
before resuming its downward trend.
   Gold prices fell sharply but were recovering from their
overnight lows on a wave of fresh buying.
   Foreign exchange dealers attributed the dollar's firmer tone to
tighter U.S. interest rates and a lull in the West German mark's
upward climb.
   ``What's happening is that the mark was being overbought and
this has slowed slightly,'' one Milan trader said. ``At this point,
it's the mark that's moving everything, not the dollar.''
   Many Frankfurt dealers said the dollar will continue to move
lower against the mark in coming days, but some traders said the
market may now try to test the dollar's upside.
   ``I personally believe the short-term outlook is bullish,'' said
one trader at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt. ``I think the next move is
up. People have been buying overnight.''
   News that Deutsche Bank chief Alfred Herrhausen was killed in a
bomb attack early today was spreading through the markets but
didn't have any impact on the mark or other currencies, dealers
said.
   ``Certainly it raises concerns about internal security and
public order, but the world is focused on issues of wider
implication in Germany,'' one trader said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.63 yen to a closing 142.90 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 142.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7890 West German mark, up from 1.7825
   _1.5960 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895
   _6.1025 French francs, up from 6.0810
   _2.01855 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0100
   _1,318.50 Italian lire, up from 1,315.50
   _1.1645 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1658
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5680 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5655 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406.20 a troy ounce,
down from $412.50 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of
$406.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.75, down from $411.70 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.59 to close at a bid $405.76.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.57 a troy ounce, down
from Wednesday's $5.65.
