<HEAD>Gorbachev to Brief Allies on Summit With Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will meet with
other leaders of Warsaw Pact countries in Moscow in early December
to discuss his talks with President Bush, Tass reported today.
   It will be the highest-level meeting of the seven countries of
the East bloc alliance since hard-line Communists fell from power
in East Germany, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
   Tass did not report the date of the meeting.
   Bush and Gorbachev will meet Saturday and Sunday aboard U.S. and
Soviet warships off Malta.
   Their topics are expected to include reductions in NATO and
Warsaw Pact troops and tanks across Europe, and cuts in U.S. and
Soviet arsenals of long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear
submarines.
   Bush will travel to Brussels, Belgium, following the summit to
brief leaders of the 15 other countries that make up the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The last Warsaw Pact meeting, held in July in Bucharest,
Romania, papered over growing tensions in the Soviet-led alliance,
including differences over democratic reforms.
