<HEAD>Toddler Recovering from Liver Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Alyssa's condition improving, mother
may visit today. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alyssa Smith is ``on the road to a very good
outcome'' after undergoing the nation's first liver transplant from
a living donor, a hospital spokeswoman said today.
   Doctors planned to meet today to determine if the 21-month-old
child's condition should be upgraded from critical but stable, said
Mary Fetsch of the University of Chicago Hospitals.
   ``The first blood tests today show Alyssa's liver function is
improving,'' Fetsch said. ``She's still on an average recovery
course but certainly on the road to a very good outcome.''
   Alyssa, who underwent surgery Monday, should be able to go home
within a month, doctors said Wednesday.
   Her mother, Teresa, 29, who donated a segment of her liver to
her daughter, is progressing well enough to be released next week,
hospital officials said.
   Mrs. Smith may be able to visit Alyssa today for the first time
since the operation, Fetsch said.
   Alyssa suffered from an often fatal disorder called biliary
atresia, the leading cause for liver transplants involving
children. She had been waiting more than when her parents asked to participate
in the hospital's
new living-donor program.
</TEXT>
