<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   11-30 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0508,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Fortify Positions Near Christian Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Hrawi's comments at news
conference; pickup 13th graf pvs, `A Moslem...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Elias Hrawi said today he was
determined to gain control of the presidential palace from
rebellious Christian Gen. Michel Aoun but that he would spare no
effort to avoid bloodshed.
   ``I don't want bloodshed, either in east Beirut or in west
Beirut,'' Hrawi told reporters at a Lebanese army barracks in
Syrian-policed eastern Lebanon.
   But, he added: ``I'll use all possible means to reunite the
country.''
   Hrawi has fired Aoun as army commander and ordered him to
relinquish the presidential palace. The general refused, and he
accused Hrawi of being a lackey of the Syrians, whom he has been
trying to force out of Lebanon.
   Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
hundreds of Syrian army trucks hauled ammunition to forward
positions facing Aoun's troops in south Beirut and the eastern and
northeastern mountains.
   ``The Syrian troops are in combat formations. Their command is
supplying them with enough ammunition for quite a long time,'' one
military source said.
   France sent an amphibious troop ship, the Orage, to Lebanese
waters in preparation for a possible evacuation if French nationals
were endangered. It sailed from the southern port of Toulon early
today.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt said Lebanese army units serving
under the new commander, Adm. Emile Lahoud, would take part in any
effort to dislodge Aoun from his headquarters at the
shell-shattered presidential palace in Baabda, east of Beirut.
   ``Aoun will not quit easily. The nationalist army would take
part in the battle to evict him,'' said Jumblatt, who is minister
of public works in Hrawi's unified government.
   About 22,000 mainly Moslem troops serve under Lahoud, while Aoun
has a predominantly Christian force of 20,000 soldiers.
   Hrawi, a Maronite Catholic like Aoun, accused the rebellious
general of ``partitioning Lebanon.''
   A Moslem government official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Wednesday: ``The next 48 hours will be decisive to
determine whether Aoun's problem will be dealt with politically or
militarily.''
   Parliamentary deputy Butros Harb, a Maronite Catholic, was
dispatched by Hrawi to the Vatican and Paris early in the week ``to
discuss ways of solving Aoun's problem,'' the official said.
   Thirty-three right-wing French parliamentarians were on their
way back to Paris today, a day after they flew into Lebanon's
Christian enclave to declare support for Aoun.
   In heavy rain Wednesday, protesters carried umbrellas and took
cover under pine trees to maintain a human shield around the
presidential palace. A large crowd was still there today.
   ``The army usually defends the people. Now the people are
defending the army and its general,'' the Aoun spokesman said.
   But the Moslem Voice of the Nation radio, in a commentary, said
Aoun was using the Christian youths as ``human sandbags to hide
behind.''
   Shiite Moslem militia chieftain Nabih Berri, in a statement,
called on ``our brethren in the Christian enclave to support the
survival of Lebanon, not the survival of a person (Aoun).''
   Berri, who doubles as minister of electrical and hydraulic
resources, said Hrawi's government was one of ``national unity. A
government of peace. We prefer to solve this problem peacefully,
but we cannot wait for ever.''
   Parliament elected Hrawi president on Saturday to replace his
assassinated predecessor, Rene Mouawad. Both pledged to implement
the provisions of a Lebanon peace agreement hammered out by
Lebanon's parliament in Saudi Arabia.
   Aoun, who fought the Syrians for six months earlier this year,
rejected the accord because it did not include a fixed timetable
for a Syrian troop withdrawal.
   The Syrians have 40,000 troops controlling 70 percent of
Lebanese territory under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
</TEXT>
