<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HazelwoodHearing     11-30 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazelwood Hearing,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Did Not Want Exxon Third Mate Indicted, D.A. Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The district attorney's office
considered bringing charges against the third mate of the Exxon
Valdez in addition to the captain, but Alaska's attorney general
vetoed the idea, a prosecutor says.
   Anchorage Assistant District Attorney Brent Cole said he favored
indicting Gregory Cousins, who was in control of the tanker when it
struck a reef March 24 and began spilling nearly 11 million gallons
of oil into Prince William Sound.
   Cole testified Wednesday at a pretrial hearing for fired skipper
Joseph Hazelwood that he was told ``the attorney general said no''
to a Cousins indictment.
   ``The reasons we were told were that they felt Mr. Cousins could
help them out in their civil case, and they didn't want to make Mr.
Cousins an enemy in their civil case,'' Cole said.
   His testimony came on the third day of the hearing for
Hazelwood, who has been charged in the spill. Cole, who will be the
prosecutor at Hazelwood's trial Jan. 22, was among a string of
witnesses the state has presented to show why the captain should be
tried.
   Hazelwood, 43, a veteran mariner from Huntington, N.Y., was not
on the bridge at the time of the grounding. He left the tanker
under the supervision of Cousins.
   Hazelwood faces felony charges of criminal mischief plus
misdemeanor charges of reckless endangerment, operating a vessel
while intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil.
   Hazelwood's lawyers say charges should be dismissed because he
reported the tanker accident and thereby qualified for immunity
under state law.
   Virtually every piece of evidence against Hazelwood can be
traced to his prompt report and may not be used against him, the
defense argued.
   The state contends that discovery of the spill was inevitable
and that independent sources provided information for Hazelwood's
prosecution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
