<FIRST>u a PM-HurricaneSeason 2ndLd-Writethru a0513 11-30 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hurricane Season, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0513,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Costly 1989 Atlantic Season Ends With Tropical Storm Karen Forming
Near Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with depression forming into Tropical
Storm Karen, UPDATES total of named storms. PICKS UP 14th graf, `Last year
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 hurricane season, marked by the costliest
storm in U.S. history, officially ended today with yet another
tropical storm forming in the Caribbean.
   At 8 a.m. EST, Tropical Storm Karen, with 50 mph winds, was
about 125 miles south-southwest of Havana and was not expected to
strengthen, said the National Hurricane Center in suburban Coral
Gables. It was drifttng toward Cuba at about 5 mph.
   Depressions become named storms when their sustained winds reach
39 mph; hurricanes have winds of at least 74 mph. Karen is the 11th
named storm of the season, which began June 1.
   The six-month season was far less deadly than 1988's, in which
550 people died in storms.
   This year's storms killed 84 people, including 56 in the United
States, said meteorologist Mark Zimmer. Hurricane Hugo was blamed
for 49 deaths, including 21 in this country. It slammed into South
Carolina on Sept. 21.
   ``I've seen greater damage in smaller areas,'' said Bob Sheets,
director of the hurricane center. ``But I've never seen it on such
a large scale where you go mile after mile with such massive
damage.''
   Overall damage from Hugo totaled about $10 billion. In the
United States, it caused a record storm damage of about $7 billion.
Most of the U.S. damage was around Charleston.
   The U.S. Virgin Islands are racing to recover from Hugo in time
for the tourist season.
   ``We are still in a sense reeling from the effects of Hugo but
that didn't dampen our spirit,'' said Alexander A. Ferrelly,
governor of the U.S. Virgin Islands. He said Wednesday that St.
Thomas and St. John are ready for winter tourists and St. Croix
would be ready by early 1990.
   It was the most expensive disaster for the American Red Cross
since the organization began 110 years ago. Latest figures show the
agency has spent about $38 million in the Caribbean and the
Carolinas, said Michael Caudill, a spokesman in Washington.
   The hurricane season, which began June 1, had four tropical
storms, counting Karen, and seven hurricanes. The storms also were
stronger than usual, said Sheets.
   Last year, there were seven tropical storms and five hurricanes.
The Atlantic season usually has 10 named storms. Normally, only
five or six whip up the 74-mph sustained winds to become a
hurricane.
   Hugo, the fifth major Atlantic hurricane in the last decade to
reach U.S. shores, may have marked the end of a 30-year period of
fewer, weaker hurricanes, Sheets said.
   ``There have been fewer of the stronger hurricanes making
landfall since the 1960s,'' Sheets said. ``Now maybe we're starting
to return to more normal activity like we had in the '50s and
'60s.''
   During the 1950s, eight major hurricanes hit the United States,
while seven struck the following decade.
   After Hugo, the most damaging tropical system this year was
Tropical Storm Allison. It dumped large amounts of rain and caused
11 deaths and $500 million damage in Texas and Louisiana.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Comaneci     11-30 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comaneci,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whereabouts of Comaneci Still Unknown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nadia Comaneci, the world renowned
gymnast who made Olympic history when she was 14 years old, has
dropped from sight after fleeing across the Romanian border into
Hungary.
   Ms. Comaneci's former coach, Bela Karolyi, said today she was
``probably'' in the U.S. Embassy in Switzerland obtaining travel
papers, but an embassy spokesman denied it.
   Karolyi became a U.S. citizen last spring and is currently in
West Germany with an American women's gymnastics team.
   Ms. Comaneci told Hungarian border officials she had been banned
by Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu from traveling abroad and was
fleeing her native land ``for the sake of freedom,'' official media
reported.
   Ms. Comaneci crossed into Hungary by car before dawn Tuesday at
the border town of Kiszombor, with six other Romanians who were not
identified, the MTI news agency said.
   Her defection was a surprise, particularly because the
28-year-old athlete-turned-trainer reportedly had close ties with
the Ceausescu family and at one time was said to have been
romantically involved with the Romanian president's son, Nicu.
   Ms. Comaneci dropped from sight Wednesday, when she and her
companions left the hotel in the nearby town of Szeged where they
had been lodged by police, according to Hungarian press reports.
   Ms. Comaneci had been given a three-day temporary residence
permit.
   A spokesman at the Hungarian Olympic Committee told The
Associated Press today the gymnast had not contacted them and they
knew nothing of her whereabouts.
   Because of her achievements, Ms. Comaneci was named a ``Hero of
Socialist Labor'' by Ceausescu, the hard-line leader who declared
at last week's Romanian Communist Party Congress that he would not
yield to the forces of reform sweeping the rest of the East Bloc.
   At age 14, Ms. Comaneci dazzled the sports world at the 1976
Montreal Olympic Games with the first-ever scores of perfect 10s in
Olympic gymnastics. She won three gold medals, in the uneven bars,
balance beam and overall competitions.
   The achievements of the 4-foot-11 teen-ager brought her elite
status in her homeland and tremendous popularity in the United
States.
   During a competitive career that lasted until 1984, Ms. Comaneci
won a total of 21 gold medals in Olympic and other international
contests.
   She reportedly had been living in an eight-room villa and had a
Western car, both extremely rare for private citizens in a country
that has endured chronic shortages of consumer goods for most of
this decade.
   In the past two years, tens of thousands of Romanians have
sought refuge in Hungary because of worsening economic conditions
and political intransigence at home.
   ``Just like me, she was chased out of the country by the
Romanian authorities,'' said Karolyi, who defected to the United
States in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
