<FIRST>u a PM-RiotTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 11-30 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0565,0839</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman Says Motorcyclist Was Aiming For Him</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th pvs, `Lozano's account ...' with cross-examination
of officer. PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Lozano was ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer whose slaying of a black suspect
set off three days of rioting took the stand at his manslaughter
trial today and said he fired because the man was bearing down on
him with his motorcycle.
   ``I turned my body to face the motorcycle. He just came straight
at me with a tremendous noise,'' said Officer William Lozano. ``He
was just aiming at me. I was just able to turn my body, draw my gun
and shoot.''
   The five-year veteran of the Miami Police Department said he
thought he was going to die and was briefly in shock.
   After recovering, he said, he found no vital signs when he
checked on the motorcyclist. He saw that the cyclist's passenger
was injured and radioed a dispatcher to say he had fired his weapon
and a fatality was involved.
   The prosecution charges Lozano acted with gross negligence when
he shot and killed the motorcyclist, Clement Lloyd, 23, on Jan. 16,
sparking three days of rioting in the community's black
neighborhoods. The passenger, Alan Blanchard, died the next day.
Lozano is charged with manslaughter in their deaths.
   Lozano, 31, testified that he was ``hyper'' and that the
dispatcher did not understand his first transmission. He said he
took a deep breath and repeated it.
   Within moments, an angry crowd gathered and Lozano said he and
others ``were getting hit right and left'' with rocks and bottles.
   Lozano's account came after a half-hour of questioning about his
personal history and his police service, giving the jury an
impression of a well-trained officer with a list of commendations.
   Under cross examination, Assistant State Attorney John Hogan
asked Lozano to read aloud from a police review document that
listed Lozano as average in most categories, including
decision-making and reliability.
   Hogan also had Lozano recount an incident in which a jai-alai
player accused Lozano of physical abuse during a strike.
   Lozano was just beginning to review the events leading up to the
shooting when the trial was recessed for 45 minutes after an
alternate juror complained of abdominal pain and nausea.
   Addressing his answers with a slight Spanish accent directly to
the jury, the Colombian-born Lozano wore a dark blue suit, dress
shirt and red tie for his appearance. The testimony was broadcast
live on Miami television and radio.
   Prosecution witnesses contended that the motorcyclist was in the
opposite lane from Lozano when the officer coolly took aim at the
driver, tracked him with his gun and fired the fatal shot as the
bike was about to pass him.
   The defense, however, insists that the motorcyclist, attempting
to outrun a pursuing squad car, had crossed into the traffic lane
where Lozano was standing and the officer shot in self-defense to
avoid being run over.
   One defense witness, 18-year-old Dedrick Belle, balked at giving
depositions and had fled investigators attempting to talk to him,
according to court testimony.
   Belle, who lives in the Overtown neighborhood where the shooting
and subsequent rioting occurred, told the court Wednesday he feared
for his life if he was made to testify for the defense.
   ``It will result in violence ... because I'm black and he shot a
black guy,'' Belle told Dade Circuit Judge Joseph Farina.
   Over the objections of media attorneys, the judge banned any
filming of Belle during his brief testimony.
   His testimony was aimed at compromising star prosecution witness
Eddie Johnson, who was talking with Lozano just before the
shooting. Johnson wound up with the cartridge casing from the fatal
bullet after the shooting, but denied on the stand that he had
waved it about or shown it to neighbors before turning it over to
police.
   Belle, however, said Johnson showed the shell to everyone, and
even let him hold it.
   Other defense witnesses Wednesday included a former University
of Miami professor, Geoffrey Alpert, who prepared a study of Miami
police weapon discharges between Jan. 1, 1980, and Dec. 31, 1986.
   Alpert, who now teaches at the University of South Carolina,
said 13 percent of the 150 shootings he examined were instances in
which an officer was firing while being attacked by a vehicle.
   The prosecution has contended that Lozano disregarded police
policy when he failed to step out of the roadway, and then fired at
a moving vehicle.
   When the case opened Oct. 23, the defense attempted
unsuccessfully to move the trial, arguing that Miami juries would
be too worried about renewed racial violence to find Lozano
innocent.
   Twice before in this decade, innocent verdicts favoring
policemen accused of killing blacks have led to rioting, and the
Miami and Metro-Dade police forces have been on alert because of
Lozano's trial.
</TEXT>
