<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-LeaningTower     11-30 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leaning Tower,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Close Leaning Tower, Pisa Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local officials Thursday disputed the
government's plan to close Pisa's famed leaning tower for
restoration work, saying it is in no immediate danger.
   ``The closure is unjustified because the situation of the tower
has not worsened recently and because conservation work can be
initiated without banning tourists,'' said Giuseppe Toniolo, who
heads Opera Primaziale, the private institution managing and
restoring the tower.
   An estimated 800,000 visitors a year climb the 294 marble steps
of the 162-foot monument, bringing in revenue of about $71.4
million.
   The government commission for public works suggested Tuesday the
leaning tower be closed immediately. A final decision by the
government is expected soon, although the city can appeal it to
Parliament.
   Government experts are worried because its tilt has been
increasing by an average 0.047 inches a year since measurements
began in 1918.
   The tower was completed in 1360, and experts believe it began
leaning immediately because it was built on sinking soil.
   The government has allotted $7.1 million for the conservation of
the tower, but experts have been stumped on how to save it.
   Gero Geri, a professor of topography in Pisa, has said it will
take at least 100 years before the tower reached the point of
toppling.
</TEXT>
