<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Hugo-Trees     11-30 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hugo-Trees,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Carolina Gets $8.4 million in Federal Money for Fire Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government will give South
Carolina $8.4 million to fight the threat of forest fires fueled by
thousands of trees downed by Hurricane Hugo, state and federal
officials said Thursday.
   The money will be used to cut 11,400 miles of firebreaks, lease
fire detection and fighting equipment, fund a public awareness
program and coordinate efforts to salvage downed timber worth an
estimated $1 billion, said Paul Hall of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency.
   ``We at FEMA believe the Hugo forest blow-down is a serious
emergency with the potential for great danger in the event of
serious, uncontrolled wildfires,'' Hall said.
   Officials say 36 percent of the 12.2 million acres of forested
land in South Carolina was damaged by the Sept. 21 storm. They say
they are weighing plans to ban burning in some unincorporated areas
of the state to lessen the fire danger.
</TEXT>
