<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     11-30 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 Killed, 450 Injured in Violence During General Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violence broke out amid a nationwide
general strike, and two people were killed and 450 injured, police
said Thursday.
   A supporter of the National Socialist Party, was killed in a gun
battle inside the Dhaka University campus with student activists of
the Awami League during the general strike, a police official said.
   The National Socialist Party and the Awami League both oppose
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad and his government, but like most
opposition groups, they periodically fight each other. Both groups
supported the strike, which was called for Wednesday and Thursday.
   One person was killed and at least nine others injured when two
bombs exploded at an opposition rally in Dhaka on Thursday, the
officer said.
   The strike was called by the Awami League and the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party, another major opposition group, to dramatize
their demands for Ershad's resignation.
   In Dhaka, shops, banks and schools remained closed and traffic
was sparse Thursday. News reports said the strike was successful in
at least 20 other major towns.
   Police and news reports said at least 450 people were injured
and 300 anti-government demonstrators arrested nationwide in
clashes with police.
   It was the latest in a series of strikes called by opposition
parties to try to force free elections under a caretaker
government. Ershad says he is willing to hold new elections without
relinquishing power, a proposal the opposition has rejected.
   Ershad's two main political opponents _ Sheik Hasina of the
Awami League and Khaleda Zia of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party _
said the success of the strike was a verdict against the government.
   Mrs. Zia told Ershad to resign by Dec. 31 or face more street
protests.
   Ershad, 59, a former army general, seized power in a bloodless
coup in 1982. He resigned from the army in 1985 and a year later
was elected to a five--year presidential term in elections that
many believed to be rigged.
</TEXT>
