<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-30 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hummingbird that stayed too long in
Alaska is about to get a free flight to California with the help of
an amateur ornithologist who took the bird under her wing.
   Hummingbirds usually leave the Alaska Panhandle by late summer,
but a male Anna's hummingbird appeared in October outside the home
of a woman who had put her hummingbird feeder away for the winter.
The woman put the feeder back outside and contacted Bev Woods, a
volunteer with a Juneau wildlife group.
   Woods provided a trap to catch the bird, and is feeding it at
her home until transportation can be arranged.
   Woods said Wednesday that the species of hummingbird has been
spotted in Juneau only in recent years. ``The Anna's hummingbird
pretty much breeds along northern California and into Oregon,'' she
said.
   Woods has received about 20 offers from people planning to fly
to northern California or southern Oregon in the next few weeks and
willing to take the bird along. A hummingbird expert in San
Francisco has offered to acclimate it to the weather there before
releasing it, she said.
   It will be the second hummingbird to receive a free trip south
from Alaska this fall. About a month ago a Costa's hummingbird
found in Anchorage was flown to Seattle and released.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the land of the power lunch, some
professionals tired of the same old faces and deal-oriented dining
prefer just to share a nice midday meal with someone new.
   Capitalizing on that need, entrepreneur Stephen Bagish arranges
blind lunch dates at $15 a pop.
   Bagish, 29, quit his job as a video distributor three months ago
to create the Lunch With Someone New service, which he says is
designed for the purely platonic joining of kindred souls.
   ``My service pairs people for a friendly lunch _ not for love or
sex,'' he said.
   Bradley Rose, an attorney who signed up, said the lack of dating
pressure made the noontime encounter more enjoyable.
   ``For $15, you expect to maybe make a new friend at lunch, to
have a good time. That's exactly what it was,'' Rose said.
   Bagish said he came up with the idea after dining with the same
colleague day after day.
   ``He's a nice guy,'' Bagish said. ``But every day? No way.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TARENTUM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who may have the world's largest
bell collection says it's easy to become hooked on the hobby.
   ``Touch one or two and first thing you know, you're a
bell-a-holic,'' said Iva Mae Long, whose children and grandchildren
also have caught the bug.
   Mrs. Long's home in western Pennsylvania is brimming with about
20,000 bells. A 2,200-pound one is displayed in the front yard.
   Mrs. Long caught the bug from her father, James Oliver Elliott,
who died in 1983 at age 93. He started the hobby in the early
1950s, though the idea for the collection had been planted in his
mind before the Great Depression.
   ``He rode with his father on a milk wagon, and they used to ring
a bell at each stop to signal customers to come out with their
containers to be filled,'' she said.
   Mrs. Long began her own collection in 1959, later inherited her
father's bells, and can't resist adding still more.
   ``After all, a bell is the only thing in the house that thanks
you for dusting it _ it rings,'' she said.
</TEXT>
