<FIRST>r a PM-MX-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0480 11-30 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MX-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Tale of Two Cities: One Accepted, Other Rejected For MX Missiles</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CLARIFY that six sites were chosen in
addition to the Wyoming base. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `The loss ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-MX Missiles, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB MOEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Forks officials were ``pleased as
the dickens'' about winning a bid for rail-based MX nuclear
missiles that would bring jobs and prestige.
   ``That's a lot of insurance policies, cars and turtlenecks,''
said Bob Gustafson, president of the Grand Forks Chamber of
Commerce, after learning Wednesday that the Grand Forks Air Force
Base was among six new sites chosen to get the missiles, all of
which are currently kept at a base in Wyoming.
   But in Minot, 200 miles to the west, there was disappointment.
   Both cities lobbied hard for the missiles, through
letter-writing campaigns and visits to Washington.
   The 50 MX missiles are to be removed from underground silos in
Wyoming and placed on 25 trains, each with two MX missiles aboard.
The trains will be in Wyoming and on bases in Grand Forks and five
other areas around the country. The missiles will be moved onto
civilian railroad tracks in time of crisis.
   The loss of the rail-based system was hard on Minot because it
came just about a year after the transfer of 18 fighter jets to a
National Guard base in Massachusetts.
   ``You win some and you lose some,'' said Bruce Christianson,
chairman of the Minot Chamber of Commerce's military affairs
committee.
   The Grand Forks base and the Minot Air Force Base maintain
nuclear missiles and strategic bombers. The Minot base opened in
1959, and the Grand Forks base in 1960. The Minot base has about
14,000 military personnel and their families, the Grand Forks base
13,000.
   Both bases contribute more than $200 million to the economies of
their communities.
   ``We're disappointed, of course,'' said Minot Mayor George
Christensen. ``We don't know what they have down the line, but we'd
accept anything else.''
   Brig. Gen. Patrick Caruana, commander of the Grand Forks base,
said construction of the MX system could begin in 1992 and the
system could become operational two years later.
   North Dakota houses about 300 Minuteman missiles _ each capable
of carrying three warheads _ in underground silos near Minot and
Grand Forks. The MX missiles can carry up to 10 warheads.
   Caruana said the Grand Forks garrison will cost $80 million to
$100 million, and employ as many as 450 people.
   But Grand Forks Mayor Mike Polovitz, along with the state's
congressional delegation, cautioned that the project might not be
built at all because of changes taking place in the Soviet Union
and its Eastern European allies.
   ``I still have some questions whether it will be funded because
of what is happening in Europe now,'' Polovitz said. ``I'm pleased
that we as acommunity got together and worked for this. I'm also
pleased with what's happening in Eastern Europe, so we're kind of
caught in between.
   ``If they go ahead with the rail garrison and fund it, I'm
pleased as the dickens to have it here in Grand Forks.''
   Peace activists, meanwhile, were unhappy with the entire idea of
the MX missiles.
   ``An MX missile by its very nature is a first-strike weapon,''
said Al Hermodson of the Crookston Peace Workers in Crookston,
Minn., near Grand Forks. ``I see this either as a continuation of
first-strike capability or as a welfare program for weapons
manufacturers. I think it's a little of both.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Religion Bjt   11-30 0902</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Religion, Bjt,0926</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Son of Stavropol Peasants Finds Place for Religion in His Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man struggling to renew Lenin's revolution
more than 70 years after it declared religion the ``opiate of the
people'' was himself baptized in his peasant village into the
ancient rites of Russian Orthodoxy.
   And if 58 years later Mikhail S. Gorbachev does not believe in
God, his early years apparently engendered a healthy respect for
those who do, including his mother.
   The Gorbachev years have seen a dramatic shift in official
tolerance of religion in a country whose people ostensibly have
been turned into spiritual materialists by decades of Communist
dogma. Gorbachev has told religious leaders that they, too, have a
place in the Communist-led healing of the nation's psyche.
   But as government pressure eases, the future of a nascent
religious revival is beginning to depend more on the willingness of
church leaders to throw off their own strictures and traditional
subservience.
   Since Gorbachev became Soviet leader in March 1985:
   _ The number of baptisms and reopenings of churches in the
Christian heartland have increased dramatically. Important
religious centers like the Pechorsky Monastery of Kiev have been
given back. Jews also enjoy greater religious freedom and a revival
of Islam in Central Asia is increasing the number of seminary
students and mosques.
   _ Scores of religious dissidents of all faiths have been freed
from jails and prison camp.
   _ The patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church has met with the
Soviet leader for the first time in more than 40 years. Clergy
celebrated the 400th anniversary of the Moscow Patriarchate on Oct.
13 with the first service in more than 70 years in the Kremlin's
Uspensky Cathedral, where Russian czars once were crowned.
   _ Gorbachev has met with a top representative of the Vatican,
and will meet with Pope John Paul II on Friday. Members of the
banned Ukrainian Catholic Church in the western Ukraine believe the
Vatican meeting will lead to legalization of their church after 43
years underground.
   Asked in July whether he had been baptized after his birth in
1931 in the southern Russian village of Privolnoye, Gorbachev
replied: ``Yes, I was. I think it's quite normal, isn't it?''
Reporters who have visited the area say his mother, Maria, still
regularly attends Russian Orthodox services.
   Interviewed by Finnish TV in conjunction with Gorbachev's visit
to Helsinki in October, Archbishop Anatoly of Stavropol said the
official attitude toward religion in that region, which includes
Privolnoye, eased when Gorbachev was the local Communist Party
leader.
   ``Practically speaking, beginning in 1975 in Stavropol churches
and groups of believers have been able to exercise all their
rights,'' he said. ``We've had perestroika since 1975.'' Gorbachev
was regional party chief from 1970 to 1978.
   When he met with Patriarch Pimen of the Russian Orthodox Church
prior to the celebration of the church's millenium in 1988,
Gorbachev made clear that religious believers have both a stake and
a place in his reform program.
   The millenium, he said, should be ``marked by the consolidation
of our country's believers, all working people, for the sake of our
common great cause of perestroika, of the renewal of socialism, the
complete unfolding of its humanistic ethical potential.''
   Soviet officials have been reporting for more than two years
that a new law on religion is being prepared, and they say it is
likely to be presented to the Soviet legislature soon.
   They promise the law will ease strict Stalin-era prohibitions on
group religious instruction and charitable work by churches, and
make it easier for them to receive official recognition.
   The law has not yet been changed, but some Russian Orthodox
churches have begun to act. According to the weekly Moscow News,
Moscow parishes are contributing heavily to support children's
homes in the capital.
   Veniamin Yefremov, an inspector for the government Council of
Religious Affairs that has been charged with overseeing believers,
encouraged more charitable work.
   ``Apparently some people are waiting for some instructions from
above. There is only one instruction in such work _ the dictates of
the heart,'' he said.
   Muscovites say baptism has become increasingly popular, even
fashionable, in some circles. But it does not mean that the
baptized know much about the faith they have embraced, or even want
to know.
   Two scholars, writing in the Communist theoretical journal
Kommunist in 1987, said people had begun flocking to churches to
find some beauty in the religious chanting and church icons that
was missing in their increasingly cheerless lives in the Soviet
system.
   Religious critics wonder whether Russian Orthodox Church
officials, used to taking what the government is willing to give,
can take advantage of the freer atmosphere.
   During recent harsh years, the Russian Orthodox Church
concentrated much activity on disarmament issues, which at the time
coincided with Soviet government propaganda efforts.
   Ukrainian Catholics are demanding the return from the Russian
Orthodox Church of buildings and property taken over when their
religion was forced underground in 1946.
   ``If we could count on sincerity and Christian love from the
Russian church there wouldn't be a problem,'' said Father Yaroslav
Chukhny, who led Lvov's Cathedral of the Transfiguration from the
Russian Orthodox Church to the Ukrainian Catholic Church on Oct. 29.
   ``The essence of religion is not building churches or holding
beautiful services, but the morals of man,'' he said.
</TEXT>
