<FIRST>r i AM-Stealth-Fighter     11-30 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth-Fighter,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Photos of Stealth Fighter Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photos of the U.S. Stealth fighter, said to show
the top-secret warplane in unprecedented detail, have been
published in a weekly defense magazine.
   Jane's Defense Weekly said the pictures show that the view of
the plane given by the U.S. Air Force a year ago ``was carefully
selected to conceal the F-117's true shape, and made the aircraft
appear much shorter and wider than it is.''
   The article accompanying the two pictures was written by Bill
Sweetman, a leading civilian authority on the Stealth program to
build bombers and fighters that can elude radar detection.
   One picture appeared to show the delta-winged Lockheed F-117A
flying horizontally, while the other showed it in a vertical
position. In each picture its landing gear was down and it was
accompanied by a T-38 chase plane.
   Sweetman wrote the aircraft is coated in radar-absorbent
material and ``faceted'' to discourage the scattering of radar
energy toward the transmitter location.
   The fighter is a different aircraft from the Stealth bomber
recently unveiled for TV cameras.
   Sweetman wrote that the fighter's overall length is 66.6 feet,
wingspan is 41.6 feet and maximum takeoff weight is about 45,100
pounds.
   The report said two squadrons of F-117s are operational with the
4450th Tactical Group at Tonopah, Nev.
   It said the last of 59 F-117s, including five test aircraft,
were likely to be delivered next year. It said one test aircraft
and two production planes have been lost in accidents since the jet
made its first flight in October 1981.
</TEXT>
