<SECOND>PM-Mass Taxes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Legislature Takes Up Tax Increases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `As the ...' to ADD that Dukakis has endorsed
the package. House debate begins 1 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state legislative committee approved and sent to
the House for debate today $1.1 billion in tax increases to close
the budget deficit that signaled the end of the Massachusetts
Miracle.
   The package of higher taxes on capital gains, sales and gasoline
was approved on a voice vote Wednesday by the House Ways and Means
Committee. It immediately drew fire from both legislators and the
public.
   ``This bill imposes the most regressive kind of a tax, hitting
hardest those in Massachusetts who can least afford it,'' said
Edward E. Mulligan, head of Massachusetts Electric Co.
   The House was scheduled to begin debate on the package today,
and House leaders said they hoped to send it to the Senate by the
end of the week.
   The proposal is the Legislature's latest move to deal with the
deficit, which a Ways and Means Committee staffer said had swelled
to $825 million. Only a year ago, the economic boom dubbed the
Massachusetts Miracle nearly carried Gov. Michael Dukakis to the
White House.
   As the committee sent the proposal to the House, the Senate held
hearings on a $350 million House-approved package of spending cuts.
Legislative leaders envision enacting the cuts in conjuction with
the tax package, which has been embraced by the governor.
   Under the tax package, the sales tax would rise from five cents
to seven cents on the dollar; the gas tax would go from 11 cents to
21 cents per gallon, and capital gains would be increased from 5
percent to 7.5 percent.
   The package would raise nearly $1.1 billion in additional
revenue by the next fiscal year. Still more revenue would be raised
by shifting $30 million more in cigarette taxes into the general
fund and by collecting $24 million in unclaimed returnable-bottle
deposits.
   The package was developed by the House leadership, and Speaker
George Keverian backed it up by telling several committee chairmen
they should resign if they they could not support it. One committee
chairman quit on Tuesday.
   Democratic Rep. John McDonough spoke up for new taxes before the
Ways and Means vote, saying it was time the Legislature and the
administration corrected spending errors that were based on overly
ambitious revenue estimates.
   ``At what point do we face up to the fact that we were all wrong
about the deficit?'' he asked.
   Rep. Steven Pierce, the Republican minority leader, said the
Democratic leadership's deficit estimates are designed to promote
taxes. He estimated the deficit is less than $500 million and
accused the Democratic leadership of ``twisting arms and getting
that tax bill through here as quickly as possible.''
   John Gould, head of Associated Industries of Massachusetts, said
the increase in the capital gains tax would stifle economic growth.
   ``We are going to ... hurt our image and make ourselves less
attractive to investors from outside the state,'' he said.
</TEXT>
