<SECOND>AM-Stolen Books,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Librarian Charged With Theft Of Rare Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head librarian at the
University of Texas Medical Branch has been charged with stealing
five rare medical books from the school.
   Emil Frey, 62, surrendered to Galveston County sheriff's
officials Wednesday and was later released on $23,000 bond.
   An indictment handed up Monday accuses Frey of stealing five of
80 books missing from the UTMB Moody Medical Library's
12,000-volume Truman G. Blocker Rare Book Collection _ one of the
nation's largest collections of rare medical texts. The indictment
says the books were valued between $750 and $20,000.
   University police found several books in a private storage shed
rented by Frey, said a statement issued Wednesday by the Galveston
County district attorney's office.
   ``Police officials contend the books were sent to a bookseller
in New York City for sale by Frey for his personal benefit,'' the
statement said.
   Frey's attorney, David Walker, declined to comment on the case,
saying he hadn't had a chance to go over the indictment in detail.
   Frey became director of the Moody Medical Library in 1973. He
resigned from his $83,000-a-year position May 17 amid an
investigation into the disappearance of the books.
   Officials at the University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston
have said the missing books were duplicates of others in the
collection.
</TEXT>
