<HEAD>British Cosmonauts Travel to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two British finalists for a joint space
mission with the Soviet Union in 1991 flew to Moscow on Thursday.
   Helen Sharman and Timothy Mace were chosen from 13,000
applicants seeking to become the first Briton in space.
   The candidates will train at the Gagarin Center near Moscow for
18 months, learning Russian and practicing experiments along with
physical preparations for the flight, organizers said.
   Only one will be chosen for the eight-day mission aboard the Mir
space station. The other will be a backup.
   `I don't know exactly what is in store for us but there will be
a lot of physical training and we will have to learn about
navigation and how to fly the spacecraft,'' said Ms. Sharman, 26, a
food technologist from London.
   Mace, of Hampshire, a 33-year-old advanced instructor in
helicopters and the British freefall parachuting champion, said:
``I'm very excited and looking forward to the challenge.''
   The mission is being financed by international companies and
both British astronauts will be paid about $78,000 by the
fund-raising company Antequaria.
