<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam-US     11-30 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vietnam-US,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Team Discusses MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team has completed
talks with Vietnam on cooperation to find out what happened to
American servicemen missing in the Vietnam War, a U.S. Embassy
spokesman said Thursday.
   The team returned from Hanoi on Wednesday after three days of
talks, said James Williams of the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok.
   He quoted the U.S. team leader, Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, as saying
the talks ``ranged from researching and investigating specific
crash sites to the exchange of wartime information.'' They agreed
to meet again in January.
   Harvey commands the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center, which
is trying to determine what happened to 2,323 Americans who did not
return from the war.
   The talks were the first since October, when special U.S.
presidential envoy John W. Vessey met Vietnamese Foreign Minister
Nguyen Co Thach. Vessey said Vietnam agreed to work on lists of
top-priority ``discrepancy cases'' involving about 80 Americans.
Such cases include people the United States believes were taken
prisoner but not freed after U.S. involvement in the war ended in
1973.
</TEXT>
