<HEAD>Soviet Denies U.S. Charge of Arms for Salvadoran Rebels</HEAD>
<UNK>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official on Thursday denied an accusation
by U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III that Moscow has
broken its promise to see that no Soviet-made arms reach Salvadoran
rebels.
   Baker said Wednesday that President Bush would complain about
the matter when he meets with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
during their summit off Malta.
   Baker said the Soviets have promised to prevent Marxist
Nicaragua from shipping Soviet arms to rebels fighting the
U.S.-backed government in El Salvador, but that the pratice
continues.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, who was
in Rome for Gorbachev's three-day visit to Italy, reiterated the
Kremlin's insistance that it does not supply arms for Central
American conflicts.
   Responding to questions about the White House complaints,
Gerasimov said: ``We don't supply Salvadoran rebels.''
   ``You must believe us,'' Gerasimov said, adding the Soviets
understand that their allies in the region, Cuba and Nicaragua,
also ``are not sending arms'' to El Salvador.
   Gerasimov said Bush and Gorbachev could discuss the dispute,
which he described as involving a ``discrepancy in information.''
