<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Belknap Bjt   11-30 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Belknap, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belknap Sailors Rush To Prepare Site For Superpower Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine captain drilled the honor
guard in crisp salutes while sailors scrubbed and painted the USS
Belknap Thursday for President Bush's shipboard summit with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The almost 600-member crew aboard the guided missile cruiser
worked around visiting reporters and a tour of Soviet sailors and
officers to spruce up the Belknap and prepare its rooms for the
heads of state.
   ``Of course the real importance of this visit is not the ship
itself, but the president of the Soviet Union and the president of
the United States meeting on this ship,'' said Capt. John Sigler,
the commander of the Belknap.
   ``We feel very honored to be a part of this hopefully very
historic moment,'' he added.
   When Bush, a former Navy aviator, first steps off a helicopter
onto the deck of the Belknap, he'll be able to see a hand-lettered
``Beat Army'' poster pasted to a bulkhead.
   Bush will sleep in the quarters of Vice Adm. J.D. Williams, the
6th Fleet commander, meet privately with Gorbachev in the admiral's
small dining room and be host for a state dinner prepared by White
House chefs in the crowded confines of the officer's mess.
   The Belknap is anchored a few hundred yards behind the Soviet
missile cruiser Slava, where Gorbachev will be host on Saturday for
talks with Bush in richly paneled wardrooms appointed with plush
furniture and oriental rugs.
   By comparison, the site of Saturday's state dinner in the
Belknap wardroom is spartan. The walls are white and wainscotted
with artificial paneling. A Soviet and American flag are displayed
below one porthole. Two tables, one seating 20 and the other 10,
are crowded into the room along with a large milk cooler that can
be hidden with a navy blue curtain.
   Sigler, who was to visit the Slava later Thursday, said he had
heard the Soviet warship had more creature comforts.
   ``I heard they have a sauna for example,'' he said.
   ``I think we are comfortable,'' he added. ``I don't feel at a
disadvantage, I just think there is perhaps a different emphasis
here than there.''
   There are other, more obvious differences between the two ships.
   The Slava is 17 years younger than the 25-year-old Belknap,
slightly longer and its decks are bristling with arms. There are 16
surface-to-surface missile tubes on the Soviet cruiser, compared to
just four on the American ship.
   ``It's a beautiful ship,'' Sigler said of the Slava. ``Of course
it is much newer than my ship and the Soviets tend to have most of
their weapons topside, where we have most of ours below decks. The
result is that she looks heavily armed. I think our capabilities
are very similar in a lot of ways. But she certainly looks
imposing.''
   Bush's quarters aboard the Belknap are small and cramped. The
blue-carpeted cabin has just about 20 square feet of floor space, a
double bed, a gold recliner and a Toshiba color television with
Fisher VHS and Sony Beta videotape players.
   From his porthole on the starboard side, the president will have
a view of the St. Luciano Watchtower, a 16th Century castle built
by the Knights of Malta on a jagged cliff that juts into Marsaxlokk
Bay at the point closest to the American and Soviet warships.
   The president also will use the admiral's office, which is
dominated by a large wooden desk on which sits a Christmas card
addressed to Bush from Emily Shewchuk, the 7-year-old daughter of
one of the Belknap's officers. Gorbachev will be given a holding
room in the chief of staff's office.
   Bush's cabin and office are one flight up a steep metal ladder
from the main deck and just steps away from the admiral's mess
where the two leaders will meet with just two interpreters and two
people to take notes.
   Bush and Gorbachev will deliver their joint statement at the end
of the summit Sunday on the Belknap's forecastle, standing beneath
the launchers for the cruiser's surface-to-air missiles.
   Earlier Sunday, Bush will attend a non-denominational Protestant
church service at the same site.
   ``I am very nervous, very nervous,'' said Lt. David Schwabauer,
a Presbyterian minister who is the ship's chaplain. ``The thought
of preaching to the president of the United States is terrifying.''
</TEXT>
