<FIRST>u a PM-AIDSPlay-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0531 11-30 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Play-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Damages Home of Politician Who Opposed AIDS Play</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire ruled accidental, CLARIFIES that
student led campaign in support of the play. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that damaged the home of a
legislator who had tried to keep a state university from putting on
a play about AIDS and homosexuality was declared accidental today.
   Fireplace embers dumped in the back yard Wednesday night by one
of Jean Dixon's children ignited leaves and scrap wood and spread
to the state representative's home, Chief Fire Marshal Dale Bittle
said.
   Arson investigators had been called in to determine whether the
fire was set, like a blaze on Nov. 15 that destroyed the home of a
student who had led a campaign in support of the play, Larry
Kramer's ``The Normal Heart.''
   Fire Chief Phil Johnston estimated damage Dixon's home at $5,000
to $10,000, mostly involving the attic and exterior. There were no
injuries.
   Dixon and her husband were away at the time, but five Dixon
children ranging from 7 to 20 years old were at home with an adult
friend, the fire chief said. A neighbor discovered the fire about
12:40 a.m. and alerted those inside, who included three sleeping
children.
   Dixon, a Republican, was among the most vocal opponents of a
presentation of ``The Normal Heart'' at Southwest Missouri State
University on Nov. 15-20. She objected to use of a public facility
for a play that presents homosexuality as an acceptable lifestyle.
   Kramer and his supporters accused her of censorship and said the
play, which quickly sold out amid the controversy, helped educate
students about AIDS.
   The night the play opened, someone apparently set a fire at the
home of Brad Evans, 22, after forcing open a back door,
investigators said. Evans was leading a candlelight ceremony in
support of the play when the fire occurred.
</TEXT>
