<FIRST>u a PM-RockyFlats-Plutonium 1stLd-Writethru a0564 11-30 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats-Plutonium, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0564,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Suspending Some Plutonium Operations at Rocky Flats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with Energy Department saying it is suspending
some but not all plutonium operations. PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Last year
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department today said it is suspending
some plutonium operations at Rocky Flats while a new contractor
takes over at the weapons plant, which is under FBI investigation
for alleged safety violations.
   Catherine Kaliniak, an Energy Department spokeswoman in
Washington, said a ``major curtailment'' of plutonium operations at
the plant will be completed sometime next week. The plant makes
plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons.
   Kaliniak would not disclose how many plutonium operations will
continue, saying that was classified information.
   Last year the plant was shut down temporarily after a safety
violation. The move came amid a rash of safety and management
problems, interruptions and shutdowns at the 16 major facilities in
12 states involved in making nuclear weapons.
   Kaliniak said the Rocky Flats suspension had nothing to do with
safety concerns, and David P. Simonson, manager of the Energy
Department office at Rocky Flats, said the move is part of the
process by which EG&amp;G Inc. is taking over from Rockwell
International Corp. as operator of the plant 16 miles northwest of
Denver.
   ``The department is using this transition period to work with
EG&amp;G to establish a formal, structured program for the resumption
of nuclear facility operations,'' Simonson said. ``The program now
under development with EG&amp;G will ensure that future operations are
governed by the highest standards of performance.''
   Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., had announced Wednesday that he
asked Energy Secretary James Watkins in a Nov. 16 letter to halt
production at Rocky Flats. Hours later, Simonson said the plant was
already in the midst of a production curtailment that was scheduled
in August, began Nov. 13 and would continue through mid-January.
   Skaggs, whose district includes the plant, said later Wednesday
that the curtailment ``falls far short of what I have called for.''
   Skaggs said an Energy Department report last month indicated
only luck has prevented a serious accident at Rocky Flats. He said
the report concluded the fail-safe system at the plant is flawed
and does not follow accepted nuclear industry standards and that
the plant does not have adequate control over its plutonium stock.
   Simonson maintained that Watkins has ordered ``essentially all
the recommendations mentioned by Congressman Skaggs in his Nov. 16
letter.''
   FBI agents earlier this year raided Rocky Flats for evidence of
safety and environmental violations.
   Gov. Roy Romer said Watkins would visit Rocky Flats on Friday
and make more information available on the plant's safety. Ms.
Kaliniak said she could not confirm that Watkins was even
considering such a visit.
   On a related issue, Romer and Skaggs say they have concluded
there were no illegal midnight burnings of toxic waste inside a
top-secret building at the plant.
   The allegation, denied for months by Rockwell and the Energy
Department, surfaced in an affidavit the FBI filed to support
search warrants for a June 6 raid on the plant.
</TEXT>
