<FIRST>r i AM-DalaiLama     11-30 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama to Meet Top Leaders Over China's Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials will receive the Dalai
Lama after he accepts the Nobel Peace Prize, despite angry demands
from China that Tibet's exiled religious leader be ignored, news
reports said Thursday.
   The Buddhist monk has led a nearly 40-year non-violent struggle
to free Tibet from Chinese occupation.
   He will meet privately with Prime Minister Jan P. Syse and
Foreign Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik on Dec. 11, one day after the
ceremony, according to the national news agency NTB.
   Last year, the government snubbed the Dalai Lama during a visit
because of diplomatic pressure from China.
   China condemned the Norwegian Nobel Committee's Oct. 4
announcement that the Peace Prize had gone to the Dalai Lama, and
accused Norway of interfering in China's internal affairs.
   Beijing later threatened economic sanctions against Norway if
the Dalai Lama was received officially, Norwegian reports said.
   ``It's a well established tradition that any Peace Prize winner
who wants to meet government officials may do so,'' said Janis
Bjoern Kanavin of Norway's foreign ministry.
   The Peace Prize winner ruled the isolated mountain kingdom until
Chinese troops moved in in 1950. He fled into exile in India with
about 100,000 followers in 1959.
</TEXT>
