<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     11-30 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Agency Criticized by Bush Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration sharply criticized a
U.N. agency Thursday for strengthening its cooperation with the
Palestine Liberation Organization and denying a U.S. official the
agency's chairmanship.
   The State Department spokeswoman said that, in light of the
agency's actions, the United States was considering cutting off all
financial support for the Food and Agriculture Organization.
   At a meeting of the FAO's general conference in Rome, 96
countries voted for a resolution authorizing the agency to assist
agricultural development on the West Bank and in Gaza ``in close
cooperation'' with the PLO.
   The resolution accused Israel, which controls the territories,
of hampering economic development and denying land and water to
Palestinian residents.
   ``The outcome of the conference was unacceptable to us for a
number of reasons,'' State Department spokeswoman Margaret D.
Tutwiler said.
   She called the resolution ``extremely objectionable'' and
accused the FAO of lagging behind in reforming its procedures and
expanding its budget at the expense of the United States and a
handful of other countries that bear most of the costs.
   Ms. Tutwiler also said Dan Amstutz of the United States had been
denied his right under a rotation system to serve as chairman of
the FAO council.
   Referring to these actions, the spokeswoman said ``this brings
into serious question our funding of FAO. This is being seriously
discussed here today, but I am not prepared at this briefing to
make an announcement of what action or actions the United States
will be taking.''
   On another Mideast issue, Ms. Tutwiler said Egyptian Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid had informed Secretary of State James
A. Baker III that he could not approve a U.S. proposal for setting
up negotiations between Israel and Palestinians.
   Egypt has been dealing with Baker in behalf of the PLO.
   Evidently, Meguid requested some unspecified changes in the U.S.
approach.
   But Ms. Tutwiler said any ``clarifications'' would be considered
only after Egypt gave its ``yes'' to the U.S. plan.
   The Israeli Cabinet earlier gave its approval, but also stated a
number of reservations. Its main concern is that the PLO not play a
role in the negotiations.
   The PLO, however, is recognized by all Arab countries as the
only legitimate representative of the Palestinians.
</TEXT>
