<FIRST>r a PM-DefectorExpelled 1stLd-Writethru a0482 11-30 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defector Expelled, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Hungary Expels Former CIA Agent Who Defected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs with embassy and Interior Ministry comment;
PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `CIA Director ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A renegade CIA agent who defected to the
Soviet Union after allegedly passing secrets has been expelled from
Hungary, a newspaper reported today.
   It was not known where the defector, Edward Lee Howard, went
after his expulsion, the Los Angeles Times said.
   Howard, who eluded U.S. counterintelligence agents in New Mexico
in 1985, revealed to the Soviets the names of people and technical
equipment being used by the CIA.
   A U.S. official told the Times that federal authorities had been
trying to persuade Hungary to expel Howard for months. The
newspaper said the United States is stepping up its efforts to
apprehend Howard.
   ``Our argument was, `Here's this guy who cast his lot with the
Soviet Union but tried to avoid the hardships of Gulag socialism,'
'' the unidentified official was quoted as saying.
   Hungary revoked his asylum at least a month ago despite protests
by the KGB, the Soviet intelligence agency, according to a U.S.
government source quoted by the newspaper.
   Asked about the report, Hungarian Interior Ministry spokesman
Lt. Col. Janos Horvach said in a telephone interview, ``It's news
to me.''
   The U.S. Embassy said it had no immediate information on the
circumstances surrounding Howard's expulsion, and Soviet Embassy
spokesman Sergei Semyonov said, ``I regret but we know nothing
about such a man.''
   CIA Director William H. Webster made a veiled reference to
Howard's expulsion in a speech Wednesday at the National Press Club
in Washington.
   He was asked about cooperation between intelligence services of
East Bloc countries and the Soviets in light of the recent
political developments in Eastern Europe.
   Webster cited the case of ``a prominent defector from the United
States (who) was permanently expelled from a bloc country which had
provided him comfort and sanctuary in the past. And that would have
been contrary to the wishes of the KGB.''
   David Wise, author of a book documenting Howard's defection,
said Howard spent significant time in Hungary after defecting to
Moscow.
   ``It was a lot more Western _ the closest he could get to the
West,'' Wise said.
   Howard's wife, Mary, who lives in St. Paul, Minn., with the
couple's daughter, had spent up to three months with him in
Hungary, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
