<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Stronghold Bjt   11-30 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Stronghold, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Fight Uphill Battle Against Reform in Industrial Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSTRAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This steel and coal town in
Moravia has always been a Communist Party stronghold, but even new
party leader Karel Urbanek's roots in the region aren't enough to
stem the quest for reform.
   The winds of change are strong even in this major industrial
center, although ``we are always days behind Prague,'' said Dusan
Kubat, a journalist and staunch supporter of the Civic Forum reform
movement.
   Civic Forum was a major force in the pro-democracy
demonstrations that led to the downfall of former party chief Milos
Jakes. He was replaced by Urbanek, who is from Bojkovice, a village
in southern Moravia.
   ``The situation is more complicated here,'' said Kubat, 30.
``People are more conservative. But I think most workers are
already with us.''
   Workers crowding a beer hall appeared to support his assessment.
   ``I am happy that the young ones started the fight,'' said
steelworker Josef Koukl. `` I am already 40 but I would like to
join them. Everybody who has a sense of justice should join them.''
   Stanislav Novak, a 40-year-old father of two, put down his glass
of plum brandy and nodded: ``I would like my children to live in a
better world.''
   The Civic Forum's call for a two-hour general strike Monday was
heeded by most plants here, with at least 20,000 workers taking to
the streets after sirens signaled the start.
   At the Zarubek coal mine, however, the management ``did not let
us gather and waited until the last moment before it allowed a
group of miners to come up to take part in the strike,'' said a
technician met at the gate, who refused to give his name.
   A rumor spread among miners before the strike that participants
would lose their Christmas bonus of up to $900.
   Miners draw up to three times the national worker's pay. Once
they work above ground, however, their wage is slashed
substantially unless they are diagnosed to be suffering from
silicosis. Complaints from their ranks that silicosis victims are
increasingly being refused full pay were cited as a factor
prompting the large miner participation in the strike.
   The local Communist Party organized a rally Wednesday on
Ostrava's People's Militia Square, at which traditional
overall-clad workers were noticeably absent.
   One speaker was worker Jaroslav Cahlik, who called on the Prague
government ``to immediately stop the talks'' with the opposition.
   The mostly middle-aged crowd of about 5,000, including a group
of army officers, broke into chants of ``Long live the Communist
Party. We are still here,'' while a group of about 100 younger
onlookers rose their arms in the ``victory'' sign of the opposition.
   ``They may still be here, but without power,'' said one
bystander.
   Alexandra Hnikova, a 29-year-old textile worker, joined in the
pro-party chants.
   ``I will be with the party no matter what happens,'' she said.
   ``Of course there have been mistakes, but that will change
now,'' she added after a brown-coated man whispered something into
her ear.
   Ostrava has a mining engineering college where students are on
an indefinite strike to press for the resignation of their rector,
an orthodox Communist. The strike is being led by a teacher of
Marxism-Leninism.
   Most of the mines in the region are no longer profitable but the
party has opposed shutting them down for fear of stirring
discontent. Their future is likely to figure in upcoming
discussions about economic reforms.
   ``I am afraid that the economic situation will become worse,''
said mechanic Ladislav Mlynar outside Ostrava's Hotel Atom as smoke
billowed from a nearby blast furnace.
   ``The changes are so fast,'' said passerby Ondreas Imrich. ``I
still fear that everything will end in a dead-end street again or
that it will be suppressed.''
</TEXT>
