<DOCNO> AP891130-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i Summit-Color 1stLd-Writethru a0618 11-30 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>Summit-Color, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short of Flags, but Otherwise Ready, Malta Awaits Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with security details, inserting 2 grafs after 17th
graf pvs, Two small</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long experienced in dealing with
invaders, the Maltese are blocking off roads and mobilizing the
military _ and even the boy scouts _ to get ready for this
weekend's superpower summit. They're also churning out T-shirts.
   Prime Minister Edward Fenech Adami declared his island nation
set for the arrivals Friday of President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev for their talks aboard warships anchored in a
Maltese harbor.
   ``The arrangements have gone beautifully,'' Fenech Adami told a
news conference Thursday.
   Malta's entire 1,200-man military and most of its 1,000 police
officers have been assigned to security tasks for the meeting,
manning roadblocks and checkpoints and making round-the-clock
patrols on land and at sea.
   Even a shortage of tiny, wavable Soviet flags hasn't been enough
to hamper the preparations, said Eddie Stafrace, who reports
selling 160 American and Maltese flags a day from his little toy
store behind the Palace of the Grand Masters in Valletta.
   ``They never sent the Russian ones,'' Stafrace said of his
Italian suppliers. ``When Soviet sailors come ashore, they normally
don't have money and want to exchange. I traded for some pennants
with Gorbachev's face on them. But I've sold all them already.''
   The Maltese government has come up with enough large Soviet and
American flags to decorate the public buildings in Valletta, a
capital of steep narrow streets lined with ocher stone buildings.
   The stark, almost treeless setting could be mistaken for North
Africa, if it weren't for the Christmas decorations strung across
the main shopping streets in this heavily Roman Catholic country.
And the signs in the distinctive Maltese language, influenced by
Arabic, Italian, French and English. St. John Street, for instance,
becomes Triq San Gwann.
   At a shop around the corner from Triq San Gwann and just up from
the deep harbor, Joseph Civelli also had no Soviet flags, but was
making up for it with colorful T-shirts showing Bush and Gorbachev
floating along in separate fishing boats, shaking hands over the
water in front of a Maltese cross.
   ``The whole world is looking at Malta, I think. It's great,''
said Civelli. ``Tell your president to bring peace to the whole
world. We've suffered a lot from wars.''
   Malta's wars began thousands of years ago, with Greeks,
Etruscans, Carthaginians, Romans, Arabs and Normans among the
conquerors.
   In the 16th century, the knights of the Order of St. John _
later known as the Knights of Malta _ built the impressive
fortresses that still dominate Valletta's rocky skyline, and fought
off the Ottoman Turks.
   Napoleon eventually kicked out the Knights of Malta, then Lord
Nelson kicked out the French. Malta was still under British rule
through World War II, during which it survived ferocious bombing to
remain a key Allied outpost in the Mediterranean, just 58 miles
south of Sicily.
   Among the buildings badly damaged by German and Italian bombing
was the 16th century hospital of the Knights of Malta, now rebuilt
into a conference center. Its 530-foot-long Main Ward has been
lined with tables and telephones for the 2,000 journalists
accredited to cover the Gorbachev-Bush encounter from shore.
   Joining them are promoters of Maltese business opportunities
eager to take advantage of the sudden attention _ and a few dozen
khaki-clad scouts given the week off from school to run errands at
the center.
   The Soviet missile cruiser Slava and the USS Belknap, a guided
missile cruiser, are anchored in Marsaxlokk Bay, a harbor at the
southern tip of Malta, about a 30-minute drive from Valletta.
   Two small Maltese patrol boats sailed around the two warships
Thursday, making sure no pleasure boats wandered nearby.
   Troops were stationed at Marsaxlokk to ensure security on land,
and extra helicopter patrols of the area began Thursday, said Brig.
John Spiteri, commander of Malta's armed forces.
   Spiteri, in charge of security for the summit, said Maltese
officers began a thorough search of the airport Thursday in
cooperation with American and Soviet experts. Patrols also watch
the airport perimeter around the clock, he said.
   Some roads are already blocked to traffic, and more will be shut
through the weekend, forcing the Anglican Cathedral in Valletta to
cancel church services this Sunday.
   Still, hundreds of curious tourists and local people have
already made the trek to look out from a once-sleepy fishing
village at the ships bristling with armaments in the harbor.
   With many more rubberneckers expected Saturday and Sunday, the
Maltese government has lined up several local bands and scheduled
fireworks at Marsaxlokk to keep people occupied while they wait for
history to be made offshore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
