<DOCNO> AP891130-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-GreenRiver     11-30 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Law Student Ruled Out as Suspect in Serial Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man once identified as a ``viable suspect'' in
the Green River serial killings is no longer a suspect, the
commander of a task force investigating the slayings said today.
   King County Police Capt. Robert Evans told KING-TV that records
removed from William Jay Stevens II's home and other information
gathered by detectives eliminated Stevens as a suspect.
   Stevens, 39, is in jail awaiting trial on federal firearms
charges involving guns found in a search of his and his parents'
homes in Spokane by the Green River Task Force and Spokane police.
   Stevens, who was arrested in January, was investigated in
connection with the deaths and disappearances of 49 women, most of
them prostitutes, who vanished from 1982 to 1984, mostly in the
Seattle area. The case, named for the river where the first five
victims were found, is the worst known, unsolved serial murder case
in the nation.
   An affidavit filed by the task force to obtain the search
warrant identified Stevens as a ``viable suspect'' in the Green
River slayings.
   Stevens was never charged with any of the killings and has said
he is innocent.
   The search of Stevens' and his parents' homes uncovered guns,
boxes of pornographic tapes, police paraphernalia and uniforms, and
credit card records that helped investigators trace Stevens'
travels.
   They also found a car equipped much like a police cruiser. Green
River investigators have speculated that the Green River killer
posed as a police officer to trap his victims.
   Stevens was indicted in October on charges of being a felon in
possession of a firearm. Stevens, a former law student at Gonzaga
University in Spokane, had escaped from a work-release center in
1981 while serving time for a 1979 burglary at a police equipment
supply company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DebtsForgiven     11-30 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debts Forgiven,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Reap $1.4 Billion Windfall as U.S. Forgives Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California and New York are the biggest
winners, but all states will reap dividends from a decision by
Congress forgiving $1.4 billion in hotly-contested federal
penalties under a huge family aid program.
   The penalties were owed by all 50 states because of alleged
overpayments to beneficiaries under Aid to Families With Dependent
Children, the federal-state welfare program for children who lack
parental financial support.
   About 3.7 million families receive AFDC, the nation's largest
cash assistance program.
   The biggest penalty to be wiped out belonged to California _
$308.7 million, according to Federal Funds Information For States,
a research group. New York owed $285.9 million, Michigan $134.0
million and Ohio $104.6 million.
   No state had avoided the penalties, although South Dakota owed a
just $13,000 and Nevada owed $18,000.
   Forgiving the debts and reforming the way states are penalized
for overpayments ``is extremely significant,'' said Alicia Pelrine
of the National Governors' Association. ``This is something we've
been pushing for for years. It's a tough, technical, gut-it-out
issue,'' she said.
   ``We were delightfully surprised,'' said Jerry Friedman, deputy
secretary for income maintenance at the Department of Public
Welfare of Pennsylvania, which owed $92.3 million.
   ``Obviously if we were forced to pay up, it would have made our
system hemorrhage. It would have been disastrous,'' Friedman said.
He said the state had been preparing to challenge the debt in court.
   The $1.4 billion is an estimate that includes only state
overpayments made from the 1981 through the 1987 fiscal years. When
figures for the 1988 and 1989 fiscal years are totaled, the amount
of forgiveness could run as high as $2.2 billion, according to the
Office of Management and Budget.
   The AFDC amnesty provision was contained in a $14.7 billion
budget bill passed by both houses of Congress last week in the rush
to adjourn before Thanksgiving.
   OMB had backed a cheaper AFDC plan that did not include a full
waiver of states' obligations, according to OMB spokeswoman Delores
Spitznagel. Still, she said, the budget measure is expected to be
signed by the president.
   The revenue losses caused by the amnesty plan are more than
offset in the measure by dozens of deficit-reduction provisions,
including the extension into February of spending cuts imposed in
October under the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law.
   The issue of AFDC overpayments has long caused rancor between
states and the federal government.
   Since federal money is involved, the government monitors the
program and assesses penalties when states accidentally make
overpayments to beneficiaries or grant aid to people who do not
qualify.
   Under program regulations in effect since 1983, any state with
an error rate of 3 percent or above is subject to penalties and
interest.
   But states have long held that the 3 percent ``tolerance level''
is arbitrary and ignores the realities of administering the program.
   States cite compliance figures showing that 41 states could not
manage error rates of less than 3 percent in any year during the
period.
   The new program enacted by Congress eliminates the 3 percent
error rate, replacing it with a 4 percent figure or the national
average, whichever is higher. Penalties would be assessed on a
sliding scale reflecting the degree to which a state's errors
exceed the national rate.
   David Siegel, a spokesman for the Family Support Administration,
the division of the Department of Health and Human Services that
oversees AFDC,_ said Congress apparently decided to give the
program a fresh start.
   ``This gives all levels of government the opportunity to start
with a clean slate and have a quality-control system that is
operational and functional,'' Siegel said.
   The new system begins in October 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1457EST</FILEID>
