<FIRST>r w AM-CocaineExtradition     11-30 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Extradition,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Colombian Cocaine Figure Extradited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The personal pilot of Colombia's alleged
cocaine godfather was extradited to the United States Thursday to
face prosecution in a massive cocaine importation case, the U.S.
Marshals Service said.
   He is the ninth person to be extradited from Colombia since
August when the Colombian government began a new drive against drug
trafficking, said K. Michael Moore, director of the service.
   Moore identified Jorge Mario de la Cuesta as a kingpin of the
Medellin cartel, but he is not one of those on the U.S. Justice
Department's list of the 12 most wanted drug suspects in Colombia.
   According to the Drug Enforcement Administration, as many as 300
Colombians already are under indictment in various U.S. cities on
drug-related charges, although many of the indictments are sealed.
   Jorge Mario de la Cuesta, indicted with four other Medellin
leaders last February, was brought to Jacksonville, Fla., by a team
of the marshals special operations group after being turned over by
Colombian authorities, Moore said. He faces arraignment in U.S.
District Court there.
   At the time of his arrest last month, de la Cuesta was
identified as the pilot of Pablo Escobar, leader of the Medellin
cocaine cartel.
   De la Cuesta and the others were charged in Jacksonville last
Feb. 24 with taking part in a conspiracy that resulted in more than
16 tons of cocaine being smuggled into the United States.
   The indictment accuses de la Cuesta of piloting or being aboard
aircraft that carried more than 9,500 pounds of cocaine from
Colombia to the Bahamas, the marshals service said. From there,
according to the indictment, the cocaine was smuggled into the
United States by plane and boat.
   Others named in the indictment were Carols Lehder, tried,
convicted and now serving a sentence of life-without-parole and 135
years; Pablo Escobar-Gaviria; Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez-Gacha; Jorge
Ochoa-Vasquez and Fabio Ochoa-Vasquez. All except Lehder are
defendants in the case.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh praised Colombian president
Virgilio Barco and his government for their work in the fight
against ``narco-terrorists.''
</TEXT>
