<FIRST>r i AM-India     11-30 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says it Will Seek Coalition Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition politicians said Thursday
they had cleared the way for one of their leaders to become India's
next prime minister.
   The National Front's Parliament members were scheduled to meet
Friday to officially elect Vishwanath Pratap Singh head of the
five-party National Front coalition.
   He then likely would be asked by the president to serve as prime
minister.
   Guruswamy said another contender for the job, Chandra Shekhar,
had been persuaded to withdraw his candidacy, and that no one in
the alliance would contest Singh's nomination.
   Singh, 58, could not be reached for comment Thursday, but he has
insisted he does not want to replace Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
Singh's colleagues said he had no choice, however.
   ``He has to bow to the wishes of the people and the party. He
has no alternative,'' said Mohan Guruswamy, an associate.
   Gandhi resigned Wednesday after his Congress Party failed to win
a majority in last week's parliamentary elections, but President
Ramaswamy Venkataraman asked him to continue until a new government
is formed.
   With results for all but two of the 525 Parliament seats
announced by Thursday night, the Congress Party had won the most
seats at 192. Its small-party allies together won another 17.
   The National Front has 143 seats and has been promised support
by the right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party, which has 90 seats, and
by several left-wing groups, which won 51.
   That would give the centrist National Front 284 seats, more than
the 263 needed for a majority.
   The rest of the seats went to small parties and independents who
have not taken sides.
   Singh, a former defense and finance minister, is the best-known
leader in the National Front. But the mild-mannered politician has
said he just wants to be president of the People's Party, the
largest component of the National Front.
   ``Singh is not sure he will be able to handle a hung house,'' a
senior leader of the National Front said speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``That's why he was so hesitant to become the prime
minister.''
   Another source in the National Front said: ``Singh was told he
has no business to be in politics if he does not seek office.''
   In past elections, one party _ almost always the Congress Party
_ has won a comfortable majority. In the absence of a majority, the
president chooses which party will form a government.
   The Congress Party said on Wednesday that it would not seek the
job.
   The National Front has been dogged by highly publicized internal
feuds since it was formed in August 1988. After elections were
called in October, the front's leaders set aside their differences
and united to oust Gandhi.
   But those differences started to surface this week and a leading
newspaper said Thursday they threaten the Front's chances for
success.
   ``The onus of bringing about a realignment of centrist forces,
once the government formed by the opposition has had the time to
display its ineffectiveness, is squarely with Mr. Gandhi,'' the
independent Times of India said.
</TEXT>
