<FIRST>r a AM-WhooperComeback     11-30 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whooper Comeback,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whooping Cranes Make Remarkable Comeback Following Losses in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKPORT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The endangered whooping crane population,
which suffered devastating losses in 1988, made a remarkable
comeback this year, a wildlife refuge manager says.
   A total of 144 birds have been sighted at the Aransas National
Wildlife Refuge near Rockport, where they spend the winter before
returning to their nesting grounds in Canada's Buffalo National
Park, said Brent Giezentanner, refuge manager.
   ``We're really happy. As a matter of fact, we're ecstatic so
far,'' he said Wednesday.
   Only 138 whooping cranes out of an expected 150 made it to the
refuge last year. Biologists estimated that as many as a dozen
birds may have died after leaving their Canadian habitat.
   One bird was shot by a Houston lawyer, who paid a $15,000 fine,
Giezentanner said.
   A good sign this year is that of the 21 whooping crane chicks
sighted and tagged in Canada, all but one made it to the Texas
refuge.
   The increase in the world's only remaining naturally reproducing
flock of whooping cranes is the result of favorable nesting
conditions in Canada and the fact that many of the birds are
reaching breeding age, Giezentanner said.
</TEXT>
