<FIRST>r a AM-LacklandScandal     11-30 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lackland Scandal,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheating Probe Leads To Dismissal of Military Police Academy Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cheating investigation at the military
Security Police Academy at Lackland Air Force Base has led to the
dismissal of 14 students and charges against one of them and an
instructor, authorities said.
   ``This was the first time there was a suspected compromise (of
tests) of this magnitude,'' said base spokeswoman Delores Schroeder.
   One-third of a law enforcement class at the school, which trains
police for all military branches, was dismissed as a result of the
investigation, the San Antonio Light reported Thursday.
   The investigation started in September when officials looked
into allegations that a Marine instructor had sexual relations with
a female Navy student, who in turn allegedly received test answers
from the instructor.
   The female student allegedly gave the answers to four Navy
colleagues at the academy, authorities said.
   Those four Navy students were dismissed from the academy,
although not from the military. The woman student also was
dismissed from the school, and she and the Marine instructor face
courts-martial, the Light reported. Ms. Schroeder said Thursday
that she didn't know the exact charges that are being brought.
   While investigating that case, Air Force officials uncovered
information about a separate and larger cheating ring.
   ``The two (investigations) are unrelated, other than one
investigation led to another,'' Air Force Lt. Col. Johnny Whitaker
said.
   The instructor probe led investigators to information that nine
other students at the security school had been using workbooks
prepared by upper-classmen as they prepared for their exams.
   Ms. Schroeder said that the practice was not technically
cheating, but is considered unethical, and the students were
dismissed from the school. They, too, will be retrained for other
positions in the military, she said.
   The names of those involved were not immediately released.
   This is the largest cheating case uncovered at the police
academy, although authorities have investigated smaller, isolated
cases of cheating in the past, they said.
</TEXT>
