<FIRST>r a AM-MidnightBasketball     11-30 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midnight Basketball,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Authority Instituting Midnight Basketball for Gang Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's public housing agency wants to defuse
late-night tension in some tough neighborhoods by luring gang
members into a midnight basketball league.
   ``This is for kids who have been written off,'' said Gil Walker,
a Chicago Housing Authority authority staff member and commissioner
of the new league.
   From 10 p.m. until 2 a.m. beginning in January, 150 young men
from 18 to 25 years old will be shooting at baskets.
   The idea is to keep the young men, especially the gang leaders,
off the streets during a dangerous time and give them extra support
and leadership in an effort to steer them straight, Walker said
Wednesday.
   ``This is going to be modeled after the NBA _ uniforms, playoffs
and championships,'' said Walker. ``But also, just like in the NBA,
if somebody has a drug problem, we're going to provide counseling.
Family problems, money problems, education, job training _ we're
going to help.''
   The program also was modeled on one in Glenarden, Md., just
outside Washington, D.C.
   Walker, a former semiprofessional basketball player, said he's
not alarmed by the prospect of rival gang members crowding into a
gym to watch or play.
   ``One thing I've found is that sports transcends gang feuding,''
he said. ``I've seen them lay their pistols down, play basketball,
then pick up their pistols and leave.''
   The authority has come up with $50,000, half from the federal
government, for start-up money and will seek corporate sponsors.
   ``We want to take them away to a resort for three days of
orientation to tell them exactly what we're about,'' Walker said.
   ``And it's not about winning and losing basketball games, but
about building self-esteem and personal pride,'' he said.
   Virginia Peoples, manager of the Rockwell Gardens housing
project, said she expects the program to be popular.
   The image of gang members standing around on the street corner
uninterested in anything but trouble, isn't accurate, Ms. Peoples
said.
   ``Some of the kids in gangs have come to us looking for
employment,'' she said. ``The stereotype isn't totally true.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
