<FIRST>r a AM-Palmer-NBC     11-30 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palmer-NBC,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC News Anchor John Palmer Leaving After 26 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Today'' show news anchorman John Palmer
said Thursday he's leaving NBC News in January to work on a new
syndicated daily half-hour series, ``Only Yesterday,'' that he will
anchor.
   ``I've been with NBC News for 26 years, and it's a little scary
to leave the mother ship,'' he said in an interview. ``But it
presented the kind of challenge that I think we need to do to kind
of shake up our lives a little bit.''
   ``I'm sorry he chose not to stay here,'' NBC News president
Michael Gartner said in a statement. ``I wish him the best. He is a
professional newsman and an extremely nice human being.''
   There has been speculation that Palmer would leave NBC since
September when, as part of a shakeup at ``Today,'' he was replaced
by Deborah Norville as the show's news anchor. He was shifted to
her former anchor job at the earlier ``NBC News at Sunrise.''
   Norville now is scheduled to become ``Today'' co-host in January
when Jane Pauley leaves the show after 13 years. No decision has
been made yet on who will suceed Norville as ``Today'' news anchor.
   Palmer, 54, had been been negotiating to work both as an
anchorman at station WTVJ-TV in Miami, an NBC-owned station, and as
a Miami-based Latin American correspondent for NBC News.
   But about 10 days ago, he said, he got a call from former ABC
News executive Av Westin, creator of the New York-based
newsmagazine series he will now anchor. Westin now is senior vice
president of reality-based programming for King World Productions.
   Palmer quoted Westin as saying, ``This is a wrist-grabbing call.
... Don't sign anything, I want to talk to you.''
   Their talks led to his decision to leave NBC for ``Only
Yesterday,'' which he said still is under development. The series
will look at both recent news developments and moments in
contemporary history and try to put them into perspective, he said.
   King World, which will produce and sell the series, syndicates
the successful ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy'' game shows and
the Oprah Winfrey talk show.
   No decision has been made on Palmer's successor at ``NBC News at
Sunrise,'' an NBC spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
