<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1926EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial     11-30 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Experts Mixed on Usefulness of Sedition Tactic After Mistrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury's rejection of
seditious conspiracy charges against three radicals may signal that
the little-used prosecution tactic will remain that way, a
constitutional scholar said.
   Others cautioned that the loss may be a setback, but won't stop
future sedition prosecutions.
   The nearly yearlong trial of Raymond Levasseur, his wife,
Patricia, and Richard Williams ended in a mistrial Wednesday after
the jury deadlocked on whether the three's alleged bombing exploits
constituted racketeering. Prosecutors said they may decide Friday
whether to retry the unresolved charges.
   On Monday, the jury issued a partial verdict clearing the three
on the sedition charges that they plotted to overthrow the
government.
   Arthur Kinoy, a constitutional law expert at Rutgers University,
interpreted that as a serious blow to the prosecution tactic of
filing seditious conspiracy charges.
   ``I think there were defense lawyers definitely watching who
will use (the Springfield case) as a very strong indication that
the seditious conspiracy technique has got to be totally
abandoned,'' Kinoy said. ``I think the jury was reacting in a very
fundamental and positive way to the basic constitutional
protections of the people of this country in the exercise of their
First Amendment rights.''
   William M. Kunstler, a defense lawyer who has been active in
supporting radical causes, called the jury's decision ``a big
setback'' for prosecutors, adding that it was ``a deserved one
because what they've been doing for a long time is prosecuting
revolutionary people in a far different way than anybody else, than
murderers, thieves and so on.''
   Prosecutors had claimed that the defendants belonged to a band
of terrorists who conspired to commit bombings and bank robberies
along the East Coast from 1976 to 1984 in a plot to overthrow the
government.
   The seditious conspiracy charges trace their roots to the
prosecution of Confederate spies in the Civil War era. The Sedition
Act of 1918 was used against war protesters in World War I and to
prosecute Puerto Rican nationalists in 1950. In April 1988, nine
white supremacists were acquitted of seditious conspiracy in
Arkansas.
   Prosecutors wouldn't comment on how they interpreted the
Springfield verdict.
   Elizabeth Fink, a member of the defense team, said, ``I think
they're going to give it up for a while. I think we dealt them a
stunning and complete defeat.''
   Still, Fink and retired Boston University Professor Howard Zinn,
an expert on revolutionary history, said they don't expect the
government to abandon seditious conspiracy.
   ``I'm not saying they'll use it tomorrow. But they're there as
handy weapons for them to use whenever they want to repress,'' Zinn
said.
   Meanwhile, U.S. Attorney Wayne Budd was deciding Thursday
whether to try again on the unresolved racketeering charges. A
statement may be made Friday, spokeswoman Susan Spurlock said. A
hearing is scheduled Jan. 5 in Boston to formally decide the
disposition of the case.
   Jurors had also cleared Mrs. Levasseur of a charge of
racketeering. They deadlocked on two counts of racketeering against
the two men and counts of racketeering conspiracy against all
three. Each count carries a maximum penalty of 20 years and $20,000
in fines.
   While admitting nothing, the defense had said that prosecution
was pointless since Levasseur and Williams were already serving
lengthy sentences for convictions on some of the bombings. Mrs.
Levasseur was free on bail after serving 3{ years of a 5-year
sentence for harboring a fugitive, her husband.
   The indictments were issued in May 1986 and the three defendants
were all that remained of an original group of eight. Jury
selection began in March 1988 and the actual trial began in
January. Estimates of the cost ranged from $2 million to $10
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1640EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-RedArmyFaction     11-30 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Red Army Faction,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Army Terrorist Group Has Left Bloody Trail for Two Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Banker, AM-Obit-Herrhausen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Army Faction has gained notoriety as
one of Europe's deadliest leftist terrorist groups in two decades
of bloody attacks on West German and American targets.
   Prosecutors said the group claimed responsibility for the bomb
attack Thursday morning that killed Alfred Herrhausen, chairman of
Deutsche Bank _ West Germany's largest _ and one of Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's closest economic advisers.
   The Red Army Faction, which had been relatively inactive the
past three years, began operating in the late 1960s. It was known
then as the Baader-Meinhof gang, named after its founders Andreas
Baader and Ulrike Meinhof.
   It gained a reputation as a brutal, well-organized group that
struck at the heart of West Germany's industrial and economic power
by targeting leading managers for assassinations.
   American military targets have also come under Red Army Faction
attacks in the group's ``anti-imperialist struggle.''
   Most of the original Red Army Faction leaders have been killed
by police or have died in prison. Authorities say the group is now
believed to consist of a core of 20 to 30 members.
   The group's first action came in April 1968 with arson attacks
on two Frankfurt department stores.
   The group changed its name to the Red Army Faction in 1971 and a
series of assassinations and bomb attacks followed.
   On May 11, 1972, five bombs exploded at the U.S. Army's 5th
Corps headquarters in Frankfurt, killing an American officer and
injuring 13 other people.
   On May 25, 1972, three U.S. soldiers were killed and five
injured when a powerful bomb left in a parked car ripped through a
parking lot at the U.S. Army's European headquarters in Heidelberg.
The Red Army Faction claimed responsibility.
   In April 1975, Red Army Faction terrorists occupied the West
German Embassy in Stockholm in an attempt to free imprisoned fellow
terrorists. Two diplomats and two terrorists died in an explosion
during the siege.
   The year 1977 is remembered as a particularly bloody period,
when Red Army Faction attacks shook the foundations of West
Germany's society.
   That year, the group assassinated chief state prosecutor
Siegfried Buback; kidnapped and killed the head of the employer's
association, Hanns-Martin Schleyer; and killed Juergen Ponto, head
of the Dresdner Bank, one of the county's three big banks.
   A Lufthansa jet was also hijacked to Somalia in an attempt to
force authorities to free jailed Red Army Faction leaders. A West
German commando team stormed the jetliner to end the siege.
   A few hours later, Red Army Faction leaders Baader, Jan-Carle
Raspe and Gudrun Ensslin committed suicide in Stuttgart's
top-security prison of Stammheim, where they were serving life
sentences. Meinhof had committed suicide in prison a year earlier.
   Even with the deaths of the group's most notorious leaders, the
attacks did not cease.
   In August 1981, 20 people were injured in a car-bomb attack on
the U.S. Air Force headquarters in Ramstein. Two weeks later, U.S.
Gen. Frederik Kroesen, commander of U.S. Army Europe, narrowly
escaped assassination in Heidelberg when his car was attacked by
rockets.
   On Feb. 1, 1985, Munich industrialist Ernst Zimmermann was shot
and killed at his home by two terrorists.
   On Aug. 8, 1985, a car bomb killed two U.S. Air Force personnel
at the Rhein-Main Air Base outside Frankfurt and injured 20 others.
A U.S. soldier had been killed a day earlier in Wiesbaden, and the
Red Army Faction claimed responsibility for both attacks.
   In July 1986, Red Army Faction terrorists killed industrialist
Karl Heinz Beckurts near Munich, and in October that year, diplomat
Gerold von Braunmuehl was shot and killed on a street in Bonn.
   Authorities say about 60 people, including terrorists, have been
killed since the Red Army Faction began its terrorist campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
