<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSPlay-Fire     11-30 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Play-Fire,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire At AIDS Play Opponent's Home Ruled Accidental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that damaged the home of a state
legislator and leading opponent of a university play about AIDS and
homosexuality was accidental, investigators said Thursday.
   Fireplace embers dumped in the back yard Wednesday night by one
of Rep. Jean Dixon's children ignited leaves and scrap wood and
spread to the home, causing an estimated $5,000 to $10,000 damage,
Chief Fire Marshal Dale Bittle said.
   Mrs. Dixon, a Republican, was among the most vocal opponents of
the play, ``The Normal Heart,'' which was presented Nov. 15-20 at
Southwest Missouri State University in Springfield. She objected to
the use of a public facility for a play that presents homosexuality
as an acceptable lifestyle.
   On Nov. 15, a fire destroyed the home of a student who led a
campaign in support of the play. Investigators blamed arson, but no
arrests have been made.
   Supporters of the play, which sold out quickly amid the
controversy, had accused Mrs. Dixon of censorship and said the
production helped educate students about AIDS.
