<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     11-30 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Largest Group of Volunteers Repatriated to Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered jet carrying 130 Vietnamese who
volunteered to return to the Communist homeland they fled flew for
Hanoi on Thursday amid signs that many more boat people may soon be
repatriated against their will.
   The sixth and largest batch of Vietnamese to voluntarily return
home included nine babies who were born in Hong Kong. The total
number to return home since the first flight in March is 637.
   The voluntary repatriation program, which is sponsored by the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, has only attracted a
small fraction of the nearly 57,000 Vietnamese languishing in Hong
Kong, where they are seeking asylum after fleeing their homeland by
boat.
   About 44,000 of the Vietnamese arrived after June 1988, when
Hong Kong adopted a policy that treats all arriving boat people as
illegal immigrants subject to repatriation unless they can prove
they fled political or religious persecution.
   Boat people denied refugee status may soon be sent back to
Vietnam forcibly. British Foreign Minister Francis Maude said the
program of mandatory repatriation will start before the next
sailing season begins in February or March.
