<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MallickBankruptcy     11-30 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mallick Bankruptcy,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friend Of Former House Speaker Wright Files For Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman whose financial
relationship with former U.S. House Speaker Jim Wright was
investigated by a congressional ethics committee has filed for
protection under federal bankruptcy law.
   Fort Worth developer George Mallick listed debts of $12.2
million and assets of $533,626 in the petition filed Wednesday in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   Mallick and his wife, Marlene, filed under Chapter 7 provisions
of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, which allow a debtor's unprotected
assets to be liquidated to pay creditors.
   Mallick's $500,000 home and $30,000 worth of personal
possessions are exempt from seizure, said Mallick's attorney, Henry
Simon Jr.
   With those exemptions, the 177 creditors listed in the
bankruptcy filing are likely to receive ``virtually nothing,''
Mallick told the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
   Mallick, 55, said the Texas oil and real estate busts took his
fortune, just like those of the Hunt brothers and former Gov. John
Connally. ``My economic fate was set, as was everybody else's, when
oil prices went to $10 in 1986. We all got caught,'' he said.
   Mallick estimated his net worth peaked at $7 million in 1982.
Although he has focused on real estate, he also once had oil
holdings worth about $1.5 million.
   More than 80 percent of Mallick's debt is in three large loans
for real estate developments, including $6.2 million owed to NCNB
Texas for financing on a $10 million office tower in Fort Worth.
   Mallick is one of Wright's closest friends. The longtime
congressman from Fort Worth resigned in June after a House ethics
committee said he committed 69 ethics violations, most involving
business and book deals.
   Among other issues, the committee questioned Wright's business
dealings with Mallick in a partnership called Mallightco.
   The committee said there was ``reason to believe'' that Wright
had improperly accepted nearly $145,000 in gifts from Mallick and
failed to report them.
   Most of the money came from an $18,000 annual salary to the
speaker's wife, Betty, over four years. It also included use of a
car, a condominium and an apartment.
   At the time, Mallick denied the partnership was a device to
funnel money to Wright and said Mrs. Wright had earned her pay.
   This week, Mallick said his Chapter 7 filing does not involve
Wright, Mrs. Wright or Mallightco, which is now controlled by one
of Mallick's daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
