<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Cambodia     11-30 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Cambodia,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Members Want No Role For Khmer Rouge In Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of 203 members of the House
and Senate on Thursday expressed concern to Secretary of State
James A. Baker III over reports of U.S. support for a Khmer Rouge
role in a transitional government in Cambodia.
   In a letter signed by 177 House members and 26 senators, timed
to coincide with President Bush's depature for the Malta summit
with Soviet President Gorbachev, the lawmakers said they would
``welcome some clarification'' about U.S. policy toward Cambodia.
The civil war there is one of several regional conflicts to be
addressed at the summit.
   The Khmer Rouge, blamed for the deaths of more than a million
Cambodians during its rule of the country in the 1970s, is the
strongest of the factions engaged in a civil war against the Phnom
Penh government.
   The United States is supporting other, non-communist rebel
groups as Cambodia's future leaders. But Baker reportedly has
explored giving the Khmer Rouge a minimal role in a transitional
government to break a diplomatic deadlock there.
   ``We are concerned that any U.S. effort directly or indirectly
to promote a power-sharing role for the Khmer Rouge _ no matter how
minimal _ would represent an implicit legitimization of a movement
the world finds abhorrent and would constitute a profound shift in
our policy,'' stated the letter, circulated by Rep. Chet Atkins,
D-Mass.
   The letter was signed by members of the House and Senate
leadership and numerous committee chairmen, and included House
Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and Senate Majority Whip
Alan Cranston, D-Calif.
</TEXT>
