<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Race     11-30 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Race,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hepatitis B Four Times as Common Among Blacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first nationwide scientific survey for
hepatitis B infection shows the infectious liver disease is four
times as common among blacks as whites, the national Centers for
Disease Control reported Thursday.
   In a survey of more than 14,000 people over five years, 4.8
percent showed signs in blood tests of having been infected with
hepatitis B virus some time during their lives. Among blacks, 13.7
percent tested positive, compared with 3.2 percent among whites.
   Previous studies, including checks of blood samples given by
blood donors, have pointed to an increased hepatitis B rate among
blacks. But this study is the first among a statistically
representative sample of people in the United States, said Dr.
Miriam Alter, a CDC hepatitis specialist.
   The survey was conducted in the years 1976-1980 by the CDC's
National Center for Health Statistics, but the results were
reported Thursday for the first time. The CDC gave no explanation
for the delay.
   Blacks' increased likelihood of getting hepatitis B sometime
during their lives was especially evident in test results for
people 65-74. In that age group, 39.6 percent of blacks had had
hepatitis B infections, compared with 6.9 percent of whites.
   Hepatitis B is transmitted in ways somewhat similar to AIDS _
through sexual intercourse or direct contact with blood. Infections
can cause inflammation of the liver, jaundice and flu-like
symptoms. The disease can be prevented by a vaccine developed in
1982.
   Researchers believe as many as half the people infected with
hepatitis B never suffer severe symptoms and never know they are
infected.
   The CDC did not speculate on reasons for the increased
prevalence of hepatitis B among blacks, but the Atlanta-based
agency did say that the traditional targets for hepatitis B
vaccinations _ health workers who handle blood, dialysis patients
and some institutionalized people _ may be the wrong targets.
   Given the high prevalence of hepatitis B infections among blacks
and a trend toward infection during adolescence, ``immunization of
the traditionally targeted risk groups will not markedly affect the
spread of infection in the United States,'' the CDC said.
   ``Immunization programs need to include adolescents and young
adults,'' the agency said.
   The CDC noted that survey findings showing higher rates of
active infection for people in the 12-24 age group, compared with
children under 11.
   Twenty thousand hepatitis B cases have been reported in the
United States this year; many cases go unreported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
