<FIRST>r p AM-Bagert-Senate     11-30 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bagert-Senate,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Legislator Announces Senate Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. Ben Bagert, a veteran
legislator who switched to the Republican Party in February,
announced Thursday he will challenge incumbent Democrat J. Bennett
Johnston for the U.S. Senate next year.
   Bagert, of New Orleans, is the second Republican candidate to
join the race against Johnston, who is seeking his fourth term in
1990. Secretary of State Fox McKeithen, who switched this year to
the GOP, announced his bid last month.
   Bagert said, in making his announcement, that Johnston had not
put Louisiana's interests first.
   ``Senators we send to Congress seem to get so wrapped up with
the strange world of Washington, they lose touch with the people
who sent them,'' Bagert said. ``And nowhere in this country is a
senator more a stranger to his home state than J. Bennett Johnston
is to Louisiana.''
   Bagert described himself as a conservative reformer and
supporter of lower taxes, cutting government spending and tough
drug laws and environmental legislation.
   Bagert also criticized Johnston, chairman of the Senate Energy
Committee, for working for a bill to build pipelines to transport
coal slurry _ coal mixed with water to make it easy to move by
pipeline _ instead of lines for Louisiana natural gas.
   Tony Garrett, a spokesman for Johnston, responded that the coal
slurry pipelines were designed to export coal and Louisiana ports
could benefit.
   He added that Johnston was not available to comment directly
because he was on a tour of the state, proving that he was not out
of touch with the people.
</TEXT>
