<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--CalifSalesTax     11-30 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Calif Sales Tax,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rate Rises One-Fourth Cent Friday for Quake Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beginning Friday, California shoppers
have to dig one-quarter of one percent deeper into their
pocketbooks to help pay for earthquake relief.
   The quarter-cent-per-dollar sales tax increase was approved in
the Legislature's November special session and lasts until Dec. 31,
1990.
   The extra revenue is expected to total $800 million over the
next 13 months. The extra tax was timed to take advantage of the
two year-end holiday retail sales surges.
   Most of the money it raises will help pay for rebuilding roads,
bridges and public buildings damaged in the earthquake that struck
the San Francisco area Oct. 17.
   For most counties in the state, the new sales and use tax rate
will be 6.25 percent.
   However, voters in 13 counties, including Los Angeles,
Sacramento and San Francisco, had previously approved half-cent
sales tax increases, so their new rate is 6.75 percent. Five
counties, including San Diego, have had two such local increases,
so their rate is 7.25 percent.
   The Legislature agreed to the tax increase in a special session
called by Gov. George Deukmejian, rejecting arguments from some
legislators that state surplus funds, instead of a tax increase,
should go to quake relief and arguments from the other side that
the quarter-cent hike was not enough.
  
</TEXT>
