<FIRST>r w AM-Riegle-LincolnS&amp;L     11-30 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riegle-Lincoln S&amp;L,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riegle Hires Attorney In Ethics Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Donald Riegle has hired a lawyer who
briefly worked for Oliver North in the Iran-contra affair to
represent Riegle in the probe of his role in the nation's biggest
savings and loan failure.
   Riegle, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, and four other
senators met with federal regulators on behalf of the failed
California thrift in 1987 _ two years before it was seized by the
government. Lincoln's owner, Charles H. Keating Jr., and his
associates made large campaign contributions to all five. Riegle
received $78,250 but returned it in 1988.
   Riegle has retained Washington lawyer Thomas Green to represent
him before the Senate ethics committee, which announced this month
it had hired an outside counsel to determine whether a full-scale
probe of the senators' conduct was justified.
   Green, 48, is a former assistant U.S. attorney general for the
District of Columbia.
   He represented North, a retired Marine lieutenant colonel and
former White House aide, in the early stages of the Iran-contra
case. Other Green clients for a short time were Albert Hakim and
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord, key figures in the
arms-for-hostages scandal.
   Green dropped North's case after an incident involving
classified documents given North by his secretary, Fawn Hall, who
had smuggled them out of the White House.
   Green later refused to testify to a grand jury about the
incident on grounds of attorney-client privilege and Fifth
Amendment protections.
   Riegle repeatedly has denied any wrongdoing in the Lincoln
Savings &amp; Loan affair. In an interview Wednesday, he voiced
confidence that the ethics probe would find that his conduct had
been ``entirely proper.''
</TEXT>
