<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0649 11-30 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0856</SECOND>
<HEAD>New President Wants to Recover Palace From Aoun Without Bloodshed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 18th pvs `Aoun rejected...' to ADD Washington
comment supporting Hrawi. Picks up graf 19 pvs, `Syria has ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New President Elias Hrawi vowed Thursday
to recover the presidential palace and other government
institutions from a defiant Christian Gen. Michel Aoun, but said he
would try to avoid bloodshed.
   He spoke at a news conference as hundreds of Syrian army trucks
carried supplies to frontline positions in south Beirut and in
mountains east and northeast of the capital.
   ``The Syrian troops are in combat formations. Their command is
supplying them with ammunition enough to last for quite a long
time,'' according to a military source in Moslem west Beirut.
   Preparations for a final showdown to oust Aoun from the
presidential palace in suburban Baabda have been afoot all week.
   Syrian troops and armor began rolling in Monday, strengthening
forces along the front lines after Aoun rejected Hrawi's election
Nov. 24 and subsequent presidential decrees dismissing the general
as army commander and disbanding his interim military Cabinet.
   Israel radio reported Aoun has requested military support from
the commander of Israel's surrogate militia in south Lebanon, Gen.
Antoine Lahd, but that Israel rejected the appeal.
   Lahd commands the Israeli-backed, 2,500-man South Lebanon Army
militia, which patrols a buffer zone Israel maintains in Lebanon,
ostensibly to protect its northern border against guerrilla attacks.
   Aoun aides had no immediate comment on the report.
   ``I will resort to all possible means to regain the state
institutions from those who control them,'' Hrawi, a Maronite
Catholic, said at the news conference in Ablah, an army barracks in
the Syrian-policed Bekaa valley.
   Hrawi moved to an officer's residence at the Ablah barracks
Wednesday pending settlement of the dispute over the presidential
palace.
   Hrawi accused Aoun, also a Maronite, of ``partitioning
Lebanon,'' adding that he ``has hope in our armed forces to reunite
the nation.''
   ``I don't want bloodshed, either in (Christian) east Beirut or
in west Beirut. ... I'll use all possible means to reunite the
country,'' he said.
   He urged all 42,000 Lebanese army soldiers to be ``at the
disposal of your new commander, Adm. Emile Lahoud,'' who was
appointed Tuesday to replace Aoun as army commander. About 20,000
soldiers remain loyal to Aoun, and the others, mainly Moslem units,
have accepted Lahoud as commander.
   Addressing Aoun and his supporters, Hrawi said: ``You have
killed the president of the republic and attacked the residences
and property of parliamentary deputies. These attacks will not go
unpunished.''
   Hrawi's predecessor, President Rene Mouawad was killed by a bomb
in west Beirut on Nov. 22, 17 days after his election.
   Syria and its allies blamed Aoun for the killing, but he denied
the charge.
   The homes of at least six Christian parliamentarians were
destroyed by bombs in the Christian enclave after Parliament
approved a peace plan to end 14 years of civil war at a special
session in the Saudi Arabian resort Taif in October.
   Aoun rejected the accord because it did include a timetable for
a Syrian troop withdrawal.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said the United States has contacted the Lebanese government, key
European allies, Arab friends, the Soviet Union and Syria to
express support for Hrawi and ``our wish that the process of
reconciliation continue through peaceful means.''
   She also said Thursday that U.S. officials believe Aoun should
``step aside in favor of Lebanon's constitutionally sanctioned
government.''
   Syria has 40,000 troops controlling 70 percent of Lebanese
territory. They moved in under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate, but later became the Moslems' main backers.
   Aoun fought the Syrians for six months this year. An Arab League
cease-fire halted hostilities in September.
   Hrawi said Lebanon's interest would ``best be preserved by
implementing the Taif accord,'' which mainly redistributes power
equally between Christians and Moslems.
   France, the Christians' main protector, on Thursday ordered the
amphibious troop ship, Orace, to sail from Toulon toward Lebanon to
be ready to evacuate French nationals should the security situation
deteriorate. There are 6,000 French nationals in Lebanon, many of
them Lebanese with dual nationality.
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, said France has
``contradicting'' policies toward Lebanon.
   ``On the one hand, France declares support for the legitimate
Lebanese authorities, and on the other it does not miss a chance to
show its muscles in the face of the legitimate authorities,'' he
said.
   France had supported Hrawi's election and backed the Arab
League-brokered Taif accord, but 33 right-wing French
parliamentarins visited Lebanon on Wednesday and declared support
for Aoun.
   In Israel, Cabinet Minister Roni Milo said Israel was carefully
following developments in Lebanon after Syrian troop buildups
against Aoun the past few days.
   A Moslem government official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said: ``The next 48 hours will be decisive. They will
determine whether Aoun will be dealt with politically or
militarily.''
</TEXT>
