<FIRST>r w AM-IndependentBroadcasters     11-30 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Independent Broadcasters,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Stations Group Names New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James B. Hedlund has been named president of
the Association of Independent Television Stations, replacing
Preston Padden, who has resigned, the association said Thursday.
   Padden, who announced earlier he was becoming senior vice
president, affiliates, for the Fox Broadcasting Co., will remain
with the association until the beginning of the year, INTV Chairman
John A. Serrao said.
   Hedlund, who joined the lobbying organization in 1983, most
recently has been its vice president for government relations. He
will resume his new duties immediately.
   The Milwaukee native formerly was vice president for government
relations at the National Cable Television Association, the cable
industry's representative in Washington.
   Hedlund also has held positions at the White House Office of
Management and Budget, the Department of Housing and Urban
Development and the House Budget Committee.
   Hedlund faces a full plate of issues as INTV president,
including the organization's campaign to stem the movement of
sports to cable TV and efforts to work out an agreement with cable
representatives on what over-the-air stations must be carried by
cable systems and where the stations are positioned on the TV dial.
   Padden was unsuccessful in reaching a ``must carry'' agreement
with NCTA this year.
   INTV represents more than 180 TV stations nationwide that are
not affiliated with the ABC, CBS or NBC television networks.
