<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury that convicted Rep. Donald Lukens
for having sex with an underage girl should have been allowed to
review her school and juvenile records, the congressman's attorney
told an appeals court Thursday.
   The prosecution contended that the girl's past was irrelevant to
the case against the 58-year-old Republican.
    After hearing 40 minutes of argument in Lukens' bid to overturn
the conviction, a three-judge panel of the 10th Ohio District Court
of Appeals took the case under advisement. It could take several
months for the court to rule.
   Lukens was convicted May 26 in Franklin County Domestic
Relations Court on a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the
unruliness of Rosie Coffman. She testified that in November 1988,
when she was 16, Lukens paid her to have sex with him at his
Columbus apartment.
   Judge Ronald Solove would not let Lukens' attorney, Thomas
Tyack, introduce Ms. Coffman's school and juvenile records into
evidence at the trial.
   Tyack said he has not seen the girl's juvenile record, but it
would have given the court a chance to determine Ms. Coffman's
credibility and motive. He said her school records show she had a
tendency to fantasize, often defied authority and had exhibited
psychological problems.
   He also argued that Solove's instacross the three branches of the
federal government; and not unreasonably restrictive so as to
discourage able citizens from entering public service.''
