<SECOND>AM-Angola-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department: US Not Acting Like Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs with Wolpe comment after 9th graf pvs, The Angolan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department denied on Thursday that
the crash of a CIA plane in Angola indicated the United States was
acting like the Nicaraguan government it has accused of helping
leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler refused to confirm
publicly, as other officials have said privately, that the plane
was on a covert CIA mission to resupply Angolan rebels.
   However, she responded to suggestions at a news briefing of a
parallel between the crash and a similar incident over the weekend
involving equipment that U.S. and Salvadoran officials say had been
earmarked by Nicaragua for leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   ``I would point out to you the fact that there is a regional
peace agreement signed by Nicaragua, committing the signatories not
to support subversion of neighboring countries. The Nicaraguans are
clearly violating this obligation,'' she said.
   This was a reference to the twin-engined Cessna that went down
last Saturday in El Salvador while carrying surface-to-air missiles
and other equipment. The Salvadoran government and the State
Department charged that the plane originated in Nicaragua but
Sandinista authorities denied that.
   On Wednesday, U.S. officials said an L-100 cargo plane flying
from a military base in Zaire crashed while carrying supplies to
rebels fighting Angola's leftist government.
   They said a huge fireball was created on impact, suggesting that
the plane was carrying large quantities of weapons.
   The State Department said all four Americans on board are
believed to have died. The plane crashed not far from the UNITA
rebel headquarters in southeastern Angola.
   The Angolan government issued a statement Wednesday confirming
the crash but gave no new details. U.S. officials, noting that the
crash took place in rebel-held territory, said it was doubtful the
Angolan government had any independent information about the
incident.
   The chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Africa subcommittee,
Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., said he hoped the crash and its
``wholly unnecessary loss of lives'' would prompt the Bush
administration to reconsider its policy of supplying weapons to
UNITA.
   Covert U.S. support for the war ``runs counter to our diplomatic
efforts'' in the region and undermines the credibility of both the
United States and Zaire when they seek peaceful solutions to the
conflict, Wolpe said.
   Improving U.S.-Soviet relations have provided new opportunities
for diplomacy around the world, Wolpe noted. But he added: ``I
don't think our policy in Angola has caught up with the changing
dynamic.''
   The Angolan statement used the occasion of the crash to accuse
UNITA of showing no interest in a peaceful settlement to their
14-year old conflict.
   The statement said that the country's Roman Catholic bishops had
indicated support for the UNITA position by calling for a
cease-fire and free elections, but that the plane incident showed
who really wanted peace in Angola.
   The Bush administration also has been an advocate of free
elections as the best hope for a peaceful outcome in Angola.
   U.S. officials said that President Bush, in his discussions with
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev this weekend, is expected to
press for that option rather than engage in debate over aid levels
to the opposing factions in Angola.
   According to some estimates, the Soviets have been providing
$800 million a year to the Angolans while U.S. assistance for the
rebel forces is said to be in the $40 million to $50 million range.
</TEXT>
