<FIRST>r w AM-Satellite'sDemise 1stLd-Writethru a0629 11-30 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellite's Demise, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Now Expected to Fall to Earth Friday Night</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Rephrases last graf to say satellite slowed by atmosphere, pulled
in by gravity.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solar Maximum satellite lost about 20
miles altitude in a 24-hour period Thursday, prompting the U.S.
Space Command to predict that it will fall to Earth about 10:45
p.m. EST on Friday.
   Most of the satellite will burn up in the atmosphere but up to a
dozen larger pieces, weighing up to 100 pounds, may survive.
Officials weren't ready to say in what part of the satellite's
track they might come to Earth.
   ``We can't predict because there is about a six-hour margin of
error in our calculations,'' said Capt. Thomas Niemann, spokesman
for the space command. ``That's four orbits of Earth.''
   More than 80 percent of the satellite's path is over water and
the chances of debris hitting anyone are considered remote. The
only parts of the United States under Solar Max's ground track are
South Florida and the extreme southern parts of Texas, and Hawaii.
   Solar Max, which has been studying the sun for nearly 10 years,
exhausted its positioning fuel recently and has been tumbling. Its
electricity-producing solar panels and antenna were jettisoned by
radioed command late last week.
   On Thursday, Solar Max was orbiting the globe every 88.4
minutes. When that period is down to 87.5 minutes, the satellite
will be near enough to be slowed by the thickening atmosphere and
pulled in by gravity.
</TEXT>
