<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-HeartAttacks     11-30 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Heart Attacks,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Addicts Risk Heart Attacks Even After Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine addicts are in danger of suffering
heart attacks even for a few weeks after they stop taking the drug,
a group of Los Angeles researchers reported.
   Researchers from the West Los Angeles Veterans Administration
and UCLA report that the effects of cocaine may linger after
withdrawal, altering the balance of chemicals in the brain that
direct the cardiovascular system.
   Other scientists studying how cocaine affects the heart said the
report offers ``compelling'' evidence of the risk of heart attacks
and may have implications for drug treatment.
   The report appears in the Philadelphia-based journal Annals of
Internal Medicine in the issue being published Friday.
   Young abusers often experience fatal heart attacks while using
cocaine. The 1986 deaths of University of Maryland basketball star
Len Bias and Cleveland Browns football player Don Rogers were both
ascribed to cocaine-induced heart failure.
   But the Los Angeles study, which measured the heart function of
21 men who were in a substance abuse treatment program, discovered
that addicts may experience abnormal heart activity for as long as
four weeks after quitting cocaine.
   The report's lead author, Dr. Koonlawee Nademanee of the VA
medical center, warned that the first few weeks after withdrawal
are crucial.
   ``I feel that during withdrawal, patients should be carefully
monitored. The most important thing is to make sure the patient is
completely abstinent from the drug,'' he said.
   The researchers found that eight of the 21 subjects had episodes
of abnormal blood flow to the heart. They speculated that cocaine
had upset the balance of chemicals in the brain that prevent the
arteries from undergoing spasms, making heart attacks more likely.
   A heart attack causes the death of part of the heart muscle. It
occurs when arteries that are narrowed or blocked keep a section of
the heart from getting enough oxygen, which is carried in the blood.
   Cocaine restricts blood supply to the heart while increasing the
heart rate, blood pressure and demand for oxygen.
   ``This is the strongest evidence to date that cocaine may cause
spasming of the coronary arteries,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Isner, a
cardiovascular medicine professor at Boston's Tufts University.
``This really is incontrovertible evidence,'' he said, calling the
study a ``spectacular report.''
   But Douglas Wilkerson, who studies the cardiovascular effects of
cocaine at the Medical College of Ohio, cautioned that researchers
do not have enough evidence to attribute the heart attacks to
spasms of the arteries.
   Some scientists argue that the heart attacks could be caused
instead by clots forming in the arteries or simply by blood flow
inadequate to the heart's demand, he said.
   One member of the Los Angeles group, Dr. David Gorelick, now
with the National Institute of Drug Abuse, said the group ruled out
heart disease as the cause of the temporary heart abnormalities in
the subjects.
   ``With longer periods of abstinence from cocaine, the (blood
flow) went back to normal,'' he said.
   The report has immediate impact on how emergency room physicians
will treat addicts experiencing chest pains, according to Dr.
William Spivey, chief of emergency room research at the Medical
College of Pennsylvania.
   ``It's going to make us realize that we're going to have
problems (after withdrawal) with these cocaine addicts,'' said
Spivey.
   The study ``opens our eyes'' to the value of preventive medical
treatment for addicts withdrawing from cocaine, said Dr. Gary
Schaer, a cardiologist at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical
Center in Chicago.
   An estimated 25 million Americans have used cocaine at least
once, including 6 million regular users and 1 million addicts,
according to Isner.
   Gorelick said the Los Angeles scientists now plan to focus on
how cocaine use alters the chemicals in the brain to reduce the
flow of blood to the heart and use other, more precise tests to
examine heart function in cocaine addicts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
