<FIRST>u a AM-RadarBlocked     11-30 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radar Blocked,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Airport Hotel Has Grand Opening, Radar Dispute Renewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotel built too close to an airport
radar because of a typographical error had its grand opening
Thursday, renewing air traffic controllers' complaints that it
blocks some radar coverage.
   The controllers dispute the government's claim that keeping
planes at high altitudes above the blind spot is a temporary
solution.
   ``It's just as bad if not worse,'' said Cheryl Readio, a member
of the National Air Traffic Controllers Association. ``We still
can't see airplanes in that area.''
   Controllers said they would like to see the Federal Aviation
Administration make a stronger response to an ``unsatisfactory
condition report'' filed in May. At the time, controllers noticed
that as the six-story Quality Suites hotel went up, more and more
planes began disappearing from the radar screen.
   The FAA conducted tests that showed gaps in radar coverage up to
about 2,000 feet in a corridor of air space up to seven miles wide
and extending about 25 to 35 miles southwest of Portland
International Jetport.
   Until the radar can be moved, the agency adopted interim
guidelines under which airplanes going through the area are kept
well above 2,000 feet, said Walter Claxton, FAA tower manager at
the airport.
   ``I can't say the problem is completely solved,'' Claxton said.
``We set up the interim procedures until the problem is solved. If
it was a real safety issue, the radar would have been moved two
months ago, or we'd put a new one in.''
   Claxton said only small planes are affected, because larger
planes are not flying that low when they are 30 miles out.
   Jim Breen, the New England representative of the air traffic
controllers association, said controllers also have to keep
jetliners out of the area even if they are at a high altitude
because pilots cannot be advised about what might be flying under
them.
   Ms. Readio said commercial flights from Boston often go near the
area, and controllers have to make sure they stay away from the
blind spot.
   ``We can't tell them what's there,'' Breen said from Bradley
International Airport, just north of Hartford, Conn. ``The system
could be safer by getting this radar moved soon.''
   Claxton said the radar might be moved within the next year.
   ``We're going to move the radar,'' Claxton said. ``Where we're
going to move it, I'm not sure. It kind of sits low on the airport,
and things were fine until the building came along.''
   The FAA said it never objected to the hotel construction because
when the project was first proposed, the developer's plans
contained a typo that indicated the building would be 12,000 feet
from the runway when it was in fact just 1,200 feet from the runway.
   Breen blames the FAA for the mixup.
   ``Twelve-hundred feet and 12,000 feet are quite a bit
different,'' Breen said. ``Typo or not, you'd think somebody would
have noticed it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
