<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-30 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snowshowers Scattered Over Northeast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT slugline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Light snow was scattered across much of the Northeast on
Thursday, with nearly a foot of snow at a New York state ``snow
belt'' town, and temperatures fell well below zero in the northern
Rockies.
   Snow showers were scattered over northern Maine, Vermont, the
northwestern two-thirds of New York state, the northwestern third
of Pennsylvania, eastern Ohio, northern Lower Michigan, eastern
Upper Michigan, and northeastern Minnesota,
   The small upstate New York community of Barnes Corners, about 10
miles south of Watertown, had 10 inches of new snow. The town is in
a ``snow belt'' downwind of Lake Ontario, whose moisture
contributes to ``lake effect snow.'' Watertown got 6 inches of snow
between 7 a.m. and noon, the National Weather Service reported.
   In western New York state, Springville had 5 inches of new snow.
   Elsewhere, snow was scattered over northwestern New Mexico. And
near San Angelo, Texas, less than an inch of snow fell overnight
across the Concho Valley, leaving patches of ice on roads and
highways in the morning.
   Rain was scattered from northwestern Texas across central Texas
and the central half of the Texas Gulf Coast.
   South of Florida, tropical storm Karen dumped heavy rain on
Cuba, with 14 inches in 24 hours at Punte del Este on the Isle of
Youth, the weather service said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees at Jackson, Wyo., to 75 at Miami.
   Thursday's low for the Lower 48 states was 12 degrees below zero
at West Yellowstone, Mont.
