<FIRST>u w AM-DefectorExpelled 1stLd-Writethru   11-30 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defector Expelled, 1st Ld-Writethru,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Defector Expelled From Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng: ``Officials declined'' to UPDATE with
official confirming Howard still in Soviet bloc, SUBS 18th graf pvs bgng:
``Thornburgh met'' to UPDATE with Runkel saying the attorney general did
not discuss Howard with KGB head, makes minor editing changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former CIA agent who fled to the Soviet
Union just before he was charged with passing secrets was recently
ordered expelled from Hungary, U.S. officials said Thursday.
   The U.S. government urged Hungary to permanently bar Edward Lee
Howard, a defector wanted on an espionage charge who has made
extended visits to the eastern block country, said the officials,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In 1985, Howard eluded FBI surveillance near his home in Santa
Fe, N.M., and fled the country two days before he was charged in a
warrant with passing secrets to the Soviet Union.
   He later turned up in Moscow and the Soviet Union announced
nearly a year after his defection that it had given Howard
political asylum.
   Howard, 37, is charged with selling secrets to the Soviet Union
for $6,000 in 1984 during a trip to Austria.
   He is said to have exposed the network of CIA contacts in
Moscow, a spy post for which he was trained but never assigned to
because he was fired in 1983.
   ``He certainly gave away the entire CIA operation in Moscow,''
said David Wise, author of the 1988 book about the Howard case
entitled ``The Spy Who Got Away.'' Wise reported in the book that
Howard was paid more than $150,000.
   One official confirmed that Howard was still in the Soviet bloc.
Wise said Howard was probably in Moscow where he has an apartment
and a nearby summer house.
   Besides exposing dead-drop locations and codes the CIA employed
to contact Soviet contacts, Wise said Howard exposed details of
electronic eavesdropping the agency conducted in the Soviet capital.
   ``There wasn't much he didn't give up,'' Wise said.
   CIA Director William Webster made a veiled reference to Howard's
expulsion when asked by reporters Wednesday about cooperation
between intelligence agencies of the Soviet Union and Eastern bloc
nations.
   Webster cited the case of a ``a prominent defector from the
United States (who) was permanently expelled from a bloc country
which had provided him comfort and sanctuary in the past.''
   ``And that would have been contrary to the wishes of the KGB,''
said Webster, who didn't identify Howard or the country by name.
   But the U.S. officials confirmed a report in Thursday's editions
of the Los Angeles Times that Webster was referring to Howard's
expulsion from Hungary.
   Asked about the report, Hungarian Interior Ministry spokesman
Lt. Col. Janos Horvach said in a telephone interview, ``It's news
to me.''
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel refused to comment
about the case.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh met with Howard's handler
during a recent visit to Moscow.
   Thornburgh met with Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, who was the No. 2 KBG
official at the time he was directing Howard. Runkel said the
Howard case was not discussed during the meeting at KGB
headquarters.
   The meeting was scheduled ``only to talk about areas where there
could be discussion on cooperation in the law enforcement area,''
including efforts to combat terrorism, Runkel said.
   Wise, who interviewed Howard for his book during a visit to
Hungary, said the former CIA agent spent a lot of time in that
country, enjoying visits to Budapest and Lake Bolatov, a resort
area.
   ``I would doubt if he would set foot in the West'' for fear of
being snatched by U.S. agents, Wise said. Howard was even nervous
about visiting Budapest, where he feared the CIA could inject a
tranquilizer in his arm and spirit him across the Austrian border,
Wise said.
   Given the current political climate in Eastern Europe, Wise said
it is most likely that Howard has returned to the Soviet Union,
where he would feel safe from U.S. efforts to arrest him.
   While Howard would not be subject to extradition from a Western
country because espionage is a political crime, Wise pointed out
that he might feel threatened by the new overseas snatch authority
conferred on the FBI.
   A legal opinion issued last June by the Justice Department said
that the FBI had the legal authority to seize U.S. fugitives
overseas without the permission of a foreign government.
   Wise reported in his book that Howard was paid handsomely for
his spying by the Soviets. Howard had $150,000 in a Swiss bank
account before he defected and afterwards, his wife, Mary, led FBI
agents to a spot in the New Mexico desert where her husband had
buried $10,000 worth of gold and other valuables.
   Howard's wife, who lives in the Minneapolis area with the
couple's son, could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
