<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     11-30 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Assembly Strips Opposition Candidate Of Immunity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista-dominated National
Assembly voted Thursday to strip opposition candidate Virgilio
Godoy of his immunity from prosecution as a deputy, opening the way
for possible charges of mismanagement.
   Even before the vote, Godoy scoffed at the procedure. He called
it part of a leftist Sandinista plot to discredit him as vice
presidential candidate of the National Opposition Union and weaken
the anti-government bloc.
   The 14-party bloc is the major rival of the ruling Sandinista
National Liberation Front in Feb. 25 elections.
   ``What they have done today is a farce, and farces are performed
by humbugs,'' Godoy said after the vote, which he boycotted.
   Sandinistas hold 61 of the 96 seats in the single-house
legislature. Deputies from six opposition parties hold the
remaining 35 seats.
   Godoy is president of the Liberal Independent Party and one of
its nine deputies in the assembly.
   The measure to strip him of his parliamentary immunity passed
61-1, with one abstention. A Conservative Democrat Party deputy
voted against. A deputy belonging to a Liberal faction opposed to
Godoy abstained.
   Thirty-three deputies were absent, including 21 opposition
deputies.
   Accusations focus on items and about $60,000 donated to a
Godoy-directed research center by the Friedrich-Naumann Foundation,
based in Bonn, West Germany.
   The foundation said it was satisfied with how its donations were
managed and called questions about the management ``baseless.''
   Godoy says members of a rival Liberal faction who questioned the
center's handling of donations were put up to it by the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
