<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0667 11-30 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Conclude Emotional Testimony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with weekend recess called. SUBS
grafs 15-16, `The pictures ..., with 6 grafs to UPDATE with later testimony.
Picks up penultimate graf, `Mahoney is...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCRL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony by survivors of the nation's
worst drunken driving accident concluded Thursday with several
badly burned teen-agers weeping as they detailed the horrible
aftermath of the bus crash.
   A weekend recess was called after the sixth day of testimony in
the trial of Larry Mahoney, 36, charged with murder and drunken
driving in the fiery crash on May 14, 1988, south of this Ohio
River town.
   Christy Pearman, 15, testified she cried out for her father,
John R. Pearman, who was driving the First Assembly of God church
bus, as she struggled to escape the heavy smoke and flames inside.
   ``I turned around to see my dad and I saw the fire,'' she
testified. ``I was standing in the aisle, yelling for my dad.'' He
did not survive.
   Miss Pearman said she was trapped in her eighth-row window seat
in the crush of panicked teen-agers making their way to a rear
emergency door. She managed to free herself and began climbing over
a bus seat to escape.
   ``The seat was so hot it melted my right palm,'' she said.
   Twenty-seven people died in the fire and 40 survived, but some
with disfiguring burns.
   Carroll Circuit Court Judge Charles Satterwhite called a
15-minute recess after Ciaran Foran, 16, of Radcliff broke down in
sobs during testimony.
   Miss Foran sobbed heavily when asked by Assistant Attorney
General Paul Richwalksy Jr. to describe what she had seen seconds
after the bus collided with a wrong-way driver on Interstate 71.
   Some jurors turned their eyes away from Miss Foran, who was
wearing a special pressure garment to assist healing of severe
burns on her neck, face and shoulder.
   After the unscheduled break, Miss Foran testified that her head
was resting on a plastic helium balloon that blew up in her face
after the crash. Miss Foran spent about six weeks in a hospital and
underwent 19 operations.
   Also testifying was Joseph Percefull, 16, who suffered first-and
second-degree burns to his arm, legs, wrists and face.
   Percefull, who escaped through a crowded rear emergency door,
told the court he saw his ``skin from the heat _ it rolled up on my
arm.'' He also said he heard a sound like a match thrown on
gasoline seconds after the collision.
   Other survivors told of falling unconscious as they were
overcome with smoke and heat inside the bus, and somehow being
pulled from the wreckage. They also told of losing friends inside
the bus.
   Carey Aurentz, 15, of Radcliff, sobbed as she held small color
pictures of Kashawn Etheredge, Jennifer Arnett and Emillie
Thompson, all of whom died in the wreck.
   In the courtroom gallery, family of victims and survivors wiped
at tears and sniffled.
   The pictures were placed on a large seating chart of the bus to
show the jury the exact location of each of the 67 passengers at
the time of the crash. Some of the girls sat on the laps of boys,
and some were lying in the aisle, asleep after a long day at a
Cincinnati-area amusement park, according to testimony.
   Defense attorneys have said that they would argue that it was
defects in the bus, which was manufactured before federal rules
requiring more safety features went into effect, that led to the
deaths. Later buses were required to have, among other things,
better shielding around the gas tank.
   Louisville surgeon Dr. Mark Malangoni testified that six of the
survivors he treated would have died of suffocation if they hadn't
received prompt medical attention.
   He also described amputating the severely burned foot of Miss
Aurentz, who suffered burns over 55 to 60 percent of her body and
has required extensive surgery.
   Mahoney is charged with 27 counts of murder, 42 counts of wanton
endangerment, 12 counts of assault and one count of drunken driving.
   Testimony is expected to move onto the 27 murder counts next
week, but Richwalksy declined to say when that phase of the trial
would begin.
</TEXT>
