<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 2148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LegalServices     11-30 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Legal Services,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Fills Two Vacancies On Legal Services Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday filled two
vacancies on the board of the Legal Services Corp. on the eve of a
scheduled vote to replace the organization's president Terrence
Wear.
   Bush gave so-called recess appointments to former Rep. John
Erlenborn, R-Ill., and Texas attorney J. Blakely Hall to sit on the
board that oversees the independent agency that gives legal help to
the nation's poor.
   Bush made the appointments during the year-end recess of
Congress, thus avoiding Senate confirmation proceedings.
   Under the Constitution, people given recess appointments can
serve until the end of the congresional session _ in this case the
end of 1990.
   The board meeting scheduled for Friday is the latest in
skirmishing between two factions over the nature of legal services.
   The corporation's board has been a battleground for
conservatives seeking to limit legal services, particularly
class-action lawsuits against the government over welfare and other
social programs.
   Conservatives also object to legal services representing
plaintiffs in lawsuits to force hospitals to give abortions to
indigent women.
   This faction held a 6-5 majority on the board until two
vacancies recently occurred, said Carolyn Stewart of the National
Legal Aid and Defenders Association.
   The group monitors the agency and supports efforts to allow
legal services lawyers to provide a full range of representation,
she said.
   Supporters of a broader range of legal services held a 5-4
majority on the board before Bush made the appointments on Thursday.
   The board was scheduled Friday to consider a move to oust Wear
and demand an accounting of more than $100,000 spent to hire a
former Reagan administration official to provide outside legal
advice, Stewart said.
   The money was paid for legal opinions provided by Charles
Cooper, a former assistant attorney general in the Reagan
administration and a conservative activist, Stewart said. Those
opinions include one by Cooper that the corporation is
unconstitutional.
   Stewart said her organization did not know how Erlenborn would
vote if he attended Friday's meeting.
   Now a private attorney in Washington, Erlenborn was considered a
supporter of legal services when he represented a suburban Chicago
congressional district, she said.
   Earlier this year, conservative activists successfully lobbied
the White House to stop the appointment of former Republican Rep.
Caldwell Butler of Virginia to the board.
   Butler had angered conservatives by stating he would not support
restrictions on the activities of legal aid attorneys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
