<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AncientMurder     11-30 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ancient Murder,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Neighbor Charged In 20-year-old Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after Susan Nason was
killed, a former neighbor appeared in court Thursday and was
charged with the slaying, and published reports said the man's own
daughter gave the information leading to his arrest.
   George Thomas Franklin Sr., 50, was arrested Tuesday at his home
in Carmichael, near Sacramento, and charged with murdering the
8-year-old girl. He was held without bail on one count of murder.
   Investigators would not identify the witness who provided the
tip that led to the arrest. But the San Francisco Chronicle,
quoting an unidentified law enforcement source, reported Thursday
that Franklin's daughter, a former classmate of the dead girl, came
forward and told investigators she witnessed the 1969 slaying.
   The source said the daughter had repressed all memory of the
event, but finally recalled seeing her father bludgeon her friend
to death with a rock in his van.
   Susan disappeared while playing after school near her home in
Foster City on Sept. 22, 1969.
   Her disappearance led to an extensive search in the San
Francisco Bay area. A $20,000 reward was offered for the arrest and
conviction of her killer by the employer of Donald Nason, the
girl's father.
   The girl's remains were found four months later under an old
mattress at an abandoned gravel pit near the Crystal Springs
Reservoir about 20 miles south of San Francisco. She had been
killed with a blunt instrument that fractured her skull,
investigators said.
   Nason, who lives in the same Foster City home with his wife,
Margaret, said he never gave up hope a suspect would be arrested in
his daughter's killing.
   ``The law has a very long memory,'' he said. ``After 20 years _
almost on the anniversary and it's pretty close to the day _ it's
something you hope for all this time.''
   San Mateo County Sheriff's Department Lt. Mike Dow said
detectives believe Franklin killed the girl because he had tried to
sexually molest her.
   At Carmichael, a suburb of Sacramento, a close friend of
Franklin said the arrest shocked them both.
   ``I talked to him today, and he's still in shock. He has
absolutely no idea what's happening or why or anything,'' said the
friend, who declined to identify herself. ``I certainly do believe
he is innocent.''
   Franklin retired to the Sacramento area several years ago after
a long career with the San Mateo Fire Department, said the friend.
The woman said Franklin is a licensed real estate agent but is not
currently working.
   ``He's an outgoing man, a delightful person,'' the woman added.
</TEXT>
