<FIRST>r a AM-StrasserSentence     11-30 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strasser Sentence,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Man Sentenced in Ethiopian's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third man charged in the racially
motivated beating death of an Ethiopian student has been sentenced
to 20 years in prison.
   Steven Strasser had pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter
in the Nov. 13, 1988, slaying of 27-year-old Mulugeta Seraw.
   Strasser asked for leniency before sentencing Wednesday but
Multnomah County Circuit Judge Philip T. Abraham called the death a
``shocking and horrendous crime.''
   ``I'll never again be a part of a group that advocates
violence,'' Strasser said in a statement to the judge. But Strasser
stopped short of denying that he harbored racist views when
questioned by Abraham.
   Abraham read from a report by a psychologist who concluded after
interviewing Strasser that he ``felt pride in the concept of the
white working man but that he did not have extreme racial views.''
   When Abraham asked if that was how he felt, Strasser replied:
``I didn't necessarily say that. I think people should have a right
to belong to a group.''
   Strasser, 21, was a member of East Side White Pride, a group
advocating white supremacy. Two other members of the same group,
Kenneth Mieske and Kyle Brewster, pleaded guilty to murder and
manslaughter, respectively, in Seraw's death.
   Strasser joined White Pride ``partially out of loneliness and
wanting to belong to a group,'' said his attorney, George Haslett.
``He is just a nice young boy whose life is ruined.''
   Besides manslaughter, Strasser also pleaded guilty to
second-degree assault for striking another victim. He pleaded no
contest to a charge of racial intimidation arising from the same
incident.
</TEXT>
