<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Baltics     11-30 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Official Cautions Lithuanians on Creating Splinter Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kremlin official Thursday warned Lithuanians
that their efforts to form an independent Communist Party would
hurt national reforms, while party members across the Baltics
pushed for more freedom from Moscow.
   ``The aspiration of certain forces to drive a wedge between the
Lithuanian Communist Party and the Soviet Communist Party will
benefit no one but will only complicate the process of
perestroika,'' Tass quoted Vadim A. Medvedev, the Kremlin ideology
chief and a member of the ruling Politburo, as telling Communists
in Lithuania's capital, Vilnius.
   Despite the well-publicized Kremlin hostility to the
Lithuanians' intentions, 39 Communists in neighboring Latvia,
including eight members of the local party's Central Committee,
called for founding a ``politically, organizationally and
economically independent'' Communist Party, Tass reported.
   ``Many party organizations in the republic look at the address
of the 39 Communists as a call for the splitting of the Latvian
party,'' the official news agency reported from Riga, Latvia's
capital.
   Meanwhile, in Estonia, the third Baltic republic, the local
party's ideology chief, Mikk Titma, said in an interview with his
party's daily that he is ``certain'' the legal guarantee of the
party's leading role in political life will be eliminated from
Estonia's constitution.
   ``Some kind of coalition'' will then govern Estonia, Titma said
in the interview, printed in the Sunday edition of the Sovietskaya
Estonia newspaper.
   The political changes in the Baltic republics come against the
backdrop of upcoming local elections across the country, which
begin in some parts of the Soviet Union on Dec. 10.
   For the first time nationwide, voters will be offered a choice
of candidates for their local ``soviets,'' or governing councils.
Party officials in the once independent Baltic republics have said
they must have a free hand to set policies popular with voters or
risk defeat.
   Medvedev, who was quoted by Tass, traveled to Lithuania
Wednesday to take part in a high-level party meeting. He spoke
Thursday to Vilnius-based delegates to a special congress of
Lithuania's Communist Party, which will open Dec. 19.
   On the congress agenda is a draft program proclaiming the
republic's party ``a political force in the creation of an
independent, law-governed Lithuanian state.''
   Since the days of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin, Kremlin
leaders have rejected autonomy for local party organizations in the
name of ``democratic centralism.'' Lithuanian party leaders were
summoned to Moscow on Nov. 16 to make their intentions known to the
full Communist Party Politburo, including Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev and Medvedev.
   Gorbachev strongly opposes plans for the Lithuanian party to
separate from the national Communist Party, which he has headed
since March 1985. At the meeting in Vilnius, Medvedev advocated
more rights for the local parties in the 15 constituent Soviet
republics, but only ``within the renewing Soviet Communist Party,''
Tass reported.
   In Latvia, the dissident Communists called for renouncing the
``utopian goal of building Communist society and the dogmatic
interpretation of Marxism-Leninism,'' Tass said.
   Despite criticism of the dissidents, the Latvian Politburo
admitted ``it was losing the initiative'' and decided to organize
working groups to draft the rules and program of the Latvian party,
Tass said.
   Latvia's Communist Party also scheduled a plenum of its Central
Committee in January ``to renew its composition'' and make changes
in the party apparatus, Tass said, indicating the likelihood of
sweeping personnel changes.
   The declaration of the 39 Latvian Communists was printed by
Latvia's major party and government newspapers, according to a
telex sent to the Moscow bureau of The Associated Press by the
Latvian Popular Front, a grassroots pro-reform group.
</TEXT>
