<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mass-Taxes     11-30 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mass-Taxes,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Delays Tax Debate As Democratic Leaders Scramble for Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state House adjourned Thursday without
tackling a $1.2 billion tax-hike package that signaled the end of
the economic boom dubbed the ``Massachusetts miracle'' and
triggered a ``firestorm'' of taxpayer protest.
   A Statehouse switchboard operator said she was handling 100
calls every 15 minutes from irate taxpayers.
   Speaker George Keverian, after a day of vote hunting, recessed
the House without opening debate on the package approved Wednesday
by the House Ways and Means Committee. It includes hikes in sales,
capital gains and gasoline taxes.
   ``Considerable time has gone by today and I apologize to many of
you who have been here waiting for the beginning of debate,''
Keverian said. ``Our position is the same as it was. We intend to
make some refinements and some suggestions tomorrow.''
   The committee's package would add two cents to the sales tax,
increase the gas tax by 10 cents over the next two years and hike
capital gains from 5 percent to 7.5 percent. Most increases would
take effect Jan. 1, 1990, but the capital gains would be
retroactive to last January.
   The proposal is the Legislature's latest move to deal with the
deficit, which a Ways and Means staffer said had swelled to $825
million.
   As the committee sent the proposal to the House, the Senate held
hearings on a $350 million House-approved package of spending cuts.
   Keverian said later Thursday the Democratic leadership would
propose an amendment to lower the sales tax increase to 6 cents on
the dollar, up from the current 5 cents. That would cost $190
million in new revenue this fiscal year and about $400 million next
year.
   Keverian said the loss would be made up with additional cuts and
possibly with additional revenue in the tax package. He said he did
not anticipate any other significant changes, although he would not
predict the outcome of a vote on a rank-and-file amendment he said
he expects will be offered to remove the capital-gains tax hike
from the bill.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, who had suggested he had some
reservations about the package, urged approval, saying he realized
taxes were unpopular but elected officials should take a tough
stand.
   ``If there's anything we've got to have now it's fiscal
stability,'' the governor said. ``And that's what this package is
going to bring.''
   The Republican minority leader, Rep. Steven Pierce, said the
size of the package and the leadership's effort to rush it through
were a losing combination.
   ``They failed to get it out because they're pushing an
outrageous bill,'' Pierce said, adding that it had set off a
``firestorm of angry criticism from an angry public.''
   ``The answer should be the same no matter what the package is.
The answer should be no,'' Pierce said.
   Rep. Marjorie Clapprood, a Democrat and supporter of the
package, predicted the sales tax increase would be lowered. ``I
think it is clear as the package stands, we are short of the 81
votes needed to pass it,'' she said.
   Clapprood suggested shutting off the Statehouse switchboard and
locking lawmakers in the House chamber to get the bill passed.
   She said she got one call at home at 4:30 a.m. Thursday from a
woman opposed to higher taxes.
   ``The whole state of Massachusetts has called,'' said one of the
Statehouse's two switchboard operators who declined to give her
name.
   Barbara Anderson of the Citizens for Limited Taxation said the
Legislature was trying to con voters into accepting taxes by
slashing human services and education budgets.
   ``The point is, are we going to give into this kind of
blackmail?'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
