<DOCNO> AP891130-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-Soviet-LongWinter Adv03   11-30 1221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet-Long Winter, Adv 03,1255</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cold and Snowy Gray Skies Set Mood for Soviet Winter of Discontent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As snow begins to fall and the sky turns gray,
Soviet citizens enter a long winter of discontent over barren store
shelves, strikes and ethnic clashes that, far from being halted by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, often have worsened.
   ``There's much that we'd like to have, but the Russian people
are used to difficulties,'' said Luda Panina, 33, as she sold red
carnations outside a Moscow subway station on a cold, snowy day.
   Russians _ and the Soviet Union's more than 100 other national
groups _ have endured hardships for decades, but the difference is
that now they expect more, both from Gorbachev and from his
perestroika program that 4{ years ago promised to make their lives
better.
   Preparing for his shipboard summit with President Bush in the
Mediterranean Sea this weekend, Gorbachev indicated a principal
goal of the talks would be to discuss easing of international
tensions so that he could focus more on problems at home. ``To put
it in a nutshell, we need a normal external environment
for our domestic work,'' he said.
   The country has been torn by long-simmering ethnic, economic and
environmental woes that the leadership previously ignored or
stifled, but which have surfaced as ``glasnost,'' or openness,
exposes harsh realities.
   Inflation, crime and budget deficits, around for decades, were
hushed up until glasnost brought out the shocking numbers: crime up
34 percent in the first 10 months of 1989 over the same period last
year, a budget deficit reaching 120 billion rubles ($194 billion),
inflation pegged by one economist at 4 percent to 5 percent yearly.
   Ethnic tensions among the myriad Soviet peoples _ many of whom
were brutally oppressed under dictator Josef Stalin _ have pitted
Armenians against Azerbaijanis, ethnic Turks against Uzbeks and
Russian minorities against Estonians, Latvians, Lithuanians,
Ukrainians and Moldavians. Ethnic clashes have taken more than 300
lives, by official count.
   In addition, growing campaigns for independence in many of the
15 constituent Soviet republics, especially in the Baltics, are
threatening the very glue that holds the union together.
   Strikes by coal miners, angry about official inattention to
their hazardous work conditions and poor lifestyles, have depleted
fuel supplies going into the winter.
   In the southern republic of Georgia, the government ordered
businesses to switch days off to Wednesdays and Thursdays because
of an electricity shortage, caused in part by the shutdown of
Armenia's nuclear power plant after last year's devastating
earthquake.
   Outright economic sabotage is afoot as well. Azerbaijan
blockaded the ethnic hotspot of Nagorno-Karabakh and neighboring
Armenia for two months, preventing trainloads of fuel, food and raw
materials from getting through. The blockade delayed reconstruction
of the area leveled by the Dec. 7, 1988, earthquake that killed
25,000 Armenians. Officials now say rebuilding will take three
years, one more than planned.
   Other headaches the nation and Gorbachev have suffered include
the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear power plant explosion and fire that,
according to one Soviet newspaper, led to the deaths of 250 people
and cost billions of rubles, a gas pipeline blast in June that
killed more than 600 passengers on passing trains, and extensive
water and air pollution.
   To many Soviets, however, their mood depends largely on what
there is to eat and wear.
   For the most part, Gorbachev's reforms have brought not
improvements in Soviets' standard of living, but more of what
people here call ``deficits,'' shortages of products that have led
to the widespread rationing of butter, cheese, meat, sugar and tea.
Some economists even propose rationing everything, to prevent the
hoarding that is now common.
   As Soviets approach the end of the year, many would agree with a
prediction made months ago.
   ``One can expect that the year 1989 will be the most
unsuccessful of all those we have lived through,'' Vasily Selyunin,
a specialist in economic affairs, wrote in April.
   Statistics tell the 287 million Soviets what they already know
from painful experience:
   _Of 211 food products, a consumer demand institute found only 23
could be bought freely. The rest require connections with the
sellers or overpayment or they are rationed.
   _Soviets eat half the meat and fruit consumed by the average
American, but twice as many potatoes.
   _Because of losses in distribution and processing, one-quarter
of all farm products don't reach consumers.
   _Nearly 80 percent of Muscovites buy up items in short supply,
even though they don't really need them at the time, and there is
unsatisfied consumer demand in the capital worth the equivalent of
$14 million to $16 billion, a research institute estimates.
   Gorbachev now speaks openly about the failures of perestroika
and has increasingly expressed worry over the people's mood.
   ``The shortage of food creates social tension and generates not
merely criticism but actual discontent,'' he told the Communist
Party Central Committee in March.
   Yuri Maslyukov, the state planning chief, also has spoken of
``mounting social discontent.''
   Gorbachev and his aides admit they failed initially to pay
enough attention to the people's welfare and say improving it is
now their No. 1 priority.
   ``All of our productive capacity must be reoriented to produce
what the people need: consumer goods,'' the Soviet leader said in
May.
   To that end, some 300 military factories are being converted to
civilian production and the 1990 government budget calls for
increasing consumer goods output by 12 percent.
   The Kremlin also is turning to other countries for quick fixes.
It plans to use its precious reserves of foreign currency and
Western credits to import $51.8 billion worth of consumer goods
next year.
   To help Soviet industry gear up to produce such goods on its
own, plans call for importing $2.6 billion worth of raw materials
and light industry equipment.
   This year, the government brought in 15 million pair of leather
shoes, 12 million pair of warm women's boots, 300 million razor
blades, 10 million compact cassette players, as well as clothing,
soap, detergent and toothpaste. Contracts were signed with foreign
companies from Turkey to Japan.
   An encounter with Ms. Panina, the flower saleswoman, showed the
imports are reaching the people. Two large boxes of Danish laundry
detergent she had bought sat on the ground next to her flower
stand. American-brand toothpaste also has appeared in some Moscow
stores.
   But the Kremlin cannot afford such costly imports for long, and
Western officials say they will not help solve the basic problem:
inadequacy of domestic production.
   U.S. aid ``might take the pressures off for a few months,'' one
senior Western diplomat said, but later ``the shelves would still
be bare.''
   Gorbachev has said the ``socio-economic situation'' must be
righted within a year and a half at most, but one of his chief
economic advisers, Abel Aganbegyan, says it will take twice that
long to end shortages. Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev estimates
it will take until 1996 to bring Soviets' diet up to nutritional
norms.
   In the meantime, Soviets keep scrounging around.
   ``You must run around to stores to buy what you need,'' said Ms.
Panina. A look of wonderment on her face, she added, ``They say in
America you go to one store and buy all you want.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
