<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv03   11-30 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 03,0952</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 3, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators United Against White House Bid To Control Judgeships</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a display of bipartisanship with a
vengeance, Republican and Democratic senators are feuding with the
White House over the senatorial prerogative of saying who should be
appointed a federal judge back home.
   The administration is trying to enforce a multiple choice system
instead of letting GOP senators pick names for almost automatic
nomination to federal district judgeships. That has angered
Republicans, gained them Democratic allies, and set the lines for a
confrontation after Congress reconvenes on Jan. 23 unless the
dispute can be settled first.
   ``It is said that marriages are made in heaven, but judgeships
are made in the Senate,'' a Democratic senator declared, applauding
a Republican colleague for challenging the Republican White House
on the matter.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Wednesday that President
Bush ``wants a pool of suitable candidates from which he can choose
his nominee,'' and govern the process himself. He said if senators
won't accept those terms, ``that's a matter between them and the
president.''
   On this one the lines are institutional, not political. Senators
don't have much in the way of patronage, and they are not about to
let go of the judgeships on which they have claimed selection
rights for 150 years and more.
   The case at issue involves the appointment of a federal district
court judge for Vermont. Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., has been
trying all year to get Fred I. Parker of Weybridge nominated to
fill the vacancy.
   The dispute erupted into debate just before Congress adjourned
10 days ago. Because of it, Jeffords held up the confirmation of
federal judges in Alabama and Arkansas, and said he will block
nominations wholesale next year if necessary.
   The Senate Republican Conference sided with him, and told
President Bush that he ought to nominate Jeffords' choice.
   Jeffords said district court judgeships have been the
prerogative of senators since 1840, a tradition so strong that
President Herbert Hoover once nominated a man he didn't want
because a senator insisted, and then sent administration aides to
lobby, unsuccessfully, against confirmation.
   That tradition has been whittled a bit during the past two
administrations. Jimmy Carter had selection panels look at all
nominees, and required that there be more women and minority
nominees. While he bent the old system, he did not break it.
   Ronald Reagan had a review commission, and his administration
required that senators send the Justice Department three names for
each vacancy instead of just one. But Republican senators left no
doubt about which name counted, and they got their way.
   Jeffords said the Reagan changes didn't really interfere with
Senate prerogatives. ``What formerly was a formality is now a
reality,'' Jeffords said. ``It is the policy of this administration
that any senator must send at least three names, and it also has
been made clear to me personally that they are not restricted to
those names to select from.'' Bending to the administration,
Jeffords did supply two more names, but made clear that Parker's
was the only one acceptable to him.
   Jeffords said the names go to ``a review panel of five
bureaucrats somewhere in the bowels of the Justice Department.''
   ``If they, as in my case, decide that that candidate is
unacceptable, that is the end of the process,'' he said.
   That's why he decided to fight, using another Senate prerogative
to block other nominees.
   In Vermont, Jeffords said, a nine-member, bipartisan panel
reviews candidates for the federal bench. He said Parker was rated
the best of a dozen potential nominees, far ahead of any other, and
he insisted the state selection board is better equipped than the
administration to choose the best judge for Vermont.
   Jeffords told the Senate that if he yields on Parker, every
other senator will be at risk when it comes time to fill a federal
court vacancy.
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., agreed with Jeffords on the system
and on the selection of Parker, whom he called the best possible
choice. He said judgeships should continue to be made in the Senate.
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del. chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, said there's more at stake than an ancient prerogative.
``Unlike five bureaucrats in the White House subjecting nominees to
litmus tests or any other tests, the home state senators know
better the quality of the people in their states,'' Biden said.
   Jeffords, a Senate freshman, has ventured no public guess as to
why the administration is making his choice a test case. Parker,
who practices law in Middlebury and Burlington, was an assistant
attorney general when Jeffords served as state attorney general.
   Murray Dickman, an aide to Thornburgh, has cited Parker's
membership in the all-male Ethan Allen Club of Burlington. Parker
resigned from the club before his name was recommended for the
bench.
   Dickman noted that Leahy once complained to Thornburgh about the
membership of another judicial nominee in an all-male club. The
nomination of Vaughn R. Walker of San Francisco was held up for
nearly two years, and finally approved this month.
   There's not much political logic there. Walker also was
sponsored by a Republican senator, and two Republican
administrations stuck with him, Democratic opposition and club
affiliations notwithstanding.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 3</NOTE>
