<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--NuclearPriest Adv04   11-30 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Nuclear Priest, Adv 04,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nuclear Test Controller Lives Double Life As Priest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Why We Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As an Episcopal priest, Bob Nelson prays that
no one will ever use what he helps to produce at his day job.
   Other priests may lead protests against nuclear weapons; Nelson
leads the teams that explode those weapons deep underground at the
Nevada Test Site. It's contradictory, being ``the only priest I
know who fires nuclear weapons.''
   And it forces him almost daily to reconcile his occupation and
his calling.
   ``There are no right or wrong answers,'' he said. ``I would like
to be in a situation where there are no nuclear weapons. But I
would also like a situation where we maintain the system of freedom
and justice we have in our country.''
   The 48-year-old deputy manager of Nevada operations for the U.S.
Energy Department is a nuclear veteran, having begun his career in
the Navy on the staff of Adm. Hyman Rickover, a force behind
nuclear development.
   He's a newcomer to the clergy, however, having for years put
aside his thoughts of becoming a priest. ``The way God works, he
just doesn't follow the rules at all. With my family, work and
other commitments, I thought becoming a priest was something that
just couldn't happen,'' said the father of two.
   Nelson, a lifelong Episcopalian, was nominated into the
priesthood by the congregation at All Saints Episcopal Church under
a canon allowing elevation of parishioners to priests in remote
parishes. He was ordained two years ago. The church has not taken a
position on continued nuclear testing.
   Nelson takes pains to separate his role as a priest from the job
in which he has given the final approval to detonate more than 30
nuclear devices. But he also believes his experience in the weapons
program has given him insight into the everyday world that is
useful in his role as a priest.
   ``I deal with a lot of real world things here that perhaps the
clergy who have been clergy for their whole careers don't see,'' he
said.
   Nelson doesn't shy away from defending his beliefs on continued
nuclear testing and he is often asked to go before anti-nuclear
groups and explain the government's position that testing is vital
to the nation's security.
   ``I don't think in any of these discussions I change anybody's
mind or they change mine, but we come away from honest and direct
discussions the better for it. The best comment I ever got from one
anti-nuclear activist was, `I don't agree with what you're doing,
but I'm glad you're the one doing it.'''
   ``He's the kind of guy I admire and respect whether he worked
for me or was on the other side,'' said Nick Aquilina, manager of
the test site. ``I believe he comes across in a very credible way
because he's so honest. I've never second-guessed his motives on
anything because he's always so honest.''
   Nelson goes out of his way not to criticize anti-nuclear
protesters who often congregate at the gates of the test site.
Many, in fact, are his friends, including the wife of another
Episcopal priest in Las Vegas.
   Nelson and the priest's wife are founding board members and work
closely together on a project to build a shelter for homeless women
and children in the city. ``We just don't talk about nuclear
weapons when we're working together. She and I have the same
ultimate aim. We'd both like not to have nuclear weapons. The
difference is how we get there.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 4</NOTE>
