<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv04   11-30 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 04,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Dec. 04, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Food-Poisoning Toxin Helps Vocal Cord Disorder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small doses of a toxin that causes food
poisoning can help people with a condition that strangles their
voices, researchers say.
   Injections of botulinum into the vocal cords of people with
spasmodic dysphonia relax the tightly squeezed cords within days,
said Dr. Robert Miller, chairman of Tulane Medical Center's
department of otolaryngology and head and neck surgery. The only
adverse reactions are brief hoarseness and difficulty swallowing,
and the toxin does not spread to the rest of the body.
   Spasmodic dysphonia is uncommon, but reliable estimates are not
available of the number of people affected. It seems to worsen with
stress and was long thought to be psychosomatic, but evidence has
accumulated linking the problem to nerve disorders such as tics and
other uncontrollable movements.
   Injections of botulinum toxin have been used to treat facial
tics, Miller said, so researchers decided to try it against the
vocal cord disorder. Work is also being done in New York, San
Diego, Houston and at the National Institutes of Health, said Dr.
Joseph Jankovic, a Baylor College of Medicine neurologist.
   The treatment does not cure the condition. The shots, costing
about $300 each, must be repeated every few months.
   The toxin works with the vocal cords for much the same reason it
causes food poisoning, Jankovic said. In each case, it binds to the
synapse and blocks release of acetylcholine, a chemical that helps
transmit nerve impulses. In the case of food poisoning, the nervous
system's control over breathing often is disrupted, causing death
by respiratory paralysis, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Listening to the Private Lives of Hogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers are eavesdropping on the most
private, intimate moments in the lives of hogs, hoping for hints
that will help farmers.
   ``We're not trying to talk to the animals. What we're doing is
listening to the animals and seeing what they have to tell us,''
said Jim DeShazer, who has established that hogs make different
sounds identifiable with greeting humans, romancing mating
partners, hunger, stress and other conditions.
   In a more subtle distinction, sound- and signal-analysis
equipment has helped determine that there is a single peak to a
sound wave emitted by a sow during nursing and a double peak to the
sound while giving birth.
   ``Even though it's not picked up by hearing, instruments and
maybe other animals can pick it up,'' said DeShazer, an
agricultural engineering professor at the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln whose research has drawn on the talents of
psychologists, speech clinicians and even dentists.
   Differentiating hog sounds could have practical applications.
Microphones and sound-measuring devices could summon a farmer to
help when a sow is giving birth, for example, or could identify
sounds inaudible to humans that might be stressful to hogs _ like a
squeaking ventilator fan, he said.
   Such equipment ``allows us to pick up sounds animals make and to
analyze those sounds that tell us there's some stress problems or
other indicators that need to be taken care of, or that things seem
to be all right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Dec. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
