<FIRST>r f PM-SavoyHotel     11-30 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savoy Hotel,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upper-Crust British Institution Fends Off Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Savoy Hotel, an upper-crust British
institution, has won an eight-year legal battle to fend off a
takeover by Trusthouse Forte PLC, a giant hotel and catering chain
founded by an Italian immigrant.
   Lord Forte, who powered Trusthouse on the back of a single
London milk-drinks counter he opened in the 1930s, called off the
fight Wednesday because he was not willing to spend large sums of
money in legal fees, an aide said.
   Trusthouse said it would not buy any more shares in Savoy Hotel
PLC for five years and the Savoy said it would not issue any more
shares for five years without Trusthouse approval.
   After spending about $64 million, Trusthouse owns 69 percent of
Savoy shares but controls only 42.3 percent because of the stock's
voting structure. Forte employed a team of lawyers in an
unsuccessful bid to gain more votes.
   In return for the truce, the Savoy offered seats on its board to
Rocco Forte, Lord Forte's son and Trusthouse chief executive, and
to Trusthouse financial director Donald Main.
   But Savoy Manging Director Giles Shepard said he will continue
to have final say in the Savoy's operations. He estimated that
fending off the takeover had cost the Savoy at least $1.56 million
in legal fees.
   ``We are delighted to have come to this agreement with the
Savoy,'' Rocco Forte said. ``We have always recognized the
excellence of the Savoy's hotels'' Built in 1889, the Savoy runs
separate kitchens on each of its seven floors, keeps count of its
famous guests' tastes throughout their lives and decorates its 300
rooms individually so that no two are identical.
   The company also operates other famous hotels _ Claridge's, the
Connaught, the Berkeley and the Hotel Lancaster in Paris. Royalty
stays at Claridge's and the superpowers hold banquets there when
their leaders come to London.
   Trusthouse claims to be the world's most profitable hotel and
catering chain and looks after entertaining at the 10 Downing
Street residence of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who admires
its entrepreneurship.
   Sir Hugh Wontner, chairman of the company that owns the Savoy
and a former lord mayor of London, has been catering adviser to
Buckingham Palace for more than 50 years and his family controls 10
percent of the Savoy shares.
   Wontner said quality comes before profit. Lord Forte said they
go hand-in-hand.
   Trusthouse operates in more than 40 countries and Lord Forte
once said the Savoy's profits could be doubled in one year if its
``grossly overpaid'' top management were fired.
   During the legal fight, Lord Forte charged the Savoy directors
with not maximizing potential profits from the famous hotels in
Savoy group.
   Wontner dismissed Lord Forte as ``not a hotelier, just a
caterer,'' while Shepard said of Trusthouse: ``You've got a
difference in philosophy, a David versus Goliath. ... I just don't
believe they'll provide quite what we do.''
   London's Evening Standard newspaper reported the peace pact
represented defeat for Lord Forte's efforts to ``break his way''
into the British upper class ``establishment.''
   Neither Lord Forte nor Wontner, both of whom are 81, attended
the peace pact signing, which must be approved by Savoy
stockholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0210 </DOCNO>
