<FIRST>r f PM-US-EuropeTrade     11-30 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Europe Trade,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Negotiators Urged To Use Defense Accords To Push Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A business group formed by Congress has urged
U.S. negotiators to use defense accords with European allies to
open more trade opportunities for American business.
   The Advisory Committee for Trade Policy and Negotiations, which
consists primarily of business executives, said Wednesday the
Defense Department should coordinate negotiating strategy with the
U.S. Trade Representative to boost business.
   The report on U.S. policy toward the European Economic Community
comes as the 12-nation trade bloc prepares to make its 320 million
consumers into a single market in 1992.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said in a statement that
the report's recommendations ``suggest very constructive steps that
can be taken by the private sector.''
   She did not refer specifically to the defense accords. That
recommendation pointed to agreements called ``memorandums of
understanding'' between the United States and individual member EEC
governments.
   Hundreds of the agreements concern the buying of weapons worth
billions of dollars. Some are always being renegotiated by Pentagon
officials and European goverments.
   The report said renegotiations should be used as leverage to
make international rules apply to a greater share of European
governments' spending. It said such leverage would help expand
rules to new areas of interest to U.S. exporters.
   Spending by European governments was one of six issues
highlighted in the report. The report said the 12 governments buy
$600 billion worth of goods and services every year, including
about $150 billion for defense. It said 95 percent of the money is
spent within each country.
   The report also recommended ways to safeguard U.S. business
interests in Europe by urging governments there to:
   _Loosen requirements on the origin of imported goods.
   _Give Americans a greater share in setting up rules for testing.
   _Help get a common standard for enforcing rules on the transfer
of technology.
   _Be flexible about buying U.S. television programs.
   _Improve the conditions for foreign insurance and investment
companies.
</TEXT>
