<FIRST>r f PM-Wall-LincolnS&amp;L    11-30 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall-Lincoln S&amp;L, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Outside Groups Call for Ouster of Wall as Thrift Regulator</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Riegle-Lincoln S&amp;L, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three activist groups have called for the
ouster of thrift regulator M. Danny Wall but stopped short of
recommending the same for five senators who interceded with his
agency on behalf of Lincoln Savings and Loan Association.
   Joining a growing chorus of critics who blame Wall primarily for
Lincoln's loss of up to $2.5 billion in federally insured deposits
were the National Taxpayers Union, Public Citizen and Citizens
Against Government Waste.
   The three groups on Wednesday urged President Bush in a letter
to dismiss Wall as director of the Office of Thrift Supervision,
saying his decision to delay closing Lincoln for 20 months ``may
have cost citizens of this country more than any other political
appointee in history.''
   On Monday, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, also
called for Wall's resignation, saying, ``Everybody will be better
served by a clean break and new leadership.''
   House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
asked Bush in a letter last month to replace Wall. And Bush told
reporters earlier this month he ``is not closing the door'' to that
possibility.
   But at the White House on Wednesday, presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said no decision has been made.
   ``There's been no consideration of Mr. Wall's tenure,''
Fitzwater said. ``He's serving on the board and there's been no
change.''
   Wall said Sunday that he has no intention of resigning and a
spokesman for him reasserted that Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, his office issued press releases Wednesday quoting
new studies as saying that Wall's handling of 223 S&amp;L failures last
year saved the government $6 billlion to $8 billion.
   ``... While some of the 1988 deals are souring, enough of them
are holding together to make it worthwhile, so far, for Wall to
have stuck his neck out,'' said Veribank, a bank rating firm based
in Wakefield, Mass.
   Wall was chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board from July
1987 until last August, when its function as the federal regulator
of the savings and loan industry was transferred to the new office
he now heads in the Treasury Department.
   For nearly two months, he has been the chief target of hearings
by Gonzalez' committee into why the bank board allowed Lincoln to
remain open until last April even though examiners had recommended
in May 1987 closing the Irvine, Calif., thrift.
   ``Mr. Wall's behavior ..., in which he frequently appeared to
knuckle under to political pressure from members of Congress and
the thrift industry, shows he is not qualified to hold office in an
administration dedicated to high ethical standards. ...,'' the
three public interest groups said in their letter Wednesday to Bush.
   None of the groups was willing to say at a news conference that
the five senators who interceded on behalf of Lincoln in two April
1987 meetings with Wall's predecessor and Bank Board officials in
charge of the case should also step down.
   The Senate Ethics Committee is now investigating whether
DeConcini and the four other senators _ Alan Cranston, D-Calif.;
Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., John McCain, R-Ariz., and John
Glenn, D-Ohio _ violated conflict-of-interest rules.
   Together, the five senators accepted a total of $1.3 million in
contributions for their campaigns or other political causes raised
by Lincoln's owner, Phoenix millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr.
DeConcini and Riegle have since returned the money they received.
</TEXT>
