<FIRST>r f PM-FedVacancy     11-30 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed Vacancy,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Architect of Thrift Bailout Said To Be Pick for Fed Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush plans to choose David W.
Mullins Jr., a chief architect of the administration's bailout bill
for the savings and loan industry, to fill a vacancy on the Federal
Reserve Board, an administration source said.
   Bush plans to nominate Mullins, an assistant secretary of the
treasury, to fill a vacancy on the seven-member board expiring Jan.
31, 1996, said the source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged that Mullins
is the top candidate for the vacancy, adding, ``We have not made an
announcement at this point. It could come at any day, though.''
   Mullins, 43, a former Harvard Business School professor, is a
longtime associate of Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and
began serving in his current post in October 1988, shortly after
Brady became secretary.
   This year, Mullins attended lengthy congressional sessions to
write S&amp;L legislation, representing the administration in
behind-the-scenes deliberations.
   Earlier, he was the No. 2 staff person on a presidential task
force Brady headed that studied the October 1987 stock market crash.
   ``His association with Brady has been so close he's going to be
viewed as the Treasury's man on the board,'' said economist David
Wyss of DRI-McGraw Hill Inc., a Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm.
``Any time you get a strong administration type on the board, it
gives the administration a little stronger finger on the lever of
monetary policy.''
   In recent months, the Fed has been somewhat at odds with the
administration, which has favored lower interest rates than the Fed
and has pressed the central bank to be more aggressive in efforts
to improve the U.S. trade deficit by manipulating the value of the
dollar on world currency markets.
   Mullins would be Bush's first appointment to the board.
President Reagan named the other six members.
   However, economists warned that previous Fed appointees viewed
as administration representatives subsequently took an independent
line.
   ``Vice Chairman (Manuel) Johnson came over from the Treasury,
but he quickly became his own man,'' said economist David Jones of
Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a government securities dealer in New York.
   Mullins, if nominated and approved by the Senate, would succeed
H. Robert Heller, who resigned from the Fed in June to become
executive vice president of Visa International, the credit card
company.
   Mullins has little professional background in broad economic and
monetary policy-making but is highly regarded as an expert on U.S.
financial markets and the banking system.
   He received his undergraduate degree from Yale University and
graduate degrees from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He
grew up in Fayetteville, Ark., where his father was president of
the University of Arkansas.
   The Fed, as the nation's central bank, attempts to fight
inflation and sustain economic growth by manipulating interest
rates. It also regulates the banks that are members of its system
and governs the activities of bank holding companies.
</TEXT>
