<DOCNO> AP891130-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Shearson Bjt   11-30 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shearson, Bjt,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Restructures; AmEx Reportedly Seeking New Capital Infusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major restructuring announced by Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. comes as Wall Street's second-largest brokerage
confronts the fallout from an expansion strategy that was shaken by
a downturn in the securities industry.
   ``We are moving from a period of growth by acquisition to a
period of internal consolidation and selective expansion,''
Shearson Chairman Peter A. Cohen said Wednesday as the brokerage
announced major changes in its management structure.
   The restructuring, which had been expected, comes on the heels
of Shearson's announcement that it will lay off hundreds of workers
and make a drastic cut in stockbroker commissions.
   Shearson also reportedly is seeking an outside investor to
provide it with a capital infusion and reduce American Express
Co.'s 61 percent stake in Shearson.
   Under the management shuffle, Shearson is reassigning President
Jeffrey B. Lane to a lesser position and shifting another dozen top
executives. Shearson also established four core business groups and
disbanded its main policy making group.
   Pressure has increased on Shearson and other Wall Street firms
because of sagging profits in an overall industry slowdown since
the October 1987 stock market crash.
   ``American Express would like to see their ownership generating
higher profits,'' said analyst Perrin Long of Lipper Analytical
Services. ``But if the environment doesn't get better it's going to
be difficult for anyone in the industry to have better profits.''
   Shearson is dividing its businesses into four groups _ capital
markets, investment and merchant banking, private client and
subsidiary activities _ similar to realigmnents by other firms in
recent years.
   Lane will head the subsidiary activities group that will include
Shearson's money management businesses, which have more than $95
billion in assets under management, and its Boston Co. division.
   Robert S. Fuld Jr., who heads Shearson's taxable fixed-income
division, was seen as replacing Lane as Cohen's second-in-command,
although Fuld was not named as Shearson president.
   Fuld was named president of Shearson's capital markets group,
which will include the company's worldwide capital markets
activities. He also will oversee Shearson's administrative side.
   Sherman R. Lewis Jr. will head the investment and merchant
banking group and Hardwick Simmons will be president of the private
client group, Shearson's brokerage operations.
   Shearson is disbanding its chief policy-making committee, the
11-member policy group, but will create a business development
committee to ``help identify future directions for the firm.''
   Shearson's net income fell to $106 million in the first nine
months of this year, down 3 percent from $110 million in the same
period last year.
   The firm's woes stem partly from its January 1988 acquisition of
E.F. Hutton Group Inc. for close to $1 billion and its 1984 merger
with Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb Inc. The latter deal marked a major
expansion for Shearson from retail brokerage into investment
banking _ essentially arranging or providing financing for
corporate buyouts.
   Analysts said Lehman's old business generally has helped the
firm in the last two years, but Shearson's pre-tax profit margin
has not approached its pre-merger levels of 15 percent. For the
1989 third quarter, pre-tax profit margin was just over 1 percent,
compared with an industry average of about 4 percent.
   Additionally, analysts said, the Hutton buyout saddled Shearson
with debt and cost the firm more than $1 billion in writeoffs.
   ``Following the Lehman acquisition the significant increase in
the capital markets business really made them a force, particularly
in mergers and acquisitions,'' said Lawrence Eckenfelder, a
securities industry analyst for Prudential Bache Securities Inc. in
San Francisco.
   But, he said: ``The Hutton acquisition created problems because
the business didn't really pick up. It dissipated.''
   Because of the slowdown, Shearson this month said it would cut
broker commissions by 1 percent to 2 percent in 1990 and lay off up
to 800 employees by year's end. That would reduce the firm to
35,700 employees from a peak of 46,000.
   Also, American Express reportedly is considering selling a
portion of its Shearson stake to an outside investor to provide the
firm with more capital. A deal would have to be approved by
Shearson, American Express and Nippon Life Insurance Co. of Japan,
which owns 13 percent of Shearson.
   The capital infusion could help appease Moody's Investors
Service. The Wall Street credit rating agency last month said it
was considering lowering its rating on Shearson's long- and
short-term debt because of the firm's exposure to corporate buyout
debts and its softening business prospects.
   John Kriz, a Moody's assistant vice president, said Wednesday
the credit rating agency had not made a decision on Shearson.
</TEXT>
