<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FamilyBusiness     11-30 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Business,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Launches Magazine for Family-Owned Businesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of an automobile dealership may have
more in common than he realizes with the couple that runs a few
retail stores or the building contractor who owns operations spread
over several states.
   They are all involved in family-run businesses, and are the
targets of the publishers of a new magazine called Family Business.
   The premiere issue of the magazine was recently sent to a
charter susbcriber group numbering 100,000. The magazine will be
available monthly both at the newstand and by subscription starting
in January.
   In an interview Wednesday, Publisher Leonard Zweig estimated
there are 7 million family-owned businesses in the United States.
   But he said that despite the introduction of a number of
consumer-oriented business magazines over the past several years,
he found none that dealt exclusively with issues important to
owners of family businesses.
   Entrepreneur, for instance, contains information on how to get a
business started. But Zweig said information on how to pass a
business along to heirs may be more relevant for a family-run
business that has dealt with startup issues generations earlier.
   ``There has been a resurgence of interest in family
businesses,'' Zweig said. He said MBA students five years ago would
seldom admit it if they intended to go to work for their own
family's business, but today are forming clubs where issues
affecting such operations are discussed.
   The takeover wave has made family-run business a more appealing
career option, he said. ``Corporate life is not offering the secure
niche people thought it was,'' he said.
   Samir A. Husni, the University of Mississippi journalism
professor who publishes an annual guide to new magazines, said it
appears that Family Business has found a niche that has not been
filled by other magazines.
   ``It's a good idea but how well they execute the idea remains to
be seen,'' he said. He estimates only two of 10 new magazines
survive four years.
   Family Business is designed for the 1.5 million to 2 million
family-owned businesses with sales of $1 million to $100 million,
Zweig said.
   The cover story in the first issue deals with a company that is
called into to contain oil and toxic waste spills on waterways, and
describes how the father who owns the business is learning to trust
his children to run it.
   Another story discusses how healthy family companies base
salaries for family members on performance rather than sentiment.
   Regular features will include an advice column with tips on
raising capital, handling tax issues and settling disputes.
   Jack Nessel, a former editorial executive with New York and
Psychology Today magazines, is the editor-in-chief of Family
Business, which is being published from Great Barrington, Mass.
   Publishing consultant Robert S. Walker of Periodical Studies
Service Inc., said new magazines for small business are ``a hot
genre'' sustained partly by the need to advertise a proliferation
of new products these businesses may find useful, such as
computers, fax machines and cellular telephones.
   Advertisers in the first issue included investment and business
consulting companies, financial services concerns and office
equipment makers.
   There were 12 pages of ads in the first 72-page issue. Zweig
plans to have an editorial-to-advertising ratio of 60 percent to 40
percent.
   The magazine is owned by MLR Enterprises, a family-run business
based in Philadelphia that publishes the professional magazines
Mergers &amp; Acquisitions and Directors &amp; Boards and offers database
services.
   Zweig said MLR is investing several million dollars in launching
the magazine and expects that it will take four years for it to
become profitable. He declined to be specific on how much MLR was
prepared to lose.
   Subscriptions will cost $33.97 for a year and single copies will
be sold for $3.50 each at the newstand. Zweig said he would
eventually like to boost circulation to 250,000 to 300,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
