<DOCNO> AP891130-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OTC-ShortSellers     11-30 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OTC-Short Sellers,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Hears About Short-Selling Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After two days of testimony on the pros and
cons of short-selling by company heads, traders and exchange
officials, a House panel is slated to hear from federal regulators
next week.
   Market regulation and enforcement officials of the Securities
and Exchange Commission are scheduled to testify about the trading
strategy next Wednesday.
   When selling short, an investor tries to take advantage of an
anticipated drop in a company's stock price. The investor borrows
stock from a broker, hoping to replace it with stock purchased at a
lower price. The investor's profit comes from the difference
between the price of the borrowed stock and the lower price paid to
replace it.
   Profits from short-selling can be huge, but the risks are great.
If the stock's price doesn't go down, the investor will have to pay
a higher price to replace the borrowed stock.
   In opening three days of hearings on short-selling Tuesday, Rep.
Doug Barnard Jr., D-Ga., said the practice is legitimate and
accepted in the market, but the subcommittee was concerned about
``persistent reports of efforts by short-sellers to manipulate
stock prices downward through various techniques meant to be
harmful to the companies or their shareholders.''
   Barnard chairs the commerce, consumer and monetary affairs
subcommittee of the House Government Operations Committee.
   On Wednesday, the head of a nationwide association of companies
traded in the over-the-counter market told the panel that tougher
federal disclosure laws are needed to curb manipulative practices
in short-selling.
   John F. Guion, president of the National Association of OTC
Companies, told a House panel that a survey conducted by the
800-member organization points out the need for such curbs.
   Of the 183 companies responding to the survey, 22 percent said
they believed their company's stock had been the subject of
short-selling by professional short-sellers.
   Guion said the Securities and Exchange Commission should adopt a
rule requiring anyone who sells short a number of shares exceeding
5 percent of a company's outstanding stock notify the company, the
SEC and the market where the stock is traded within 10 days.
   In earlier testimony, other witnesses complained that
professional short-sellers often break the rules to get a stock to
drop quickly so they can take their profit and get out.
   Their alleged methods include spreading false rumors about a
company that it is about to declare bankruptcy or that it is under
SEC investigation.
   ``We find these companies are suffering from the standpoint of
survival,'' said Barnard, the subcommittee chairman.
   Guion said 83 percent of the companies surveyed believe
short-sellers should be required to report their short interest
positions when they exceed a specified amount of shares.
   But other witnesses were less enthusiastic about such a
requirement.
   ``It's difficult to say that additional information would not be
helpful,'' said John Pinto of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, a self-regulatory organization that oversees
the over-the-counter market. ``But I really don't think it would be
a significant regulatory tool.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891130-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Freeport-McMoRan     11-30 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freeport-McMoRan,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resources Company Cutting Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a decade of playing the field _ from
oilfields to goldfields _ Jim Bob Moffett is ready to settle down.
   Moffett, who assembled an unlikely combination of fertilizer
mills, oil and gas wells, sulfur mines, Indonesian copper pits and
Australian gold ore into the natural resources company
Freeport-McMoRan Inc., will sell up to $1.5 billion worth of assets.
   In an abrupt change in strategy, the company said Wednesday it
will prune away many of the operations it bought during the 1980s _
fully a third of the company _ and focus on phosphate fertilizers,
metals and oil and gas in the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``This is a case of selling peanuts to enjoy the watermelon,''
Moffett said, referring to seven operations ranging from the
Freeport-McMoRan Gold Co. subsidiary to the company's Canadian oil
and gas reserves.
   Moffett hopes to realize $1.2 to $1.5 billion. One unit already
has been sold and two were put on the block earlier this year.
   Of the proceeds, $900 million will be used to support huge
mineral discoveries made within the past 18 months.
   One is the largest known existing sulfur deposit in North
America, called Main Pass Block 299, situated under 200 feet of
water off the Louisiana coast. Freeport, which owns 58.3 percent of
the deposit, estimates it's worth $5.4 billion.
   The other is the Grasberg deposit on the remote Indonesian
island of Irian Jaya. Its 3.9 billion pounds of copper more than
double the copper reserves of subsidiary Freeport-McMoRan Copper Co.
   Mixed with the copper are 5.6 million ounces of gold _ more than
the twice the 2.5 million ounces of North American reserves the
company will unload by selling Freeport-McMoRan Gold Co. Because
the gold is mined along with copper and silver, its production
costs should be substantially less than those of the North American
mines.
   With $1.8 billion in debt already on its books and only $474
million in equity as of Sept. 30, it was time to decide which
assets were most expendable, Moffett said.
   ``We can't be everywhere any more,'' Moffett said. ``We have to
find niches where we have a leg up.''
   The company plans to use up to $600 million of the sale proceeds
to cut debt.
   The assets up for sale generated at least $345 million in
revenues in 1988, according to Freeport financial reports _ 18
percent of the company's total. But Moffett said earnings will
remain steady through 1992.
   The gap will be made up by a combination of the cash from the
asset sales, a $50 million cut in general and administrative costs
and lower operating and interest expenses.
   After 1992, Moffett said, revenues from Main Pass and Grasberg
will begin to gush into the company's coffers.
   Securities analysts agreed. ``We think it's a good move to
streamline operations,'' said Barbara Cranner of Howard, Weil,
Labouisse, Friedrichs. ``They had to do something about debt.''
   Low resource prices, plus high interest costs, depressed the
company's earnings performance this year. Earnings fell from $3.35
a share in the first nine months of 1988 to $1.75 in the same
period this year.
   Investors appeared only mildly impressed by the plan.
Freeport-McMoRan, which reached a high of $38 a share in april,
closed at $30.12{ Wednesday, up 50 cents. Freeport-McMoRan Resource
Partners, which owns the Main Pass sulfur deposit, closed at
$20.50, up 50 cents, while Freeport Copper, which is developing the
Grasberg strike, rose 12.5 cents to $20.87{.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
