<FIRST>r f BC-Poland-Currency     11-30 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Currency,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank to Issue 200,000 Zloty Note</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Bank said it will issue a
200,000 zloty note on Friday, marking the third time this year that
a new note has been created to keep pace with roaring inflation.
   The 200,000 zloty note will be worth $59 at the official
exchange rate, or $29 at the commercial exchange rate now legally
available to Poles.
   The bank said a 50,000 zloty note, which previously was to be
issued before the end of the year, also will be put into
circulation on Friday.
   When the bank issued 20,000 zloty notes nine months ago,
inflation was running at 60 percent annually. The 20,000 zloty was
$36 at the official exchange rate.
   The annual inflation rate is now estimated at about 700 percent,
and food prices have rocketed since price controls were lifted Aug.
1 in a ``marketization'' program introduced by the previous
communist government.
   The new 200,000 zloty note will have a panorama of Warsaw on one
side and an eagle, the national emblem, on the other, the bank
communique said.
   Poles use large notes to pay cash for high-priced items such as
cars, computers and televsion sets that can cost millions of zlotys.
</TEXT>
