<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-30 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Rise on Signs of Soviet Corn Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were broadly
higher this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade amid indications
that the Soviet Union purchased 2 million to 4 million metric tons
of U.S. corn overnight.
   The rumored buying, which was not confirmed, would be the first
significant grain export deal in several weeks. It sparked a brisk
rally in the grain markets, which have been in a downward trend due
to the slack foreign demand.
   The Soviet Union bought 8 million metric tons of U.S. corn in
October for shipment in November and December, and was expected to
buy more for January-March shipment.
   ``The question was when would they step in, and they stepped in
overnight,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s
operations on the Board of Trade floor.
   In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to 1\ cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.07 a
bushel; corn futures were 1} cents to 4 cents higher with December
at $2.38} a bushel; oats were } cent to 1{ cents higher with
December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to 5{ cents
higher with January at $5.84} a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mostly higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange while pork-belly futures extended their
sharp decline into a third day, reflecting disappointment over the
slow pace of the government's purchase of pork bellies for shipment
to Poland.
   Live cattle futures were unchanged to .05 cent higher with
December at 75.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower
to .30 cent higher with November at 83.90 cents a pound; live hogs
were .03 cent to .28 cent higher with December at 50.72 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to 1.50 cents lower with
February at 59.05 cents a pound.
   Frozen pork bellies settled sharply lower on Wednesday, leading
the livestock markets down.
</TEXT>
