<FIRST>r f BC-GerberPlant     11-30 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gerber Plant,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Food Maker To Close Canadian Plant By April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerber Products Co. said Thursday it will
close its Niagara Falls, Ontario, plant by April, terminating about
150 jobs.
   The world's largest baby food maker is consolidating production
in its three U.S. plants, in Fremont, Mich.; Fort Smith, Ark., and
Asheville, N.C., Gerber Chairman and Chief Executive Officer David
Johnson said.
   Except for two or three supervisory personnel who may be
transferred, employees at the Canadian plant will be dismissed,
Gerber spokesman Steven W. Poole said.
   Production is to be transferred to the Fremont plant, with some
product lines being moved immediately and some during the coming
months, Poole said.
   Dismissals are not expected to begin until early in 1990, he
said.
   Poole said employees will receive help in finding other jobs as
well as a severance package including two weeks' pay per year of
service, twice what Canadian law requires.
   Those costs will mean a charge of $4.5 million, or 12 cents a
share, against earnings for Gerber's third quarter ending Dec. 31,
the company said. That would cut third-quarter earnings projected
at 58 cents a share, or about $21.8 million, before the change, to
46 cents a share, or $17.3 million.
   Gerber reported earnings of $19.1 million, or 48 cents a share,
for its 1988 third quarter.
   For its fiscal year ended March 31, Gerber reported profits of
$81.4 million, or $4.13 a share, on sales of $1.07 billion.
   Gerber has about 70 percent of the U.S. baby food market and
about 25 percent of the Canadian market.
   It still will pursue Canadian sales, offering its full
U.S.-produced array of 184 products rather than just the 94
produced at the Niagara Falls plant, Poole said.
   He said studies that led to closing the Niagara Falls plant were
based on conditions prior to the U.S.-Canadian free trade agreement
adopted this year, and the plant would have been closed with or
without the agreement.
   In addition to baby food, Gerber markets infant and children's
wear under the Gerber, Buster Brown and Weather Tamer labels. The
company employs nearly 15,000 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
