<FIRST>r f BC-Ford-Canada     11-30 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ford-Canada,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford To Close Engine Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford of Canada said Thursday it will
close an engine plant at the end of 1990, eliminating 900 jobs.
   The announcement to halt engine and stamping production at
Engine Plant 2 in Windsor was expected since no product had been
allocated for the 67-year-old plant past the end of next year.
   The Canadian Auto Workers recently urged Ford to make a decision
on the plant's future to allow workers to look for other jobs.
   The plant also was shut down in 1981 during a slump in the
automotive industry, but it was temporarily reactived in 1983 to
meet increased demand for the five-liter V-8 engine.
   Ford has been telling workers for the last few years that there
is no production planned for the plant at the end of 1990, said Leo
Brown, manager of Ford's Windsor engine plants.
   The city has two other Ford engine plants, a casting plant and
an aluminum plant.
   The number of Ford cars using the five-liter engine has declined
and some have been replaced by the 3.8-litre engine, Brown said.
</TEXT>
