<FIRST>r f BC-Bass-KidnapPlot     11-30 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bass-Kidnap Plot,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Held in Alleged Plot To Kidnap Texas Billionaire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was held Thursday on racketeering
and extortion charges for an alleged plot to kidnap Texas
billionaire Robert Bass and hold him for $5 million ransom,
authorities said.
   Austin James Veleff, 57, of Germantown, Tenn., was arrested by
FBI agents Wednesday after he had driven to Texas with an
undercover agent he thought was going to help him.
   The arrest came after Veleff took pictures of City Place, a
33-story office complex built by the Bass family where Robert Bass
has his office.
   Carroll Andre, an assistant U.S. attorney in Memphis, Tenn.,
said Veleff had never met Bass and had no connection with him. He
had made Bass the target of a kidnapping after reading about him in
a business magazine, Andre said.
   Federal authorities had been aware of the alleged plot since
May. But Andre said Veleff told the undercover agent he had been
planning to abduct Bass for seven years.
   Dee Kelly, a lawyer for the Bass family, declined to comment.
   FBI agent William Fallin of Memphis, the agent in charge of the
investigation, said Veleff planned to ask for $5 million ransom
after taking Bass to south Texas.
   Veleff, an advertising salesman for the Memphis Commercial
Appeal newspaper for about 20 years, had operated a swimming pool
business for about eight years before becoming unemployed.
   If convicted, Veleff could face a maximum prison term of five
years and a fine of up to $250,000.
   Andre said that in addition to the $5 million ransom Veleff
talked about filming Bass ``in distressing situations'' and seeking
an additional $20 million after the initial ransom had been
delivered by plane to a mountain in Mexico.
   The alleged plot called for a pilot to be informed to drop the
money on a specified mountain about 45 miles south of border, Andre
said.
   Bass, 41, has a reported wealth of $1.44 billion, according to
Forbes magazine. His brothers, Sid Richardson Bass, 46; Lee
Marshall Bass, 33; and Edward Perry Bass, 44, also are reported
billionaires.
   The Bass family's business interests include oil, gas and
various investments.
</TEXT>
