<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-30 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed against the major
foreign currencies Thursday in thin European trading, dealers said.
   Gold prices declined.
   After little movement, the dollar fell sharply late in the day
on rumors that U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
was resigning because of his one-time consulting role with a
troubled savings and loan association.
   A denial by the Federal Reserve helped steady the dollar, but
dealers said a large order hitting the market at the same time as
the rumors added to the quick, sharp decline.
   There was brief dollar buying early in the day after the
assassination of Deutsche Bank Chairman Alfred Herrhausen, traders
said. They said the buying focused on the potentially destabilizing
effect a new wave of terrorism would have on Germany and its
economy.
   Dealers said the end of the month trading was very thin, giving
smaller orders greater impact on prices.
   ``No one wants to be adventurous on the last day of the month,''
said one London corporate dealer. ``The market won't be too lively
now,'' he said, predicting the markets would remain quiet until the
end of the year.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.45 yen from Wednesday's close of
143.35 yen to a closing 142.90 Japanese yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5700 from $1.5655 late
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.7800 West German mark, down from
1.7825; 1.5910 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 6.0725 French francs,
down from 6.0810; 2.0150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0100; 1,311.50
Italian lire, down from 1,315.50; 1.1632 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1658.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $410.60 a troy ounce,
down from $412.50 late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to a closing bid of $409.50, down from
$411.70 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.59 to close at a bid $405.76.
   Silver fell in London to a late bid price of $5.64 a troy ounce,
down from $5.65 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
