<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     11-30 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0287</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose in relatively slow afternoon
trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 12.37 points to
2,701.15 at 2 p.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator was up 6.40 points
at noon.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by about 7 to 6 on the NYSE,
with 730 issues up, 625 down and 556 unchanged.
   Retail and oil stocks were among the gainers, while some broader
indicators lagged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 103.15 million
shares.
   Analysts said many institutional players remained sidelined,
unwilling to make commitments before getting more clarification on
where the economy and interest rates are headed.
   The market firmed early behind a strengthening bond market.
Analysts said a drop in the Chicago-area Purchasing Management
Association index to 49.1 percent from 51.7 percent for November
suggested a further weakening of the economy and lent some support
to bond prices.
   ``It reaffirms a sluggish economy, which again raises
speculation the Fed will ease,'' said Hildegarde Zagorski, analyst
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A government report that showed consumer spending fell 0.2
percent in October also helped the bond market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.71 to 190.96.
   The American Stock Exchange market value index had slipped 0.24
to 373.40.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, USX was up ~ to 34{,
General Electric had advanced \ to 61} and L.A. Gear had gained ~
to 36~.
   BankAmerica, meanwhile, was off { to 27[, Bank of New England
was down 1\ to 12{ and Chevron was unchanged at 68].
