<FIRST>r f BC-TextronPresident     11-30 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Textron President,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textron Names New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. on Thursday named James F.
Hardymon, president of a St. Louis electrical products company, as
its president and chief operating officer.
   Hardymon, 55, will replace B.F. Dolan as president Jan. 1.
Dolan, 62, will remain as Textron's chairman and chief executive
officer.
   Dolan is expected to retire at age 65 and Hardymon would replace
him as chairman, the company said.
   Textron, based in Providence, is a conglomerate focused on
aerospace technology, commercial products and financial services.
   Textron reported third-quarter earnings of $59.5 million, or 66
cents per share, compared with 1988 results of $62.8 million, or 72
cents per share. Revenue increased about $17 million from year-ago
quarter to $1.7 billion.
   The drop of more than 5 percent in third-quarter earnings was
blamed mostly on higher costs in its aerospace businessses and soft
sales of auto products.
   Hardymon spent 28 years with Emerson Electric, and served as the
company's president since October 1988. Emerson, a global
manufacturer of electrical products and systems, reported fiscal
1989 sales of approximately $7.1 billion.
   Before becoming Emerson's president, Hardymon served as vice
president, chief operating officer and a director.
</TEXT>
