<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn and Soybean Futures Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid indications the
Soviet Union bought 2 million to 4 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Wheat futures ended mostly lower as some traders simultaneously
sold wheat and bought corn.
   The rumored Soviet buying, which was not confirmed, would
represent the first significant grain export deal in several weeks.
It sparked a brisk rally in the corn and soybean markets at the
opening bell.
   But prices closed below their opening levels, perhaps reflecting
an overriding bearish sentiment.
   Considering the size of the rumored Soviet purchase, ``the
market didn't act all that well,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   The Soviet Union bought 8 million metric tons of U.S. corn in
October for shipment in November and December, and was expected to
buy more for shipment in January through March.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 2\ cents lower to 2 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $4.07} a
bushel; corn futures were \ cent lower to 3{ cents higher with
December at $2.38\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1{ cents higher
with December at $1.42} a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to 4 cents
higher with January at $5.82} a bushel.
