<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-SovietTrade     11-30 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Trade,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Urge Bush to Push Trade With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-three congressmen urged President Bush
on Thursday to give priority in his talks with Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev to ending a rule that imposes high U.S. tariffs
on imports from the Soviet Union.
   Bush has power to waive the Jackson-Vanik amendment, a provision
in U.S. trade law that denies the Soviets the ``most favored
nation'' status because of limits on emigration. China, Hungary and
Poland already have the status.
   ``The Soviet government has come a long way in addressing the
concerns we have long expressed,'' the congressmen said in a letter
to Bush as he was leaving for the talks with Gorbachev in the
Mediterranean.
   ``Assuming you are assured of continued Soviet progress, it is
now time to recognize and reward Soviet progress with a waiver
under Jackson-Vanik,'' they said.
   At the end of August, the Soviet Union had allowed more than
96,000 of its citizens to leave, more than in any entire year for
the past two decades.
   The letter was signed six senators, including Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, and 27 House members. All are Democrats
except for six House members.
   Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., who last June introduced a resolution
supporting a waiver once Bush received assurances on free
emigration from Moscow. The Supreme Soviet is expected to complete
action in January on a bill to free emigration.
   The lower tariffs would only take effect after Soviet and U.S.
officials negotiate a trade accord. It was agreed earlier this
month to create working parties that would start work on the
agreement, but Valery Sorokin, economic counselor at the Soviet
Embassy, said on Thursday that they have not yet met.
   Formal negotiations are expected to start later and American
officials say they would take several months, after which Bush
would issue the waiver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
