<FIRST>r f AM-Occidental-NorthSea     11-30 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Occidental-North Sea,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Occidental Gets Approval To Redevelop Oil Field Where 167 Died</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. said Thursday it
has received British government approval to redevelop the Piper oil
field in the North Sea, where an explosion on a company platform
killed 167 men.
   The Piper Alpha platform off Scotland exploded in flames on July
6, 1988, and was destroyed.
   Occidental said the Piper field will be redeveloped with a
production platform designed to handle up to 140,000 barrels of oil
per day and accommodate up to 24 wells.
   Within the next few days, a 200-ton underwater drilling template
will be installed at the location of the new platform to allow up
to six wells to be pre-drilled, Occidental said.
   Occidental shut down all its North Sea production after the
explosion. It reopened production from the Scapa field last July,
and company chairman Armand Hammer said Occidental remained
committed to long-term production of North Sea oil.
   Hammer said in a statement that in addition to Piper, the
company plans to develop two satellite oil fields, Chanter and East
Piper, with combined reserves in excess of 100 million barrels of
oil.
   Occidental operates the Piper field with a 36.5 percent
interest. Partners are Texaco Britain Ltd. with 23.5 percent, LASMO
North Sea PLC with 20 percent and Union Texas Petroleum Ltd. with
20 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
