<SECOND>AM-Kodak Cuts,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Says Most Regular Employees Leaving Voluntarily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. on Thursday said more than 90
percent of the regular employees who are being cut by the end of
the year are leaving voluntarily with special benefits rather than
through layoffs.
   Kodak said it expected to trim 4,500 to 5,000 jobs by the end of
1989, up slightly from a previous estimate of 4,500.
   About 80 percent are regular employees. The rest are temporary
or supplemental employees who are being cut without special
incentives.
   The job cuts are apart from reductions in employment due to
divestitures of businesses. Kodak is cutting jobs as part of a plan
announced in August to generate up to $1 billion in operating cash
flow during 1990.
