<FIRST>u f PM-DetroitNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru f0096 11-30 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0096,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit News Stops Delivery in Michigan's Upper Peninsula</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts thruout to show that some Upper Peninsula readers still
can get News; Also moved on general news wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ESCANABA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Readers of The Detroit News in most of
Michigan are getting used to eating breakfast without the paper,
but some subscribers in the Upper Peninsula are upset they can't
see it daily.
   The News became an afternoon paper for most of Michigan on
Monday under a partial merger with its rival, the Detroit Free
Press.
   But in the Upper Peninsula west of tiny Naubinway, the News
ceased circulation because the papers can't be trucked there
quickly enough for significant street sales, said William Stille,
an assistant circulation manager for the merged Detroit Newspaper
Agency.
   Naubinway is about 500 miles from Detroit.
   Some patrons are angry about about the canceled service,
northern Michigan circulation manager Dale Powers said.
   ``...You really at times don't realize how important that
morning paper is to people,'' Powers said. ``Some people can't eat
breakfast without their paper. It's like a disease.''
   Upper Peninsula residents have other choices for morning
newspapers. The Milwaukee Sentinel and the Chicago Tribune
circulate editions there.
   The Detroit Free Press, also a morning paper, is available in
the area.
   Before the change, the News delivered to about 450 homes in the
Upper Peninsula as well as to some businesses, Powers said. The
area comprised about 1 percent to 2 percent of the News'
circulation, said Stille.
   Now the weekday News is put aboard trucks for outer Michigan at
8 a.m., arriving for distribution at Gaylord at 1 p.m. From there,
it is several more hours to newsstands in the Upper Peninsula,
Powers said.
   ``We're still delivering in Newberry, Sault Ste. Marie and St.
Ignace, but even those gentlemen are finishing their routes in the
dark,'' he said.
   Joint weekend editions produced with the Free Press will be
available in the Upper Peninsula.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
