<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EC-ThirdWorld     11-30 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EC-Third World,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Rejects EC Trade And Aid Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community's 66 partners
from Africa, the Caribbean and Pacific Ocean on Thursday rejected a
$13.5 billion trade and aid offer.
   The package, which the EC said was not negotiable, was ``very
much below the request'' of the Third World associates, Nigerian
Ambassador to the EC Joshua Iroha said.
   The Third World countries had asked for $17.5 billion.
   ``The ACP group expresses its deep concern and disappointment,''
Iroha said, adding that European Community aid had regularly
decreased in real terms since their first agreement was signed in
1975.
   The countries claimed the diminishing volume of aid granted over
the past 15 years could only be compensated by raising the funds to
$17.5 billion in the next agreement.
   Iroha said talks with the 12-member European trading bloc will
continue. He said if no solution is found, a plenary meeting of the
66 countries would be called to decide on further steps.
   The European Community nations agreed Monday on the new trade
and aid offer after a year of talks.
</TEXT>
