<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0204</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rallied in moderate trading today,
after new economic indicators raised investor hopes for lower
interest rates.
   Stocks opened on a firm tone behind a strengthening bond market
after new reports pointed to a slowdown in fourth-quarter economic
growth.
   The Commerce Department reported that consumer spending fell 0.2
percent in October despite a 0.9 percent rise in persona incomes.
   Another report by the Purchasing Management Association showed a
decline in a Chicago-area economic index for November to 49.1
percent from 51.7 percent. Analysts said that set the tone for the
purchasing agents' nationwide survey due out on Friday.
   ``It would indicate a further softening of the economy and
probable cause of the Fed to loosen interest rates,'' said Charles
Jensen, chief technical analyst for MKI Securities Corp.
   Lower interest rates would stimulate economic growth, including
corporate earnings.
   However, while blue chip issues were relatively strong, the
secondary market continued to languish, traders said.
   Bank stocks remained under pressure amid interest rate worries
and concern about leveraged buyout loans. New federal regulations
require banks to report loans for buyouts, acquisitions and
recapitalizations.
