<FILEID>AP-NR-11-30-89 1712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-30 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Futures Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rallied Thursday paced by
strong demand for wholesale home heating oil.
   Analysts said heavy buying in London's heating oil market
spilled over into U.S. trading pits. The onset of colder
temperatures throughout much of the United States also has boosted
demand.
   The contract for December delivery of No.2 heating oil surged
2.10 cents to 62.71 cents a gallon after rising 0.30 cent on
Wednesday. It was the last trading day for the December contract
and some of the buying may have been tied to the expiration.
   The January contract, which becomes the nearest-month contract
on Friday, gained 1.77 cents to 61.81 cents a gallon. The February
and March contracts ended with slightly smaller increases.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the New York
Merc, wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery finished
0.57 cent higher at 50.29 cents a gallon, adding to Wednesday's
increase of 0.19 cent. The January contract, which will replace the
expired December contract on Friday, pushed ahead 0.71 cent to
51.35. Contracts for later delivery posted larger gains.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, added 49 cents to close at $19.89 per
42-gallon barrel. The contract had gone up 15 cents on Wednesday.
Contracts for delivery in February through April finished with
slighter greater gains.
   Richard Redoglia of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.'s energy trading
division said: ``The strength of this market stemmed from the
London gas-oil market.''
   He said the demand in London exceeded normal seasonal increases
and carried the gas-oil contract _ the London equivalent of U.S.
heating oil _ past psychologically significant levels.
   A belief that winter weather has finally arrived to stay after
an abnormally mild autumn also has lifted heating oil futures
lately, he said.
   Energy traders continued to mull the implications of an OPEC
agreement reached earlier this week at the cartel's winter
conference. The feeling remained oil prices could be weighed down
by the pact raising the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries' self-imposed daily production limit.
   Ministers from the cartel's 13 members agreed to raise their
output ceiling to 22 million barrels for the first half of next
year from the current 20.5 million barrels.
</TEXT>
