<FIRST>u f AM-USX 1stLd-Writethru f0229 11-30 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0229,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn Move On USX Doesn't Clear Up Murky Speculation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs, `Corry said... to CORRECT day to Wednesday
sted Thursday; PICKS UP 14th graf, `He said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Icahn's latest move on USX Corp. sent the
company's stock climbing Thursday, but analysts say the takeover
strategist's plans regarding the energy and steel giant are no
clearer than they were before.
   Icahn, who owns Trans World Airlines Inc., has indicated several
times in recent years that he might acquire a substantial stake in
USX. But he has made an actual public buyout offer only once _ and
that was dropped following rejection by the USX board.
   ``I'm not sure whether this is a mountain or a molehill,'' said
John Jacobson, vice president of steel consulting for AUS
Consultants in Philadelphia.
   Jacobson said Icahn's disclosure Wednesday that he was
requesting federal approval to acquire at least 25 percent of
Pittsburgh-based corporation was ``just something he had to do to
keep his options open.''
   Gregory Drahuschak, an analyst with Butcher &amp; Singer in
Pittsburgh, said he has ``serious doubts'' Icahn would try to take
over USX.
   ``There's no way you'll make me believe he wants to run the
company,'' Drahuschak said. ``It's the capital commitment that
would be required. ... We're talking serious money.''
   Based on its roughly 257.5 million outstanding common shares,
USX has a market value of some $8.8 billion.
   USX stock rose 75 cents to $34.37{ Thursday in active New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   Icahn's latest filing could be an attempt to prod USX Chairman
Charles Corry to speed up restructuring or sell major assets,
analysts said. Icahn long has advocated a spinoff of USX's steel
division, formerly known as United States Steel, as a way to boost
shareholder values.
   ``Is he waving a paper tiger before USX again? Is he asking for
a divestiture of its oil and gas properties? We don't know,'' said
George Zimmermann, director of research at Gruntal &amp; Co. in New
York.
   Icahn is seeking antitrust clearance from the Federal Trade
Commission to increase his USX stake. According to a filing
Wednesday with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Icahn owned
nearly 34 million, or 13.26 percent, of USX's outstanding common
shares.
   A USX spokesman declined comment Thursday except to say Icahn
made similar requests in late 1987 and late 1988 but never boosted
his stake to the amount requested in the allotted year.
   Corry said Wednesday that he had a long telephone conversation
with Icahn last Friday and Icahn gave no indication what he planned
to do with the stock.
   ``He said once again that he thought the company's stock would
perform better if we didn't have holdings in steel and oil. He
wants one or the other,'' Corry told reporters following a speech.
   Icahn was in meetings Thursday, his secretary said. He did not
immediately return a phone call to his New York office seeking
comment.
   Icahn made a $7.19 billion, or $31 a share, offer for USX in
early 1987 but dropped the proposal after the USX board rejected
it. When he made his bid, there was speculation he only wanted to
drive up the stock price and profit from it, but he did not sell
his shares when he abandoned the offer.
   ``I think one of the reasons Icahn bought into the business is
he felt the breakup value of the pieces are greater than the value
of the whole,'' Jacobson said. ``I think that's why USX continues
to be a speculative stock candidate.''
   Zimmermann and Charles A. Bradford, senior analyst for Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets in New York, value USX stock at less than $30
a share.
   But Jacobson said the stock might be worth nearly $50 a share if
assets are sold and proceeds go to shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
