<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-30 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in light trading
Thursday amid more signs of a slowing economy. Gold prices were
mixed.
   The dollar fell in response to a Commerce Department report that
personal income rose 0.9 percent in October and rumors that
purchasing executives in Chicago believed the economy was
weakening, said Marc Chandler, a currency market analyst with MMS
International in Chicago.
   Both developments ``didn't contradict the idea that the U.S.
economy continued to slow down,'' Chandler said.
   When the economy slows, financial markets expect the Federal
Reserve to nudge interest rates lower. Declining rates make the
dollar less attractive, and the U.S. currency tends to fall when
yields decline.
   The dollar also slipped as traders who had taken profits against
the West German mark in recent days began to rebuild their
positions, Chandler said.
   The dollar fell to 1.7815 marks in New York from 1.7875 late
Wednesday after dropping earlier in Frankfurt to 1.7800 marks from
late Wednesday's 1.7825.
   Volume was light as many traders awaited two economic figures to
be released Friday, the government's Index of Leading Indicators
and the National Association of Purchasing Management's monthly
assessment of the economy.
   ``Right now, dollar sentiment is so poor, we really need some
strong fundamental data in order for it to rally,'' Chandler said.
   Overseas dealers said the dollar fell sharply late in the day on
rumors that Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan was resigning because of
his one-time consulting role with the troubled Lincoln Savings and
Loan Association.
   Joe Coyne, a Fed spokesman, said the rumors were ``absolutely
not true,'' and the denial helped steady the dollar somewhat.
   There was brief dollar buying early in the day after the
assassination of Deutsche Bank Chairman Alfred Herrhausen, the
overseas traders said. They said the buying focused on the
potentially destabilizing effect a new wave of terrorism would have
on West Germany and its economy.
   Late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Wednesday's
quotes, included: 1.5930 Swiss francs, up from 1.5920; 6.0840
French francs, down from 6.0935; 1,312.25 Italian lire, down from
1,318.75; and 1.16405 Canadian dollars, down from 1.16525.
   The dollar lost ground against the British pound. In New York,
sterling rose to $1.5700 from late Wednesday's $1.5678, and in
London, the pound rose to $1.5700 from $1.5655.
   The dollar also fell against the Japanese yen, declining to
142.80 yen in New York from 142.825 late Wednesday. In Tokyo, the
dollar fell to 142.90 yen from 143.35 yen, and it was unchanged in
London at 143.15 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.5910 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895;
6.0725 French francs, down from 6.0810; 2.0150 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.0100; 1,311.50 Italian lire, down from 1,315.50; 1.1632
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1658.
   Gold prices rose in U.S. trading after falling overseas.
   In New York, a troy ounce of gold rose $2.10 to $411.60 on the
Commodity Exchange, and Republic National Bank quoted a late bid of
$410.65 for a troy ounce, up $2.95.
   Gold fell earlier in London to a late bid price of $410.60 a
troy ounce, down from $412.50 late Wednesday. In Zurich, the metal
fell to a closing bid of $409.50, down from $411.70 late Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $5.59 to close at a bid $405.76.
   Silver prices also were mixed. Silver rose 6.8 cents to $5.668 a
troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange after falling in London to a
late bid price of $5.64, down from $5.65 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
