<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-30 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Bellies Fall Limit for Third Straight Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pork belly futures prices plunged the permitted daily limit for
the third straight day Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
as traders disappointed by the low level of exports fled the
collapsing market.
   Livestock futures finished mixed on the Merc.
   On other commodity markets, gold futures rebounded after three
days of losses; energy futures rallied; and grains and soybeans
were mostly higher.
   Frozen pork belly futures settled .40 cent to the limit 2 cents
lower with the contract for delivery in February down 2 cents at
58.55 cents a pound.
   In livestock trading, live cattle futures settled .05 cent to
.25 cent lower with December at 74.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle
were .05 cent to .20 cent lower with January at 82.62 cents a
pound; live hogs were .13 cent to .33 cent higher with December at
50.85 cents a pound.
   The February pork belly contract has lost more 6 cents, or 9.6
percent of its value so far this week after rising sharply during
the past two months amid the excitement surrounding the political
changes occurring in Eastern Europe.
   The rally got its start with the Bush administration's pledge of
food aid to Poland _ a package that was to include up to 20 million
pounds of pork bellies, the part of the hog from which bacon is
made.
   Yugoslavia's purchase of 150,000 pounds of bellies in late
October helped the rally along, as did indications that the Soviet
Union was interested in buying U.S. bellies.
   ``All of a sudden it seemed like we were going to be sending
bellies all over the world,'' said Thomas Morgan, president of
Sterling Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill. ``But if you get
the price up high enough, everyone backs away.''
   The government has purchased a paltry 1.2 million pounds of
bellies so far and a Merc report on Tuesday showed bellies piling
up in commercial freezers at a rapid pace _ an indication of slack
demand for bacon.
   Analysts said the sell-off was inevitable after so strong a
rally. The market had recorded two consecutive days of limit gains
on Oct. 31 and Nov. 1.
   ``When something goes up the way this market did, it's going to
come down the same way,'' said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   Precious metals prices rebounded on New York's Commodity
Exchange, taking back some of the ground lost Wednesday.
   The gold market, which had fallen for the three previous
sessions, posted modest gains on buying by bargain hunters and
speculators whose interest was piqued by the weaker dollar and the
rise in oil prices.
   Gold futures settled $2.10 to $2.70 higher with December at
$411.60 a troy ounce; silver was 5.9 cents to 6.8 cents higher with
December at $5.668 a troy ounce.
   Surging demand for heating oil drove energy futures up sharply
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 21 cents to 52 cents
higher with January at $19.89 a barrel; heating oil was .65 cent to
2.10 cents higher with the December contract expiring at 62.71 a
gallon; unleaded gasoline was .57 cent to 1.10 cents higher with
the expiring December contract at 50.29 cents a gallon.
   Corn and soybean futures prices ended mostly higher on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid indications the Soviet Union bought 2
million to 4 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced sales of
1.4 million metric tons of corn and 150,000 metric tons of soybean
meal to the Soviets.
   Wheat futures settled 2 cents lower to 1} cents higher with
December at $4.07{ a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 3{
cents higher with December at $2.38\ a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 1{ cents higher with December at $1.42} a bushel; soybeans were
3 cents to 4{ cents higher with January at $5.82} a bushel.
</TEXT>
