<FIRST>r f AM-Anheuser-O'Doul's     11-30 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anheuser-O'Doul's,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anheuser-Busch Rolls Out New Non-Alcoholic Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anheuser-Busch Inc. said Thursday that it is
increasing the availability of its non-alcoholic beer just in time
for the holiday season.
   ``There are many situations where a non-alcohol malt beverage
might be preferred, such as during business lunches or while
participating in athletic events,'' said Bob Merz, group brand
director for O'Doul's Non-Alcoholic Brew.
   ``And with the holidays just around the corner, it might also be
preferred when consumers know they will be driving,'' he said.
   O'Doul's has been test-marketed since March in cities in
Missouri, Florida, Alabama and Georgia. It will be made available
in December in all or part of 12 other states and the District of
Columbia, the company said.
   Anheuser-Busch, the world's largest brewery, is one of several
breweries that have recently introduced non-alcoholic beers.
   Milwaukee-based Miller Brewing Co., for instance, announced
plans in October to offer its Sharp's non-alcoholic brew for sale
nationwide by Jan. 1.
   David Krishock, new products category director for Miller, said
growth in the non-alcoholic beer market prompted Miller to bring
Sharp's out nationwide without test marketing.
   Annual U.S. production of non-alcoholic beers is about a million
barrels a year, compared with the national beer market of more than
182 million barrels. But the non-alcoholic segment is growing at
the rate of 10 percent to 15 percent a year while the overall beer
market has been stable, analysts said.
   The introduction of non-alcoholic beers is seen as a response to
a growing anti-drinking sentiment as well as to offset sluggish
beer sales with a wider variety of products.
   ``It has been our marketing philosophy to present the beer
consumer with a broad range of alternatives in terms of beer tastes
and beer types,'' said Michael J. Roarty, executive vice president
and director of marketing for Anheuser-Busch.
   Anheuser-Busch, the brewing arm of Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc.,
said O'Doul's would be available beginning Dec. 4 in Los Angeles,
San Francisco, San Diego and Sacramento, Calif.; Philadelphia;
Minneapolis; Phoenix; Hartford, Conn.; Washington D.C.; and St.
Louis.
   O'Doul's, sold in six-packs of 12-ounce cans and long-neck
bottles, also will be rolled out statewide in Delaware,
Massachusetts, Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Oregon and
Washington.
   O'Doul's contains less than 0.5 percent alcohol by volume _
about the same amount found in soft drinks and fruit juices, the
company said.
</TEXT>
