<FIRST>r f AM-DuPont-Spain     11-30 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Du Pont-Spain,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Du Pont Investing in Industrial Site in Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Du Pont Co. said Thursday it plans
to spend at least $200 million to build a Spanish industrial plant
to manufacture space-age fibers and other products.
   Construction at a site in Asturias, Spain, is expected to begin
in mid-1990 for a plant to make aramid fiber, which is used in
aerospace and protective clothing, among other things.
   Du Pont spokesman Clint Archer said it was too early to say when
the plant would open or how many people it would employ.
   The company may invest more money later to enable the plant to
manufacture other fibers, polymer and chemical products, Archer
said.
   ``The markets for the products will be the big determining
factor'' in whether Du Pont expands the operation, he said.
   Asturias, located in northwest Spain, has a good transportation
network, a strong industrial base and a well-qualified labor force,
the company said.
   Du Pont, which has had operations in Spain since 1962, employs
20,000 people in 14 European countries.
</TEXT>
