<FIRST>r f AM-FarmPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0306 11-30 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0306,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Prices Up in November</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `_Potatoes averaged ...,' to ADD that price is
per hundred pounds. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products rose 1.4
percent in November over the month before, chiefly because of
increased prices for strawberries, milk, eggs and celery, the
Agriculture Department reported Thursday.
   The increases were partially offset by lower prices for hogs,
grapefruit, apples and lemons, the department said.
   The prices were 2.1 percent higher than last year at this time.
   That increase came from higher prices for milk, hogs, cattle and
eggs, partially offset by lower prices for soybeans, corn and
broilers over the year, said the report.
   Feed grain prices, except oats, increased slightly from October.
Wheat, rice and soybeans also showed small gains.
   Hog prices decreased from October, steers and heifers were up,
but prices for cows and calves were down.
   Looking just at crops, the increase in November was .8 percent
over the month before, but 5.1 percent below a year ago.
   Here's what happened:
   _Potatoes averaged $6.14 per hundred pounds, up 84 cents from
October.
   _Dry bean prices advanced $1.60 to $27.60 per hundred pounds.
   _Commercial vegetable prices were 1.4 percent higher due mainly
to the near doubling of celery prices caused by a late harvest and
celery shortage.
   _Onions, carrots and lettuce prices were lower than in October.
   _Oil bearing crop prices were 1.1 higher than in October, but 21
percent below a year ago. Soybeans were $5.62 per bushel, up 7
cents from October. Peanuts declined 1.2 cents to 25.5 cents per
pound. Cottonseed was at $111 a ton, an increase of $17 from
October.
   Livestock and poultry was up .6 percent from October and 7.9
percent above November a year ago.
   ``Compared with October, higher prices for milk, eggs, cattle
and turkeys more than offset lower prices for hogs, broilers and
calves,'' said the report.
   Here are the details:
   _Milk sold to plants and dealers averaged $15.20 per hundred
pounds in November, up 50 cents from the month before and $1.88
from the year before.
   _Turkey prices increased 2.4 cents per pound over October to
40.9 cents.
   _Broiler prices averaged 29.8 cents per pound down .8 cents from
October.
   _Market egg prices averaged 72.8 cents per dozen for November,
an increase of 8.6 cents from October.
   _Barrow and gilt prices decreased $2.30 per hundred pounds from
October to $45 while sows decreased $3.60 per hundred pounds.
   _Beef cattle prices in November averaged $69.40 per hundred
pounds up 70 cents from October, while calf prices decreased 80
cents to $87.30 per hundred pounds.
   _Calf prices decreased 80 cents to $87.30 per hundred pounds.
</TEXT>
